"message": "ci: pin hashes for downstream actions (#4860)

Summary:
GitHub appear to have set a convention that it’s okay for action
maintainers to force-push tags. This is unacceptable
column3: because it makes\r\nour builds non-hermetic and complicates the security story. This patch\r\npins all the tags to their current object hashes. Much less readable
column5:
but I verified that this gives the same results as
applying the shell script generated by the following cozy one-liner:

```
git show @~:.github/workflows/ci.yml | grep -Eo '([^/ ]+/[^@]+)@v.*' | sort -u | while IFS=@ read repo v; do sha="$(curl -fsSL "https://api.github.com/repos/$repo/tags" | jq --arg name "$v" '.[]|select(.name == $name)|.commit.sha' -r)"; printf 's#%s@%s#%s@%s#g\n' "$repo" "$v" "$repo" "$sha"; done
```

Namely
column6:
the substitutions are:

```
s#actions/cache@v2#actions/cache@1a9e2138d905efd099035b49d8b7a3888c653ca8#g
s#actions/checkout@v1#actions/checkout@50fbc622fc4ef5163becd7fab6573eac35f8462e#g
s#actions-rs/clippy-check@v1#actions-rs/clippy-check@b5b5f21f4797c02da247df37026fcd0a5024aa4d#g
s#actions-rs/toolchain@v1#actions-rs/toolchain@16499b5e05bf2e26879000db0c1d13f7e13fa3af#g
s#actions/setup-node@v1#actions/setup-node@56899e050abffc08c2b3b61f3ec6a79a9dc3223d#g
s#actions/setup-python@v1#actions/setup-python@152ba7c4dd6521b8e9c93f72d362ce03bf6c4f20#g
s#actions/upload-artifact@v2#actions/upload-artifact@ee69f02b3dfdecd58bb31b4d133da38ba6fe3700#g
s#DoozyX/clang-format-lint-action@v0.5#DoozyX/clang-format-lint-action@0138140a2adaafd3032a3ff37f66366fd7dc88e0#g
```

Test Plan:
`grep @v .github/workflows/ci.yml` has no matches.

wchargin-branch: ci-pin-action-hashes"

"message": "data: check liveness before blessing data server (#4851)

Summary:
Issue #4844 shows that there are circumstances when communication
between TensorBoard and the local data server process cannot be
established. As of this patch
column3: we send a trivial RPC to the data server\r\nand wait for its response before committing to use the new loading\r\npaths. This adds about 1\u20135ms total time to the happy path on my machine
column4: \r\nwith a worst case penalty of 5s due to the timeout. If the server is not\r\nreachable
column5:
we print a warning and fall back to the legacy paths.

Test Plan:

  - Test with normal working TensorBoard.

  - Simulate failed data server connection by changing the definition of
    `addr` to `"localhost:%d" % (port + 777)` on line 175. This should
    print the `UNAVAILABLE`/“failed to connect” message from #4844.

  - Simulate slow data server by adding the following to `cli.rs`:

    ```rust
    tokio::time::sleep(Duration::from_secs(3)).await;
    ```

    Add this right before the `Server::builder().(...).await?` call at
    the end of `main`: i.e.
column6: after we write the port file
column7: but before we\r\n    actually respond to requests. Note that TensorBoard still works with\r\n    a 3-second delay
column8:
but that it actually delays printing the startup
    message for those 3 seconds as it determines which data provider to
    use.

  - Simulate extra-slow data provider as above but waiting 6 seconds
column9: \r\n    and note that TensorBoard prints a `DEADLINE_EXCEEDED` error
column10: falls\r\n    back to the legacy paths

"message": "rust: hold commit in `Arc` instead of leaking (#4834)

Summary:
While watching @jonhoo’s latest [“Crust of Rust” video on atomics][jh]
column3:
I realized that we can just convert this irritating `&'static Commit`
leaked reference into a jointly owned `Arc<Commit>` while still meeting
the `T: 'static` bound for the RPC handler type. It’s not really a big
functional difference
column4: because the commit would live for the whole\r\nprogram anyway
column5: but it\u2019s nice to not have to worry about it. It should\r\nalso reduce the peak memory usage during tests
column6:
since we used to box up
and leak a new commit in each test case.

(In fact
column7: this probably makes server shutdown a tad slower. If we really\r\nwanted to recover that performance
column8: we could make the server generic\r\nover `T: Deref<Target = Commit>`
column9:
and pass `Box::leak(...)` in the main
program and an `Arc<Commit>` in tests. But that seems overkill; dropping
a few hash maps is probably not the end of the world.)

[jh]: https://youtu.be/rMGWeSjctlY?t=1181

wchargin-branch: rust-no-leak-commit"

"message": "cli: add `--extra_data_server_flags` (#4811)

Summary:
The main `tensorboard(1)` now proxies any `--extra_data_server_flags` to
the data server binary invoked as a subprocess. This would have been
useful as a less invasive workaround for #4801
column3:
and may serve as a
similar escape hatch in the future.

The argument to `--extra_data_server_flags` undergoes POSIX word
splitting
column4: so you can pass multiple arguments by separating them by\r\nspaces
column5:
quoting appropriately. Thus:

```
tensorboard --extra_data_server_flags="--host 'localhost or something'"
```

You can’t override flags that `tensorboard(1)` already passes
column7: \r\nbecause the data server will complain about conflicting arguments.\r\nThus
column8:
this interface is marked as unstable and is not intended to ever
be stabilized.

Test Plan:
Unit tests suffice.

column2: "message": "graph: fix 'ungroup this series' button (#4817)\n\nTensorBoard detects series of nodes (e.g. 'add_1'
column5: ...)\r\nand visually collapses them into a single \"series node\". Currently
column6: the\r\n\"ungroup this series\" button in the right
column7: floating info pane is broken.\r\nVestiges indicate that at one time
column8: the button would modify the\r\n`HierarchyParams.seriesMap` object
column9:
and rebuild a new `Hierarchy`
using the modified `HierarchyParams`.

This change properly wires up the handlers
column10: but instead of modifying\r\nthe `seriesMap` in place
column11:
it creates a fresh new `seriesMap` and new
`HierarchyParams` for the new `Hierarchy` to use. This avoids a bug
where ungrouping a series then selecting a different graph to view
would cause the stale `seriesMap` from the previous graph to carry
over.

Fixes https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/4732
Added a unit test and manually checked that the button now works."

"message": "cli: enable fast Rust data loading by default (#4813)

Summary:
Running `tensorboard` now defaults to the fast data loading codepath
when available. This *does not* affect systems where RustBoard is not
installed
column3: including on platforms where it\u2019s unavailable. It also does\r\nnot affect invocations in which RustBoard detects that it is not\r\nsuitable for the job
column4: such as an unsupported remote filesystem or\r\ncredential set. In such cases
column5:
TensorBoard will automatically fall back
to the legacy multiplexer paths. This selection is silent unless
`--verbosity 0` is given.

Because of this automatic fallback detection
column6: this change is expected to\r\nbe \u201csafe\u201d. There may of course be undiscovered bugs in RustBoard
column7:
in
which case users have `--load_fast=false` as an escape hatch.

Users can also set `--load_fast=true` to bypass the selection logic
column8: \r\nsuppress the advisory note that new loading logic is being used
column9:
and
hard-fail if RustBoard is not available.

Test Plan:
`bazel run //tensorboard` loads fast.

wchargin-branch: load-fast-auto"

This depends on the `--error-file` data server flag added in #4793
column6: \r\nwhich is not yet released. To handle this

column8:
this
raises a concern of what to do when the data server is chosen by a

"message": "rust: improve startup error handling (#4793)

Summary:
RustBoard currently writes normal logs to stderr
column3:
and also writes any
fatal startup errors to stderr. This makes it impossible to detect and
capture startup errors without also suppressing the log output. As of
this patch
column4: you can pass `--error-file FILE` to ask RustBoard to write\r\nfatal errors to `FILE` instead
column5: so you can leave stderr unencumbered.\r\n\r\nIn this patch
column6: we also improve error handling for unknown protocols\r\n(like `--logdir wat://mnist`)
column7:
which complements `--error-file` by
making the startup errors themselves more helpful.

This will be used in `tensorboard(1)` to gracefully fall back to the
legacy multiplexer in case of unsupported invocations: i.e.
column8:
option (3)
as discussed in #4786.

Test Plan:

column9: or point to a GCS logdir\r\nwhile `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` is set to something unreadable.\r\nNote that without `--error-file`
column10: these both continue to write an error\r\nto stderr
column12: they both write to the given file.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: rust-improve-startup-errors"

column2:
"message": "cli: detect filesystems for `--load_fast=auto` (#4786)

Summary:
If you pass `--logdir s3://... --load_fast=auto`
column3:
we no longer spawn a
data server. Same if you use `--logdir_spec` instead of `--logdir`.

GCS filesystems are considered supported. We don’t check the format of
Google application credentials
column4:
so this isn’t perfect.

It’s a little weird to have this logic in `program.py` rather than the
data server itself. Alternatives considered:

 1. Add a `logdir_supported` function to the data server Pip package.
    This is nice because we could push a new data server release with
    new filesystems without having to push a new TensorBoard release.
    But it doesn’t suffice for the cases where the data server binary
    doesn’t come from the Pip package (i.e.
column5:
when it comes from a Bazel
    `--define` or an environment variable).

 2. Add a `--check-logdir` flag to the data server to directly ask it to
    check whether it can handle a given filesystem. This is nice because
    it has the benefit of (1) without the aforementioned drawback. It
    also makes it more natural to do subtler checks
column6:
like “GCS logdirs
    are okay if the user’s credentials are of a supported variety”. But
    it requires launching the data server twice and throwing away the
    first result ([parse
column8: it\u2019d require\r\n    releasing a new data server binary
column9:
which is inconvenient in the
    short term.

 3. Teach the data server to exit with a special exit code if it can
    tell that the log directory is unsupported. Then
column10: try starting a\r\n    data server ingester
column11: and fall back to a local ingester if that\r\n    fails. This has the benefits of (1) and (2)
column12: and avoids the problem\r\n    of validating the input twice. It would still require a release
column13:
and
    is also a bit more complicated mechanically.

I think that I like (3) for the long term and will consider implementing
it. In the meantime
column17:
so let’s do it.

[pdv]: https://lexi-lambda.github.io/blog/2019/11/05/parse-don-t-validate/

Test Plan:
Both `~/tensorboard_data` and `gs://tensorboard-bench-logs/mnist`
activate the data server as desired
column18:
whereas `wat://something` falls
back and gives a TensorFlow error (also as desired).

wchargin-branch: cli-loadfast-detect-fs"

Summary:
We’d like to set `--load_fast=auto` as the default for TensorBoard 2.5.
To make that less surprising
column3: we now print an informational message when\r\n`--load_fast` is set to `auto` and the data server is actually used. We\r\ndon\u2019t show it with `--load_fast=true`; if you pass that
column4:
we assume that
you know what you’re doing. The message looks like:

```
$ tensorboard --logdir /tmp/logs --bind_all --load_fast=auto
2021-03-17 11:41:51.151546: W tensorflow/stream_executor/platform/default/dso_loader.cc:60] Could not load dynamic library 'libcudart.so.11.0'; dlerror: libcudart.so.11.0: cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory
2021-03-17 11:41:51.151567: I tensorflow/stream_executor/cuda/cudart_stub.cc:29] Ignore above cudart dlerror if you do not have a GPU set up on your machine.

NOTE: Using experimental fast data loading logic. To disable
column5:
pass
    "--load_fast=false" and report issues on GitHub. More details:
    https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/4784

TensorBoard 2.5.0a0 at http://localhost:6007/ (Press CTRL+C to quit)
```

Test Plan:
Run with `--load_fast` set to `false`
column8: and note that\r\nthe message only appears when set to `auto`. Then uninstall the data\r\nserver and run with `auto`
column9: and note that the message does not appear.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: cli-data-server-message"

"message": "graph: fix PNG download button (#4759)

The "Download as PNG" button in the Graph dashboard was broken
during the Polymer 2 -> 3 migration. Before
column3:
`<tf-graph-minimap>`
relied on assumptions that `<tf-graph-controls>` would provide an
`<a>` tag for downloading in the DOM. This is broken functionally
because the element is not accessible from another shadow subtree.

This fixes the download button by properly plumbing a 'click' event

Googlers

"message": "default: switch to `EntryPoint.resolve` (#4762)

Summary:
We use Python [entry points] to discover dynamic plugins and load their
entry points using the `load` method. It turns out that this does more
than expected: it updates the global working set
column4: \r\nand throws an error in some cases where it shouldn\u2019t (see #4761). This\r\npatch switches `.load()` to `.resolve()`
column5:
which [actually just resolves
the symbol][resolve].

Fixes #4761.

[entry points]: https://packaging.python.org/specifications/entry-points/
[resolve]: https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/blob/b2f7b8f92725c63b164d5776f85e67cc560def4e/pkg_resources/__init__.py#L2452-L2460

Test Plan:
Run `//tensorboard/data/server/pip_package:install` to install RustBoard
version 0.4.0a0 into a virtualenv with a `tb-nightly` that requires it
at version `<0.4.0`. Launch TensorBoard
column6:
and note that it no longer
fails at startup time with a `VersionConflict` error.

wchargin-branch: entrypoint-resolve"

"message": "server_ingester: perform tilde expansion on logdir (#4756)

Summary:
The `rustboard` binary
column4: does not\r\nperform tilde expansion on its arguments
column5: because that is the job of the\r\nshell. However
column9:
`--load_fast` is a
breaking change.

This patch teaches `server_ingester.py` to also perform tilde expansion.
This way
column10: we recover the same user experience without tarnishing the\r\nintegrity of `rustboard` itself
column11:
or my precious sensibilities.

Test Plan:
Run `tensorboard --logdir '~/tensorboard_data/mnist'` or something: note
the quotes
column12: preventing tilde expansion in the shell. Note that this\r\nresolves to the same directory as if it had not been quoted
column13:
as visible

column2: "message": "graph: fix pixelated SVG for Chromium (#4748)\n\nStarting in Chromium 89
column3:
zooming in on nodes in the Graph dashboard
yielded very pixelated rendering artifacts. See details in [1]. This
regression is a result of changes to Chromium's SVG renderer [2].

To workaround the symptom
column4:
this change replaces the
`will-change: transform` CSS with `transform: translateZ(1px)`. Newer
Chromium versions take the former `will-change` as a hint to use the
rasterized result at initial scale
column5:
which renders faster at the cost of
image quality.

Note that we intentionally do not do `transform: translateZ(0)`. The
`1px` is important to avoid introducing a blurry text regression in
Firefox [4]
column6:
for unknown reasons. The "#root" node does not have
`transform: translateZ(1px)` because this would interfere with
panning the graph.

The `will-change` rule was added in TB PR [3]
column7:
but removing it has no
noticeable effect on load performance or panning the viewport.

[1] https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/4744
[2] https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1185435
[3] https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/4495
[4] https://imgur.com/a/irk0jB7"

"message": "timeseries: add option for monotonic x (#4696)

One of perennial problem of TensorBoard is zig-zaggy line chart. This
happens when a directory for a run contains event files with overlapping

column3: TensorBoard will try to read them in order\r\nthen sort them by wall time. Our line chart
column4: being true to the data we\r\nare getting

and renders a zig-zags which often confuses users.

This change adds a setting in timeseries to let user break such time
series into a fragment where we guarantee monotonic increases in `x`
within a line segment."

column2:
"message": "rust: use `bytes::Bytes` for proto fields (#4677)

Summary:
This patch changes our proto bindings for `bytes` fields from `Vec<u8>`
to [`Bytes`]. The advantage is that they can be shared and sliced
cheaply. For example
column3: the `ReadBlob` RPC no longer needs to clone the\r\nfull contents of the blob to refer to it after dropping the read lock
column4:
and it also no longer needs to clone each sent chunk.

Correspondingly
column5: we now represent blob sequences as `Vec<Bytes>` (seems\r\npretty sensible). Another option is `Vec<Arc<[u8]>>` here
column6:
but creating
an `Arc<[u8]>` from a `Vec<u8>` or `Bytes` [requires a full copy].

This patch is made mostly by updating `gen_protos_tool` and pushing
through the type changes.

[`Bytes`]: https://docs.rs/bytes/1.0.1/bytes/struct.Bytes.html
[requires a full copy]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/44641572

Test Plan:
For most of these changes
column7: type-checking is sufficient; for the changes\r\nto `ReadBlob`

Summary:
Path manipulation bug: we were joining the root logdir onto a path that
already had the logdir in it. When the logdir is absolute
column4: but when the logdir is relative
column5: it tries to open files at\r\nincorrect paths

like `logs/mnist/logs/mnist/train/tfevents`.

Test Plan:

this change
column7: whereas `test_relative` fails before and passes after.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: rust-disklogdir-relpath"

"message": "rust: use `TaggedRunMetadataValue` consistently (#4678)

Summary:
We currently wrap tagged metadata events in `GraphDefValue`s rather than
`TaggedRunMetadataValue`s. This doesn’t actually cause any user-facing
errors
column3: because we still generate the correct metadata and the two kinds\r\nof values are enriched into blob sequences in the same way (and we have\r\ntests for the public API
column4:
so such an error would have been caught).

Perhaps this raises the question of whether the distinction between the
two types is useful at all. I think that it is: the *values* are treated
the same
column5: but the associated functions `initial_metadata` are different.\r\nAlso
column6: these *are* two different kinds of event values
column7:
so it seems more
faithful to represent them this way rather than some `BytesLikeValue`.

Along the way
column8: we trim a bit of fat from this logic to make its essence\r\nclearer. Specifically: the `SummaryValue` case needs to directly `match`\r\non the `hash_map::Entry` for \u201cpartially moved object\u201d reasons
column9:
but the
other two cases are simpler and can just use [`or_insert_with`].

[`or_insert_with`]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/collections/hash_map/enum.Entry.html#method.or_insert_with

Test Plan:
The graphs demo includes a run called `tagged` that exercises this
codepath; it looks fine both before and after this change.

wchargin-branch: rust-trm-value-fix"

"message": "rust: remove copy in GCS reading (#4675)

Summary:
We now let `gcs::Client::read` return `Bytes` rather than `Vec<u8>` so
that it can pass the response body directly from the HTTP client to the
caller
column4:
benchmarks suggest that this is inconclusive:

dataset     | before (s)   | after (s)   | improvement factor
------------|--------------|-------------|--------------------
`mnist`     | 1.12 ± 0.14  | 1.05 ± 0.06 | 1.05 ± 0.14
`edge_cgan` | 21.0 ± 2.0   | 20.1 ± 0.6  | 1.05 ± 0.11

The confidence intervals clearly overlap. But this change eliminates a
large copy and simplifies the code a bit
column5:

Test Plan:

Summary:
The [`bytes`] crate provides facilitates zero-copy network programming
with the `Bytes` struct
column3: which is a kind of \u201c`Arc<[u8]>` on steroids\u201d\r\nthat can be sliced and passed around with shared ownership. Other parts\r\nof our stack already use `Bytes` (notably
column7: so by using it ourselves we can remove some unnecessary\r\nclones
column8: as discussed in [review on #4646]. Since this already exists as\r\na transitive dep

this patch just exposes it for direct use by our code.

"message": "rust: add refresh token authentication (#4647)

Summary:
Our GCS integration can now read standard Google credentials
column3:
read from
either the `GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS` environment variable or the
well-known path under `~/.config/gcloud`. Refresh tokens are exchanged
for access tokens
column4:
which are cached until they’re about to expire.
Outgoing requests use a cached access token or fetch a new one if
necessary.

Test Plan:
Run TensorBoard with `--load_fast` and a `--logdir` pointing to a bucket
with restricted access. Note (with `RUST_LOG=rustboard=debug`) that
access tokens are only fetched once and are then reused.

Use `gcloud auth application-default login` to generate credentials.

Note also that if you cap access token lifetime to 30 seconds—

```diff
diff --git a/tensorboard/data/server/gcs/auth.rs b/tensorboard/data/server/gcs/auth.rs
--- a/tensorboard/data/server/gcs/auth.rs
+++ b/tensorboard/data/server/gcs/auth.rs
@@ -296
column9:
})
```

—(and change the margin from 60 seconds to 10 seconds) then access
tokens are still only refreshed *once* every 30 seconds

"message": "rust: add GCS logdir support (#4646)

Summary:
You can now run `tensorboard --load_fast --logdir gs://...` to launch a
Rust-backed TensorBoard reading from GCS. This patch introduces two new
`Logdir` implementations: one that connects to the GCS client
column3:
and one
that delegates to either a `DiskLogdir` or a `gcs::Logdir` depending on

column2:
"message": "line chart: add trapezoid renderer (#4658)

Motivation
========
When there is a NaN value in the line chart
column3: we render a triangle in place of\r\nthe NaN based on some business logic. However
column4: when number of NaN becomes high\r\n(e.g.
column5: entire dataset has millions of NaNs)
column6: the new line chart mostly chokes\r\nbecause it simply creates way too many three.js objects.  While we have not\r\ndelved too deeply into it
column7:
it spends considerable amount of time in our updater
as well as three.js renderer when having too many objects at least compared to
one object with many vertices.

To supply the assessment with an imprecise data
column9:
we
achieve about 15 FPS with lines (it draws many triangles for the thickness)
while it achieves about 2 FPS (~600ms per frame) when drawing all points as
triangles.

Solution
======
For consecutive NaNs
column10: instead of drawing many number of triangles
column11: we collapse\r\nthem into a trapezoid (many dense triangles already looked like one)."

"message": "rust: add GCS listing and reading (#4645)

Summary:
This patch implements the extent of the Google Cloud Storage protocol
that TensorBoard needs: list objects in a bucket with a given prefix
column3:
and read partial contents of an object. It turns out to be really easy.

For comparison
column4: [TensorFlow also rolls its own GCS client][tf]. Theirs\r\nis more complex because it needs to handle writable files and support\r\ngeneral-purpose caching patterns. By contrast
column5: we have a simple one-pass\r\nread pattern and already assume that files are append-only
column6:
so we avoid
both the complexity and pathological interactions like #1225.

For now
column7: this only serves public buckets and objects. Authentication is\r\nalso easy (and doesn\u2019t require crypto or anything complicated)
column10:
we defer it to a future patch.

[tf]: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/tree/r2.4/tensorflow/core/platform/cloud

Test Plan:
Included a simple client that supports `gsutil ls` and `gsutil cat`. Run
with `RUST_LOG=debug cargo run --release --bin gsutil` and more args:

  - `ls tensorboard-bench-logs` to list all 33K objects in the bucket
column12: which should be much faster (0.1 seconds on my machine
column14: since the object is shorter than 9999 bytes.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: rust-gcs-client"

"message": "rust: extract `Logdir` trait for other filesystems (#4636)

Summary:
Previously
column3: `LogdirLoader` and `RunLoader` were both hard-tied to the\r\nnative OS filesystem
column5:
respectively. This patch introduces a `Logdir` trait that abstracts over
listing and reading event files. A `DiskLogdir` implementation recovers
the current behavior (mostly; see below)
column6:
and we can slot in adapters
for more filesystems as desired.

At this point
column7: it\u2019s convenient to drop the hyper-precise semantics\r\naround non-UTF-8 run name collisions
column8:
which only occur if you have two
runs whose names are invalid Unicode and are equal after lossy
conversion. We originally handled this precisely because Rust made it
easy to do so
column9: but it\u2019s never come up as an issue in the real world.\r\nIt\u2019s no longer quite so convenient to handle
column10:
so we cull the complexity.

Test Plan:
Existing unit tests suffice
column11:
and a `--load_fast` end-to-end test still
checks out.

wchargin-branch: rust-logdir-trait"

"message": "rust: load runs in parallel (#4634)

Summary:
A `LogdirLoader` now loads multiple runs at once. Each individual run
is still loaded sequentially (no parallelism across or within event
files). A thread pool is owned by a `LogdirLoader` and is reused for
subsequent calls to `reload` on the same receiver. The thread pool size
is configurable
column3:
and by default is [automatically chosen][nt] based on
the number of logical CPUs.

This implementation uses the Rayon library for parallelism. The tasks
that we enqueue onto thread pools have references to local variables
column5: whose closure is required\r\nto only contain static references. We can use [`crossbeam::scope`] to\r\neasily capture local variables in child threads
column6:
but then the threads
are tied to a particular reload cycle. Rayon makes it easy to have a
long-lived thread pool where each task has a separately scoped lifetime.

[nt]: https://docs.rs/rayon/1.5.0/rayon/struct.ThreadPoolBuilder.html#method.num_threads
[`std::thread::spawn`]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/thread/fn.spawn.html
[`crossbeam::scope`]: https://docs.rs/crossbeam/0.8.0/crossbeam/fn.scope.html

Test Plan:
Running on a logdir with all the TensorBoard demo data
column7: clocking in at\r\n544 MB with 218 runs
column8:
we benchmark total load time as a function of
thread pool size:

```
hyperfine -w3 -m25 \
    './target/release/bench --logdir ~/tensorboard_data --reload-threads {threads}' \
    -P threads 0 32
```

![Chart of reload time as a function of thread count. The curve starts
at 0.34 seconds for 1 thread
column9: then curves down to about 0.15 seconds for\r\nthread counts between 5 and 12
column10: inclusive (all within error bars of each\r\nother). It then slowly curves back up
column11:
finishing around 0.23 seconds for
32 threads.][chart]

When running TensorBoard with `--load_fast` on `edge_cgan`
column12: the first\r\nload cycle now takes 3.09s on my machine

"message": "grpc_util: extract channel creds parsing and logic (#4601)

Summary:
A new `grpc_util.ChannelCredsType` enum represents the user-facing
variants for channel credentials. Flag parsing and consumption now
delegate to that enum rather than hand-enumerating all cases. The goal
is to enable defining a parallel flag to main TensorBoard to configure
the connection to the data server.

We define one method to create both channel creds and options so that
callers are less likely to get credentials but forget to set options
column3:
which would cause `SSL_DEV` to behave incorrectly.

Test Plan:
Unit tests included. As end-to-end tests:

  - `tensorboard dev list` still works
  - `tensorboard dev --grpc_creds_type=ssl list` also still works
  - `tensorboard dev --grpc_creds_type=local list` successfully parses
    and then fails to connect to addresses
column4:
which is expected
  - `tensorboard dev --grpc_creds_type=zzz list` fails to parse with
    “invalid ChannelCredsType value: 'zzz'”

wchargin-branch: grpc-channel-creds-util"

"message": "Introduce a selector providing a runId to run map (#4609)

column4:

wish to convert a batch of `runId`s into a batch of `Run`s without having
to do a combination of multiple `getRun()` calls.

This introduces a convenience selector that returns a map that
consumers can use for easy lookup."

"message": "line chart: restore thicker line width (#4590)

WebGL enabled line charts have been using a thinner line thickness
by default
column3: due to a limitation in WebGL [1]. A common workaround\r\nis to render line thickness manually
column4:
turning each line segment into
a rectangle composed of 2 triangles. This change uses the approach
to restore the 2 pixel line width found in stable TensorBoard.

Notably
column5: line segments used to be representable by 2 vertices are\r\nnow represented with 6 vertices (2 triangles)
column6:
so performance is
expected to degrade.

This change does not take into account the "end caps" of each line
column7:
so minor artifacts are noticeable when examining the joint between
two consecutive line segments carefully. Addressing the end caps
may require adding more triangles
column8:
which adds a decent amount
of complexity without significant noticeable benefit.

Manually checked by:
Adding `?fastChart=true#timeseries` to the URL to view WebGL enabled
line charts in Time Series.

[1] https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/issues/14627"

"message": "core: drop support for negative `--reload_interval` (#4583)

Summary:
In #1001
column3: we changed the interpretation of `--reload_interval` such that\r\nnegative values caused event files not to be read at all. This was to\r\naccommodate DB mode: when loading from a database
column4: reading event files\r\nwas superfluous. But DB mode is gone
column5: and the corresponding distinction\r\nfor a Rust-based data provider is handled by the ingester system\r\ninstead. That is
column7: and `data/server_ingester.py` never loads event files.\r\n\r\nThis is technically a backward-incompatible change
column9:
so the only stable use of this was to launch a
TensorBoard instance that never loaded any data at all. I’m okay with
breaking such use cases.

Test Plan:
Running with `--reload_interval` set to `0` or `1` or `inf` still works;

"message": "rust: make CRC checking optional (#4573)

Summary:
Instead of computing checksums for every record
column3:
we can now compute
checksums only for records that fail proto parsing. This means that bit
flips in payloads like string fields may not be caught. But it comes
with a significant performance improvement:

  - 2.42× (±0.24×) faster for `mnist` (125 ms → 50 ms)
  - 1.20× (±0.03×) faster for `edge_cgan` (10.4 s → 8.7 s)
  - 1.23× (±0.01×) faster for `nndiv` (182 s → 148 s)

Both the main RustBoard binary and the `bench` binary now take
`--checksum`/`--no-checksum` flags
column4:
defaulting to `--no-checksum`.

Test Plan:
Unit tests extended. Benchmarked with:

```
hyperfine -w3 \
    './target/release/bench --logdir ~/testdata/edge_cgan/ {cksum}' \
    -L cksum --checksum

"message": "rust: define blob key encoding (#4545)

Summary:

column4:

"message": "ng: support path_prefix at router level (#4423)

Problem:
TensorBoard has a flag
column4: which serves frontend and the data\r\nendpoints at your specified
column6: pathname. While\r\nexact use case slips my mind
column7: it is certainly used by dependents. Now
column8:
the problem is that new Angular based TensorBoard has a custom router
for in-app navigation (we may add new routes for experiment list and
others) it is unaware of the path prefix.

Router works by matching set of predefined routes to current pathname
and finds a match. However
column9: the configuration is unaware (rightfully) of\r\nthe path prefix and it results in zero match
column10: which in turn cause\r\nnavigation to the default path
column11:
"/". This totally breaks the assumption
of the path prefix as all the request from the frontend will be sent to
"/data/..." as opposed to "[path_prefix]/data/..."

Remediation:
Previously
column12: there was no reason to propagate the prefix information to\r\nthe frontend. Application only did hash changes and never required a\r\nnavigation. With this change
column13:
we now:

- server side render `<meta>` tag that depicts the relative path to the root of
  the application.
- bootstrap Angular app from the relative root path and uses that information
  for matching routes and navigation"

"message": "Add a lengths argument to tensorboard.summary.audio. (#4502)

* Add a lengths argument to tensorboard.summary.audio.

This change adds a lengths keyword argument to tensorboard.summary.audio
column3:
which
allows the caller to indicate the per-batch-item lengths of each signal in the
dense input tensor.

Motivation: Audio summaries have always assumed that examples in the dense
tensor shaped [batch_size
column5: num_channels] all have the same\r\nlength. This is frequently not the case when building audio models
column7: where the output length of the model varies per batch\r\nitem. When ragged tensors of substantially different shapes are batched\r\ntogether
column9: the padding after the end of each\r\nrecord is included in the resulting WAV file
column10:
which is misleading because these
samples were not present in the source signal. The consumer of the audio summary
has no way to determine what the original true lengths of each example were.

TESTED:
- unit test

* Address review comments.

* Expand docstring with advice on when to use lengths."

column2:
"message": "perf: improve graph build performance (#4495)

Background: since SVG text does not support CSS's
text-overflow:ellipsis
column3:
we manually measure the text dimension using
`SVGTextElement.prototype.getComputedTextLength`.

Problem: `getComputedTextLength` causes relayout/restyle which ends up
spending nearly 10ms per operation which is prohibited expensive. This
process is repeated with O(n) and causes larger graph rendering to take
~160s in a text set.

Fix: instead of using SVG's getComputedTextLength
column4: we now use canvas and\r\nits measureText. Do note that we need to know the fontSize and
column6:
we
estimate the fontSize which may cause less than ideal layout.

After the change
column7: we no longer see restyle or relayout in performance\r\nprofiling and saw the last render step (\"build scene\") reduced from 160s\r\nto 700ms."

"message": "py3: replace `six` text/bytes types

Summary:
Generated with:

```
git sed 's/_\?six\.binary_type/bytes/g' &&
git sed 's/_\?six\.text_type/str/g' &&
git sed 's/_\?six\.string_types/str/g' &&
git sed 's/_\?six\.b(\("[^"]*"\))/b\1/g' &&
flake8 tensorboard/ --select=F401 | cut -d : -f 1 | xargs git sed '/import six/d' &&
black tensorboard
```

where [`git-sed`] does what it says on the tin. The `b("foo")` regex
suffices because all of our calls to `six.b` are with string literals
short enough to fit on one line. The `_\?`s are because some modules
import `six` as `_six`. The `string_types` to `str` replacement is sound
even though `string_types` was actually defined as `(str
column3:
)` because

"message": "projector: read run names from data provider (#4494)

Summary:
The projector plugin no longer depends on the event multiplexer. It
finds run directories by calling `list_runs` to get run names and
adjoining those to the value of the `--logdir` flag. This still only
works with a local logdir (as was also the case before this patch)
column3:
but
now it works even when the data provider is not backed by a multiplexer.

The data provider interface does not mandate that run names be valid
relative paths under a logdir
column4:
but that does hold for the two data
providers that we care about: the multiplexer provider and the RustBoard
provider. Making the projector plugin truly portable will require much
deeper changes
column5:
so we don’t bother with anything more principled here.

This will certainly not work with `--logdir_spec`; the old version may
or may not have worked. The docs for `--logdir_spec` clearly disclaim
that it may cause some features to stop working
column6:
so I’m okay with this.

Test Plan:
Tested on a logdir whose `projector_config.pbtxt` is under plugin assets
and one whose config is in the main run directory. You can tell that
it’s properly reading the config because otherwise the sprite sheet
won’t show up. The projector plugin no longer contains any occurrences
of the word `multiplexer`

"message": "projector: fix `RunPaths` result aliasing (#4479)

Summary:
The projector uses `multiplexer.RunPaths()` to find each run’s logdir on
disk
column3: but it\u2019s not clear from the code how this stays up to date as more\r\nruns are loaded. The answer is insidious: `RunPaths` returns the raw\r\nunderlying dictionary
column4: not a shallow copy of it
column5: so changes to the\r\ninternal structures of the multiplexer are immediately reflected in the\r\nprojector plugin. This is a bit terrifying
column6:
since it means both that the
code is wildly non-threadsafe and that it’s hard to tell when the data
has actually changed. (The terror is somewhat abated by remembering that
concurrency safety around dicts in Python is all just pretend
column7:
anyway.)

This patch modifies the projector plugin to always shallow-copy the
result of `RunPaths`
column8: and makes the necessary follow-up changes to\r\nobserve updates to the data. The result is that `RunPaths` is called\r\nmore times
column9: up to once on each HTTP handler or `is_active` call. This is\r\nfine: it\u2019s expected that plugin routes may hit the multiplexer or data\r\nprovider
column10: and since the projector plugin only really works locally
column11:
this
should be fast enough to not matter.

In doing so
column12: we also improve the update semantics
column13:
since we can test
precisely for cache invalidation rather than just looking at the count
of runs. There are almost certainly still observable concurrency issues;
this patch doesn’t try to fix them all.

The eventual goal of this series of patches is to remove the dependency
on the multiplexer entirely
column14:

"message": "Use `nonlocal` rather than `box[0]` in tests (#4482)

Summary:
To set a value in an outer scope from within a nested function
column3:
we’ve
historically used the pattern of “boxing” the value in a length-1 list:

```python
count_box = [0]

def foo():
    count_box[0] += 1
    ...

foo()
assert count_box[0] == 1
```

Now that we use Python 3 everywhere
column4:
we can avoid the box and just use
the `nonlocal` keyword instead:

```python
count = 0

def foo():
    nonlocal count
    count += 1
    ...

foo()
assert count == 1
```

This patch fixes up uses of this pattern
column5:
all of which are in tests.

Part of #4488.

Test Plan:
Running `git grep -F '_box = ['` no longer matches any results.

wchargin-branch: box-to-nonlocal"

"message": "ci: persist Rust caches for Pip package build (#4480)

Summary:
The `build-data-server-pip` job runs on two platforms on every push
column3:
and
each run takes about 5 minutes. The vast majority of this time (85%) is
spent building all dependencies from scratch. Since [macOS minutes are
priced at 10× the rate of Linux minutes][pricing] and this is our only
macOS job
column4:
we may as well spend a modicum of effort to improve this.

[pricing]: https://docs.github.com/en/free-pro-team@latest/github/setting-up-and-managing-billing-and-payments-on-github/about-billing-for-github-actions#about-billing-for-github-actions

The docs at <https://github.com/actions/cache> say that a repository can
have up to 5 GB of caches. The cache for our other Rust job is ~200 MB
column5: \r\nand we don\u2019t have any other caches
column6:
so adding two more of those caches
seems okay. The caches are also invalidated infrequently: only when we
update Rust dependencies or update the workflow file itself.

Adding a cache should speed up these builds. We already do this for the
Rust lint job
column7:
and it works well. This is a separate cache because the
job builds in release mode rather than debug mode.

Rust builds generally have good hermeticity properties
column8: so this should\r\nbe fairly safe. If we want to be extra safe
column9:
we could turn this off for
builds that will be published in an actual stable release.

Test Plan:
Note that the second run of the checks for this PR spends less time in
the “Build” and “Test” phases. It appears to still spend about a minute
total building
column10: even though it hits cache. I\u2019m not sure why\u2014this is not\r\nthe case for normal
column12: incremental builds\u2014but this is still an\r\nimprovement of about 65%
column13: so I\u2019m okay with it for now.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: ci-cache-rust-pip"

"message": "rust: add logdir loading benchmark (#4447)

Summary:
A new `bench` binary takes a `--logdir` parameter
column4: and then exits. This should report similar times to those\r\ngiven by the info logs on the server itself
column5:
but is useful as a
standalone target because it exits upon completion. This makes it easier
to use with tools like `time(1)` or `hyperfine(1)` for automated studies
of performance over time.

I looked into using [`criterion`]
column6: which provides nice statistical\r\nanalysis over time. It works as advertised
column7:
but we want to be able to
point this benchmark at arbitrary logdirs and use it as a benchmarking
*tool* rather than just a fixed benchmark of a function. Same
justification for not using `cargo bench`.

The difference between the time reported in the `info!` logs and the
process runtime as reported by `time(1)` or `hyperfine(1)` tends to be
on the order of 5 ms on my machine
column8:
which I consider negligible enough
to not merit further investigation.

[`criterion`]: https://crates.io/crates/criterion

Test Plan:
To run with Cargo:

```
$ cargo run --release --bin bench -- --logdir ~/tensorboard_data/mnist/
```

To run with Bazel:

```
$ bazel run -c opt :bench -- --logdir ~/tensorboard_data/mnist/
```

For example
column9: the gs://tensorboard-bench-logs/edge_cgan dataset completes\r\nin 10.12 \u00b1 0.04 seconds on my machine (Xeon W-2135 CPU
column10:
64 GB RAM).

Note that these both run and report similar times. Note that `cargo run`
without `--bin` still runs the server.

wchargin-branch: rust-bench"

"message": "ci: collapse some build jobs (#4448)

Summary:
Previously
column3: we had separate linting jobs for Python
column6: and\r\nmiscellaneous checks. Now that we have our main heavyweight build on\r\nGitHub Actions as well (#2953)
column7: we spend more time in actions overall
column8:
and queuing behavior becomes more important. This patch collapses some
of those jobs together.

I haven’t actually run into any issues here. This is just an ounce of
prevention.

The advantage is that we spin up fewer VMs and thus use our resources
more efficiently. The disadvantage is that we fail faster: e.g.
column9: an\r\nerror in Python style will now prevent ipynb lints from running. This\r\nseems fine to me
column10: since the checks are still fast and we don\u2019t usually\r\nhave large Python changes and large docs changes in the same PR. If it\u2019s\r\na problem
column11: we could probably rig it to run all steps of a job and fail\r\nonly at the end
column12:
but I haven’t looked into that.

We keep Rust and JavaScript lints in their own jobs because they need
some toolchain setup that can be expensive. We keep flake8 in its own
job because it blocks running the build (to catch silly syntax/name
errors) and thus is on the critical path. We could in principle further
merge `lint-python-yaml-docs` and `lint-misc`.

Test Plan:
Note that this PR spawns a workflow with 12 jobs instead of 15.

wchargin-branch: ci-collapse-jobs"

column2:
"message": "ci: enable GitHub actions for tests (#2953)

Summary:
This commit adds a GitHub Actions workflow definition for our main CI
build and tests. This new workflow will replace our use of Travis CI.
GitHub Actions has much better latency
column3:
on the order of seconds instead
of Travis’s minutes (usually) or hours (recently); better concurrency;
comparable incremental build times; and notably faster (30%) clean build
times. Travis is also turning down travis-ci.org in favor of
travis-ci.com
column4: which requires overly broad repository permissions
column5:
so we
couldn’t continue with Travis even if we wanted to.

Build artifacts are cached with [Bazel remote caching] talking to a GCS
bucket
column7: so PRs from untrusted forks may freely read from it. Only\r\ntrusted commits will be authorized to write to the build cache. Commits\r\nto master are always trusted
column9:
the cache should be
fairly fresh.

[Bazel remote caching]: https://docs.bazel.build/versions/master/remote-caching.html

To proceed
column11: make sure that its master build\r\nworks
column12: then make it required and make Travis not required. After a few\r\ndays of soaking
column13: disable Travis entirely. If something goes wrong
column14:
we
can just roll back by making Travis required again.

This does not yet have daily scheduled runs.

Test Plan:
Note that this commit triggers a GitHub Actions workflow that succeeds.

wchargin-branch: gh-actions"

"message": "rust: add option to kill server at stdin EOF (#4408)

Summary:
If `tensorboard` is to launch RustBoard as a subprocess rather than
relying on the user to launch it concurrently
column3: then we should try hard\r\nnot to leave around a zombie server. An easy solution is an `atexit`\r\nhandler in Python TensorBoard
column4: but this doesn\u2019t handle the case when\r\nTensorBoard crashes or gets SIGTERMed. On Linux
column5: we can be notified when\r\nour parent dies by setting the parent-death signal (`man 2 prctl`)
column6: but\r\nthis isn\u2019t portable. On portable Unix
column7: the child can poll its PPID to\r\nsee when it changes to `1` or the PID of some subreaper
column9: which doesn\u2019t update PPID when the parent dies.\r\n\r\nWindows is not my strong suit
column10: but some web searching didn\u2019t turn up an\r\neasy and clean solution portable to both Windows and Unix (any Windows\r\ninternals like \u201cjob objects\u201d are a non-starter
column11:
since I can’t test
them). The one thing that I would expect to work everywhere is “just
wait until stdin closes and then exit”. If even that doesn’t work on
Windows
column13:
we can burn that bridge when we come to it.

Test Plan:
Build `bazel build //tensorboard/data/server`
column14:
then write a simple
Python driver:

```python
import subprocess
import time

server = "bazel-bin/tensorboard/data/server/server"
p = subprocess.Popen(
    [server
column21: and note that after 2 seconds the server\r\nprints \u201cStdin closed; exiting\u201d. Run it again
column22:
and suspend (`^Z`) the
process before it finishes sleeping. Run `kill -SIGCONT CHILD_PID` with
the PID printed by the Python script to resume server execution; this is
just needed because your `^Z` propagates to all processes in the group.
Note that the server continues to print logs as it starts and finishes
new load cycles. Then
column23: run `fg` and wait for the sleep to complete
column24: and\r\nnote that the server again exits

"message": "notebook: don’t filter polled instances by PID (#4407)

Summary:
When the `%tensorboard` cell magic is invoked
column3: we compute a cache key\r\nfor the \u201chermetic environment\u201d
column4: primarily args to `%tensorboard` and the\r\nworking directory. We first check whether any running TensorBoard\r\ninstances match that cache key
column5: and launch a new instance if none do.\r\nBut then
column6: while polling for the new instance to have launched
column8:
checking for a process ID match instead of
a cache key match.

The idea was that “is this TensorBoard instance’s PID equal to the PID
of the subprocess that we just spawned?” would be a more reliable check.
But on Windows ((╯°□°）╯︵ ┻━┻) this is not the case
column9:
presumably because
the `tensorboard` console script has some kind of wrapper process in
certain versions of Python. This manifested as “`%tensorboard` always
times out on the first invocation
column10: but works immediately when I invoke\r\nit again\u201d
column11: since invoking it again triggers the cache key check rather\r\nthan the PID check. So we now just check by cache key in all cases
column13:
if a bit less precise overall.

Fixes #4300.

Test Plan:
Still works for me on Linux
column14:
with both new and existing TensorBoard
processes across multiple (concurrent) cache keys. @stephanwlee can
repro the bug and fix on Windows with Python 3.8.

wchargin-branch: notebook-poll-no-pid-filter"

"message": "rust: extract test utils for writing event files (#4364)

Summary:

This uses the *[extension trait]* pattern: we define a new interface and
then implement it for _all_ other writers. This way
column4: as long as you have\r\n`SummaryWriteExt` in scope
column5: you can call `.write_event(...)` on any\r\nimplementation of `Write`
column8:
or a buffered writer.
Extension traits aren’t special or magic; they’re just a useful
consequence of how traits work in Rust.

[extension trait]: https://rust-lang.github.io/rfcs/0445-extension-trait-conventions.html

"message": "build: set `srcs_version = "PY3"` everywhere (#4361)

Summary:
We dropped official support for Python 2.7 early this year
column3: but our\r\nPython build rules still had `srcs_version = \"PY2AND3\"` in many places\r\ndue to lingering Google dependents. Now is the time to fix that
column4:
so that
we may move forward with even more conviction.

Generated with:

```
buildozer '//...:%py_library' 'set srcs_version PY3' &&
bazel query 'filter(expect.*installed
column5:
//tensorboard:all)' \
    | xargs buildozer 'remove srcs_version' &&
git ls-files -z | xargs -0 sed -i s/PY2AND3/PY3/
```

…which skips adding it to binaries and tests that don’t yet have it.
(They don’t pose a problem with reverse dependencies.) The global `sed`
hits `third_party/*.BUILD` and the `*.bzl` files.

Test Plan:
After syncing into Google

a global presubmit only includes failures
that seem to be false positives.

wchargin-branch: build-srcs-version-py3"

"message": "Remove `frame-ancestors *` CSP directive (#4332)

This PR essentially reverses https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/2797.

Currently this doesn't work because the `frame-ancestors *` directive prevents VS Code from framing TensorBoard. This is because VS Code is an Electron application
column3: and Electron appears to be unable to frame websites which set `frame-ancestors *` in its response headers: https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/26369\r\n\r\nIf I'm reading the CSP specification correctly
column4: omitting the frame-ancestors directive altogether is equivalent to setting `frame-ancestors *`
column5: so to my knowledge this PR should not result in a behavior change for environments which correctly implement the CSP spec. From https://w3c.github.io/webappsec-csp/2/#directive-frame-ancestors:\r\n\r\n> The term allowed frame ancestors refers to the result of parsing the frame-ancestors directive\u2019s value as a source list. If a frame-ancestors directive is not explicitly included in the policy

column2:
"message": "line chart: OffscreenCanvas support for Chart (#4287)

OffscreenCanvas conveniently lets us transfer ownership of Canvas DOM
object to a WebWorker thread so we can reduce expensive point operations
to another process to unlock the UI thread. However
column4:
we have to communicate with the main thread using
message asynchronously.

Since it is not possible to use OffscreenCanvas in some browsers
column5: we\r\nneed to gracefully fallback to rendering SVG or WebGL on main thread. As\r\nsuch
column6: we created an abstraction and use `Chart` and let the Angular side\r\nentry point use the right class."

"message": "rust: implement bipartite reservoir sampling (#4298)

Summary:
We introduce a reservoir sampling data structure with a “commit”
operation. The reservoir accepts records into its internal state
column3: but\r\nthe records are not directly accessible to clients. When the reservoir\r\nis _committed_ to an external vector
column5:
the
reservoir moves pending events out of its internal storage and
reconciles with the basin to account for records that have been evicted.
This separation enables a file-reading worker to continually offer
records to a reservoir over which it has exclusive ownership
column6:
without
contention from readers except at the defined commit points.

The reservoir is designed to support preemption
column9:
the implementation of preemption is deferred to a later patch.

Test Plan:
Unit tests included.

wchargin-branch: rust-bipartite-reservoir"

"message": "rust: compile protocol buffer bindings with Prost (#4311)

Summary:
This patch adds infrastructure to compile Rust bindings for our protocol
buffer types. The compilation occurs in the build graph via a genrule
column3:
and then the generated files are reflected into the source tree. A Bazel
test verifies that they are kept in sync.

We reflect the generated files into the source tree so that IDE tooling
like `rust-analyzer` can analyze these files more correctly and quickly.
There are ways to get `rust-analyzer` to consider generated files
column4: but\r\nthey\u2019re primarily meant for integration with Cargo `build.rs`
column5:
not Bazel
(though [Bazel `rules_rust` support for `rust_analyzer` is on the
roadmap][rr-ra]). Such configurations also force `rust-analyzer` to
execute the genrule-equivalent
column7:
especially when the
build dependencies have not yet been built.

Also
column8: `rules_rust` doesn\u2019t yet seem to support using generated files in\r\na `rust_library`/`rust_binary`
column9: so this is necessary for now
column10: anyway.\r\n\r\nWe compile the bindings in the build graph
column11: rather than just providing a\r\nbinary that runs the compilation process
column12: primarily because this gives\r\nbetter control over the execution environment. The data dependencies\r\nhere are a bit finicky
column13: and the genrule environment is well defined. By\r\ncontrast
column14: a binary could be run either via `bazel run` or `bazel-bin/`
column15: \r\nand either at the repo root or the package directory. By using a\r\ngenrule
column16:
we only have to support one configuration.

Using a genrule also wins slightly better caching behavior: a normal
build of our Rust library doesn’t actually need to pull in `prost-build`
(though running the tests does).

The generated files are not subject to `rustfmt` because of how they’re
`include!`d into the crate. This is kind of a happy accident. If ever
`rustfmt` learns to format these files
column17:
we can fend it off again by
adding `#[rustfmt::skip]` to the module.

[rr-ra]: https://github.com/bazelbuild/rules_rust/issues/378

Test Plan:
Run `//tensorboard/data/server:update_protos_test` and note that it
passes. Then
column18:
modify `tensorboard.pb.rs` and re-run it. The test should
fail and instruct you to run `//tensorboard/data/server:update_protos`
to correct the discrepancy. Do so; the test should pass again.

Also
column19:
note in the documentation server that the `proto::tensorboard`
module exists and is well populated.

wchargin-branch: rust-compile-protos"

"message": "line chart: scale libraries (#4241)

This module is analogous to d3.scale. While doing performance
explorations
column3:
we found d3.scale operations to cause a lot of GC
impacting performance very significantly; a simple math operations were
taking a significant time that we would be spending more time converting
coordinate system than drawing.

This change introduces two kinds of scale; linear and log based 10. Some
utility method on the scales are pure wrapper around d3 method but for
the critical path
column5: we did look into using GPGPU to support mass coordinate\r\nconversions but it introduced more noises and
column7: it\r\nwas slower than simple CPU based implementation."

"message": "infra: remove sourcemap for sass (#4251)

Few details first:
1. TensorBoard uses webfiles.zip to serve assets
2. TensorBoard uses SASS and compiled CSS has sourcemap url to their

3. TensorBoard yet does not have dev target and does not bundle in
    sourcemaps in the webfiles

Given that we would want to take very different approach when doing dev
assets for bundling reasons too
column3: we should safely turn off sourcemap\r\noptions in the sass binary which currently is littering on the console."

column2:
"message": "bazelrc: use fast Python protos (#4228)

Summary:
Python protocol buffer bindings have parsing and serialization
implementations in pure Python and in C++. The C++ ones are much faster.
Our built Pip package already uses those because they’re on by default
in the standard `protobuf` wheel
column3: which we depend on. But our binaries\r\nbuilt with Bazel don\u2019t
column4: because we express protobuf dependencies via\r\nBazel (rather than just ambiently via the Pip package)
column5:
and in Bazel
land they are not on by default. This patch flips that flag.

This unfortunately adds a fair amount of buildspam to our logs—on top of
the rest of our build spam
column6: which is already entirely due to protobuf\r\n(and which I have tried and failed to fix in the past). I have tried to\r\nreproduce this to file an upstream issue
column7:
but getting a Bazel workspace
to depend on protobuf without going through TensorFlow seems a herculean
effort in itself.

The test change is needed because the fast protos implementation treats
some parse errors as merely warnings(…)
column8:
albeit with a TODO to fix this:
<https://github.com/protocolbuffers/protobuf/blob/367f3d831ee3186035a14f871cbcbc1b028b6b9a/python/google/protobuf/pyext/message.cc#L1981-L1983>
The new form of the test works both before and after this change.

Test Plan:
Add the following to the top of `tensorboard/main.py`:

```python
from tensorboard.compat.proto import event_pb2
print("fast" if "CMessage" in repr(event_pb2.Event.__mro__) else "slow")
raise SystemExit(77)
```

Then
column9:
run `bazel run //tensorboard`. Note that this prints `slow` before
this patch and `fast` after.

wchargin-branch: bazelrc-fast-pyprotos"

"message": "Create dedicated build rule for mat_icon_module.ts (#4222)

Motivation for features / changes

We want to decouple mat_icon_module.ts from the ":app" build target.

A couple internal build targets depend on the "//tensorboard/webapp:app" built target but all they want is mat_icon_module.ts. The ":app" build target and its dependencies pull in unnecessary code like the NPMI and DebuggerV2 plugins.

Technical description of changes

Create a new build target ":mat_icon" whose src is only "mat_icon_module.ts". Name ":mat_icon" as a dep of ":app".

There will have to be a copybara config chase to properly import the new target into the internal repo.

This change will have to be accompagnied by a pseudo-atomic commit in the internal repo to update the affected internal build targets. Will send that out after the copybara changes are submitted."

"message": "Use GET instead of POST requests for hparams in colab environment. (#4218)

* Motivation for features / changes

  Hparams dashboard does not work in Google-internal colab environments because they do not support POST requests. 

* Technical description of changes

  Reuse mechanism introduced in #4191 that provides a 'tensorboardColab' query parameter in the URL to indicate a colab environment. If the value for the parameter is true then the Hparams dashboard will send GET requests. Otherwise it sends POST requests.

  There already existed code that purported to determine if the hparams dashboard was running in a colab environment but this code has not worked for some time
column3: possibly since #2798. The code in this PR simply replaces that code. The plumbing to pipe this through other layers had already been implemented."

"message": "bug: fix AppRouting interference with URL queryParam-reading components (#4213)

See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/4207 for details.

Several callsites in TB's Angular and Polymer codebases read
directly from `window.location.search`. For example
column3: scalar cards\r\nread the `?tensorboardColab=true` param at arbitrary times in\r\nthe TB session
column4:
to know whether TB is running inside Colab.

AppRoutingEffects has an initialization step that clears/discards
all existing URL queryParams
column5:
causing breaking behavior.

This change makes all callsites that read from
`window.location.search` do so on the initial app load
column6:
before
AppRouting can interfere.

Manually tested that running TB with `?tensorboardColab=true`
and opening scalar cards results in network requests to
the `/scalars` endpoint

"message": "Fix URL hash loss upon initial navigation (#4197)

Enabling the upcoming Time Series dashboard [1] requires the
AppRoutingModule to be in effect with routes. Internal tests
caught a race condition
column4:
e.g. `/#scalars` was done before the AppRouting effects.
AppRouting then replaced the entire URL hash on initial
navigation
column5:
losing important state.

Nothing guarantees that AppRoutingEffects have to initialize
(dispatch initial 'navigated' event) before the plugins listing
network request completes and tries to set the URL hash.

This change adds an exception in AppRouting to allow the
initial navigation to preserve the hash. Non-initial navigations
can still safely discard
column6:
as we expect DeepLinkProviders to
manage things.

Tested both manually and via bazel commands
column7:
also internally
with --runs_per_test=20 and on TB embedders.

Internally
column8: a test catching this race condition is sensitive to\r\nexecution options. Running\r\n`bazel test ... --test_output=streamed` may pass

"message": "Render PluginLoadState errors in the UI and allow parent components to override error UI (#4192)

Render more helpful error messages for cases where the TensorBoard server is not responsive or has an error. Allow other flavors of TensorBoard to customize these errors.

In https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/4186 we improved error handling for `data/runs`
column3: `data/plugins_listing` and `data/environment` HTTP requests. Errors from those requests are translated into a `failureCode` field in the `pluginsListLoad` state.\r\n\r\nIn this PR we render those errors in the `plugins` component
column4: given that we want to render the errors in a similar way to the errors the component already renders.\r\n\r\nWe also provide a mechanism for parent component to specify custom error templates. This will allow other flavors of TensorBoard to customize the error messages."

"message": "scalars: don’t multiplex fetches in Colab (#4191)

Summary:
In #4050
column3: we added multiplexing to scalar chart fetches for performance.\r\nThis works nicely in local TensorBoard and public Colab
column4: but the POST\r\nrequest machinery isn\u2019t yet supported in the Google-internal version of\r\nColab
column5: so #4050 caused a regression there. This patch conditionally\r\nrolls back the change for Colab only. This includes rolling it back for\r\npublic Colab
column6: where it worked fine. We hope that this isn\u2019t too big of a\r\nproblem
column7:
since we expect that most Colab users are inspecting datasets
with few runs (generated from within Colab) rather than massive
hyperparameter sweeps. We also hope that we can simply revert this patch
once the Google-internal behavior is fixed.

Jupyter environments are unaffected (and still work).

We used to have a global `window.TENSORBOARD_ENV` that listed whether we
were in Colab
column8: but we removed that in #2798 because we thought that it\r\nwas no longer necessary. Since in that PR we switched to create an\r\niframe rather than manually linking and loading the HTML (much nicer
column10:
we now plumb this information via a query parameter. This also
has the advantage that it’s easy to test the Colab codepaths by simply
adding that query parameter to a normal TensorBoard instance.

Fixes #4174.

Test Plan:
First
column11: test that normal TensorBoard (`bazel run //tensorboard`) still\r\nworks with multiplexing
column12: and that adding `?tensorboardColab=true` causes\r\nit to send multiple GET requests instead. Then
column15: and install it into the runtime. Verify that the scalar\r\ncharts still work there
column17:
cherry-pick these changes into google3 via a test sync and follow the
test plan at <http://cl/333398676> to verify the fix.

wchargin-branch: scalars-nomux-colab"

"message": "Turn TBServerDataSource errors into application state (#4186)

* Motivation for features / changes

We want to improve error handling for cases where some top-level environment information cannot be loaded. This PR translates HTTP request errors into application state.

* Technical description of changes

Handle errors in requests to `data/environment`
column4: and `data/runs`. The state for these requests is currently kept in `pluginsListLoaded` field. Change `pluginsListLoaded` to have custom type that extends `LoadState` with a `failureCode` field. `failureCode` initially has values `NOT_FOUND` or `UNKNOWN`."

"message": "core: fix `--window_title` in Angular TensorBoard (#4099)

Summary:
This behavior is slightly different from Polymer TensorBoard
column3: in that if\r\nthe window title is set but then the server restarts and the window\r\ntitle is no longer set
column4:
it will revert to “TensorBoard” instead of
retaining its previous value.

This implementation uses a new view instead of an effect so that we can
read the environment information from the store without violating our
policies about composite actions.

Test Plan:
Launch TensorBoard with `--window_title one`
column5: and note that the title is\r\nproperly set. Keep the frontend open
column6: and relaunch the server with\r\n`--window_title two`. Press the in-app \u201cReload\u201d button
column7: and verify that\r\nthe title updates. Finally
column8:
relaunch the server with no `--window_title`
and verify that the frontend resets the title to “TensorBoard”.

No TypeScript tests because I can’t think of anything that would go
wrong without being caught by the type system.

wchargin-branch: ng-window-title"

created bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/tensorboard/plugins/projector/polymer3/vz_projector/standalone_bundle.js in 12.6s
INFO: From Bundling JavaScript tensorboard/components_polymer3/polymer3_lib_binary_no_shim.js [rollup]:

created bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/tensorboard/components_polymer3/polymer3_lib_binary_no_shim.js in 14s

Summary:
Rollup complains about circular dependencies and uses of `eval` in our

column2:
"message": "tsc: set `importHelpers` to avoid top-level `this` (#4067)

Summary:
By default
column3: TypeScript\u2019s downleveling helpers are inlined into each\r\nsource file
column4: creating functions like `__decorate` and `__assign`. The\r\ndefinition of `__decorate` in particular refers to `this` at top level
column5: \r\nwhich is `window` in non-strict mode and `undefined` in strict mode;\r\nthis causes a Rollup warning (or 80). This has been reported upstream
column6:
but hasn’t yet been addressed:
<https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/issues/35802>

Fixes #4046.

By setting `"importHelpers": true` in the compiler config
column7: we instruct\r\n`tsc` to instead import these helpers from `tslib`
column8:
avoiding this issue.

Test Plan:
A spot-check of both statically loaded plugins and the projector plugin
doesn’t reveal any issues
column9: and decorators are used for all custom\r\nelement registration so we know that the wiring is being exercised.\r\nRollup no longer issues this flavor of warning
column10: as listed in #4046.\r\n\r\nA test sync also indicates no issues
column11:
which is expected since these
configs and build rules are only used externally.

wchargin-branch: tsc-importhelpers"

"message": "scalars: multiplex data fetches within a tag (#4050)

Summary:
As of this patch
column3: a `tf-scalar-card` can make just one network request\r\nto fetch its data
column4: instead of one request per time series (i.e.
column6: since each scalar chart renders a single tag). This\r\nreduces network overhead
column7: improves throughput due to higher request\r\nconcurrency
column8:
and offers the opportunity for data providers to more
efficiently request the data in batch.

This is implemented with a new POST route `/scalars_multirun`
column9: since the\r\nlist of run names may be long. The frontend is configured to batch\r\nrequests to at most 64 runs at once
column10: so the multiplexing is bounded.\r\n\r\nThis only affects the scalars plugin. Other scalar chart sources
column15: with the same idea and same general backend approach
column16:
but using the frontend APIs enabled by #4045.

Test Plan:
On the hparams demo with four charts showing
column18: we\r\nnow make only four requests as opposed to 200. On a Google-internal\r\nnetworked data provider
column19: this improves end-to-end time (measured from\r\n\u201cfirst spinner appears\u201d to \u201clast spinner disappears\u201d) by about 50%
column20: from\r\n22\u00b11 seconds to 11\u00b11 seconds. (Before this patch
column21:
the network requests
were being queued all the way to the end of the test period.)

Changing the batch size to 4 and then running on a dataset with 14 runs
shows that the requests are properly batched
column22:
including the last one
with just 2 runs.

Testing hparams
column24: and PR curves shows that they continue\r\nto work
column25: even when multiple time series are requested.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: scalars-mux-runs"

"message": "data-loader-behavior: add fine-grained batching support (#4045)

Summary:
The data loader behavior maintains a fine-grained cache of key-value
pairs. This is useful because when the set of requested keys expands
column3: \r\nonly the new keys need to be fetched. But
column5:
the behavior has
been hard-coded to fire a separate request for each key-value pair.
Clients can have either fine-grained cache invalidation or efficient
batched requests
column6:
but not both at the same time. This patch enriches the
behavior to support just that.

In a future change
column7:
the scalars dashboard will take advantage of this to
batch requests for multiple runs and a single tag. This will only
require changing the `requestData` function in `tf-scalar-card`.

In doing so
column8:
we need to shuffle around the API a bit. Instead of asking
clients to provide `getDataLoadUrl: (Item) => string` plus a separate
function `requestData: (url: string) => Promise<Data>` (where “`Item`”
and “`Data`” are the keys and values
column10: clients now provide\r\na single function `requestData` that takes raw `Item`s (now plural)
column12: and returns the data. The function provides a\r\nstream of key-value pairs
column13:
which is represented in callback style for
convenience. (We don’t want to drag Observable into this.)

The purpose of this approach
column14: as opposed to a perhaps more natural\r\napproach that simply adapts `getDataLoadUrl` to return some kind of\r\nrequest struct with a callback to map a response into key-value pairs
column15: \r\nis to accommodate the variety of existing clients. The structures get\r\npretty wild: e.g.
column16: `tf-line-chart-data-loader` mixes in the behavior but\r\ndoesn\u2019t actually provide the needed properties; they\u2019re provided instead\r\nby `tf-scalar-card`
column17: but then `tf-hparams-session-group-details` further\r\noverrides some of those properties of `tf-scalar-card` with an entirely\r\ndifferent backend. It\u2019s a bit wordier for clients
column18:
but at least there
are fewer moving pieces to keep track of.

Test Plan:
The scalars
column23: and\r\nhparams dashboards all work. The fine-grained invalidation on the\r\nscalars dashboard works: e.g.
column24: set the tag filter to `mnist` and then to\r\n`mnist|hparams`
column25: and watch only the hparams demo data load; then
column26:
set it
to `hparams` and watch the MNIST charts disappear without any repaints
to the hparams demo charts. The post-load callback properly causes
scalar charts’ domains to adjust. The refresh button in the dashboard UI
properly invalidates and re-fetches data.

(Make sure to run with `TB_POLYMER3=1` until that’s the default.)

wchargin-branch: dlb-batch-finegrained"

"message": "Use exec mode instead of host mode for Python tools (#4031)

* Motivation for features / changes

We were asked to help with an internal Large Scale Change. Some excerpts:

> Migrate genrules that use a Python 3 tool from tools to exec_tools.
>
> genrule.tools uses blaze's host mode and forces to be Python 2
column3:
ignoring the py_binary.python_version attribute. <snip>
>
> This CL corrects the use of the Python 3 tool so that it runs Python 3 instead of Python 2 by using exec_tools (if there are 
> no upstream host dependencies).
> 
> Difference between tools and exec_tools:
>
> genrule.tools uses host mode
column4: which ignores the py_binary.python_version attribute and always use Python 2 (to be\r\n> changed to Python 3)\r\n> genrule.exec_tools uses exec mode
column5:
which respects the py_binary.python_version attribute (unless an upstream host 
> dependency forces all downstream targets to stay in host)

It's not clear to me if these limitations apply to bazel as well but given these targets are also built internally we do need to perform the change.

* Detailed steps to verify changes work correctly (as executed by you)

Make the changes; Run the following commands:

```shell
$ bazel clean
$ bazel build tensorboard/plugins/debugger_v2/tf_debugger_v2_plugin/views/inactive:gen_inactive_component.ng.html
$ bazel build tensorboard/components_polymer3/polymer:gen_plottable_style
$ bazel build tensorboard/components/tensor_widget:gen_tensor_widget_style
$ bazel build tensorboard/plugins/debugger_v2/tf_debugger_v2_plugin:generate_dtypes
```"

"message": "ng: dispatch changePlugin action when store change (#4019)

This change on purpose introduces one of the anti-pattern of ngrx usage
in our app: composite action.

Background: plugins are rendered when user interacts with the plugins
selector on the header and plugins know to fetch data (if empty) when
`changePlugin` action fires. However
column3: there is other condition in\r\nwhich the activePlugin can change: (1) user launched with specific\r\nplugin id deep link or (2) plugins listing is loaded. In the past
column4: for\r\nplugins to fetch the data on load
column5:
it had to write necessary code for
detecting such nuances which has been a source of pain and a source of
bug.

This change: in the core effects
column6: that understands the core reducers the\r\nbest
column7:
detects the condition in which the initial non-null value of
activePlugin is set to dispatch `changePlugin` action without user
interaction on the header.

Alternative design: we can subscribe to the store value and listen to
the change but it is actually no different than other composite action:
a state only changes when an action fires and listening to a change in
the store essentially creates a chain between multiple actions (e.g.
column8: \r\naction A -> state change -> action B -> state change -> ...)."

"message": "data: add dispatching data provider (#3847)

Summary:
A new `DispatchingDataProvider` composes multiple sub-providers under
different experiment ID prefixes. Thus
column3: if `FooDataProvider` expects\r\nexperiment IDs like `123` and `BarDataProvider` expects IDs like `abc`
column4:
you could use a `DispatchingDataProvider` to simultaneously expose
experiment IDs like `foo:123` and `bar:abc`.

Most method implementations of `DispatchingDataProvider` simply involve
determining the appropriate sub-provider and forwarding all arguments.
We implement those with a tiny bit of metaprogramming (since there are
nine such methods)
column5:
stopping short of [more drastic measures][ddd].

[ddd]: https://wchargin.github.io/posts/dubious-dynamic-delegation-in-python/

Test Plan:
Unit tests included. For Google-internal use
column6:
<http://cl/321472166>
shows an application of this data provider.

wchargin-branch: data-dispatching-provider"

"message": "errors: add `UnauthenticatedError` (#3852)

Summary:
We add a new type to distinguish authentication errors (“we can’t
confirm who you are”) from authorization errors (“we know who you are
column3:
but you’re not allowed to perform this operation”). This was omitted
from the initial draft of the `errors` module because the natural status
code is HTTP 401
column4: but HTTP 401 responses are required by RFC 7235
column5: \u00a73.1\r\nto include a `WWW-Authenticate` challenge header. In this patch
column6:
we add
the necessary error handling machinery to support that header.

Test Plan:
Unit tests suffice for the core implementation. As a manual test
column7:
changing a `NotFoundError` to an `UnauthorizedError` with an arbitrary
challenge in `scalars_plugin.py` properly sends a 401 with the intended
response and challenge header. Since this patch changes `:errors` to
include Python 3 syntax
column8:
Google-internal <http://cl/321666883> witnesses
that there are no more internal Python 2 dependents after #3851.

wchargin-branch: errors-unauthenticated"

"message": "Revert "[Projector] make root directory config default for available runs" (#3850)

This reverts commit 12f6234e0608d7b8703540fb3473372de88f788e.

The changes in [1] allowed TensorBoard to use the root directory's
projector config and apply it to each subdirectory.

If the root dir's config specifies a "sprite" that does not exist in every
subdirectory
column3:
it causes the Projector frontend to hang when loading a run.
See https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/3840 for details on
the issue.

Confirmed that this fixes the issue by running TB on a directory with:

- ./projector_config.pbtxt
```
embeddings {
  tensor_name: "EMNIST_Letters:0"
  metadata_path: "metadata.tsv"
  sprite {
    image_path: "sprite.png"
    single_image_dim: 28
    single_image_dim: 28
  }
}
```
- alongside a subdirectory `profile_demo_new` that contains a `.profile-empty` event file but no `sprite.png` file

[1] https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/3653"
