"message": "reland: preserve domains in line chart when changing settings (#3831)\n\nWhen clients of VzLineChart2 update the colorScale externally
column3:
the x/y axis
auto-scales to fit the domain. This may be unwanted behavior if clients want
to allow users to change a chart's color frequently without losing a carefully
crafted viewport domain.

This preserves the existing domains upon property changes that recreate
the chart
column4:
but do not affect the position of points.

Historical record:
- Introduced in https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/3813
- Reverted in https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/3828
  due to multiple regressions

1) Changing settings that affect position of chart points (e.g. xAxis type)
would not re-fit domain to data. Users may set xAxis to "Relative"
column5: and think\r\nthat the data was missing
column6:
when it was only outside of the viewport.

This is overcome by separating the preserve-domain logic into a separate
callback
column7:
which does not fire when properties affecting chart point positions
change.

2) Removing and re-attaching the same vz-line-chart element in DOM
could reset the domain to Plottable's default [0
column8: 1] range. The exact cause of\r\nthis is unclear
column9:
but the axis domain reset occurs within
`Plottable.Components.Table.prototype.destroy`.

This is overcome by deleting the `_chart` LineChart reference when a
VzLineChart2 is detached from DOM.

Manually tested that the regressions are addressed and updating colorScale still
preserves domain."

"message": "backend: add `RequestContext` (#3816)

Summary:
The `RequestContext` type stores request-specific information about
cross-cutting concerns. For instance
column3:
think:

  - authentication: an `AuthContext` for obtaining credentials
  - internationalization: the user’s home language
  - performance: a flag randomly set on 0.1% of requests to trigger more
    detailed profiling
  - deployment: a “debug”/“release” flag

A function call at any point in the stack can pull this information from
a `RequestContext` passed to it as an argument. A `RequestContext` is
first obtained in a request handler
column4:
where it can be extracted from the
WSGI environment.

As with the Go language’s `Context` type
column5: this context isn\u2019t just for\r\narbitrary values that we don\u2019t want to bother passing around
column6: like an\r\nexperiment ID or plugin name. Thus
column7: the context is closed to a fixed set\r\nof keys. For now
column8:
we include only an `AuthContext`.

The data provider API will soon be extended to require a context.

Test Plan:
Unit tests included.

wchargin-branch: request-context"

"message": "data: add `AuthProvider` and `AuthContext` (#3815)

Summary:
This patch adds two new types for integrating authentication into the
data provider API. The `AuthProvider` type defines an interface for
extracting a specific kind of credential (say
column3:
an OAuth token) from a
WSGI environment. The `AuthContext` type lets clients ask for a
credential from a specific type of `AuthProvider`.

As written
column4: `AuthContext` is not threadsafe. Making it truly threadsafe\r\nis tricky if we assume that the `AuthProvider`s\u2019 `authenticate` methods\r\ndo anything that Python code can
column5: including obtaining a reference to the\r\nvery same `AuthContext` and calling its `get` method with a different\r\nauth provider. (This would be a Bad Idea on the part of the caller
column6: but\r\ndeadlocking would still be unfortunate.) Since most requests are handled\r\nby a single thread
column8:
this shouldn’t be a problem.

Test Plan:
Basic unit tests added. Google-internal proof-of-concept code builds on
this work and shows that the `AuthProvider` interface suffices for now.

wchargin-branch: data-auth"

"message": "Depend on d3 via npm (#3792)

We would like to start using d3 in Angular and others. This change makes sure the
dependency added in Angular does not deviate from the Polymer one by using the
same files.

Gotchas:

- While d3 can be used as a UMD module
column3: we can also use them as regular esmodule.\r\n- d3 in Polymer is used in UMD style (accessing global variable; e.g.
column4:
d3.select)
  - we add the dependency by loading d3.min.js.
- d3 in Angular will be used via ESModule
  - import {select} from 'd3'; gets bundled by rollup
- Because of two module systems
column5: we will load multiple copies of d3 but the ESModule\r\n  one is in the closure and does not seem to collide with global d3. While this will\r\n  bloat the bundle size
column6: we hope that this is on temporary solution that will be addressed\r\n  when we bundle Polymer via rollup (after Polymer 3 migration)."

  * `np.float` and `np.floating` don't mean the same thing exactly.

column4:
etc.
  * `np.issubdtype()` used to allow the second arg to be `np.float` and it would
     interpret it as `np.floating`. But that deprecated behavior has been
     removed in the latest release of numpy (1.19.0).

    of the deprecated behavior of `np.issubdtype()`.
* Tested:

    1.19.0."

column2: "message": "Fix custom scalars full width mode (#3719)\n\nCause: due to the limitation of the tf-dom-repeat

container width).

Fix: tf-dom-repeat used to assign a slot attribute to the DOM we stamp.
However
column5: if the stamped DOM is \"dom-if\" or \"dom-repeat\"

"message": "[DebuggerV2] Remove flakiness in a Python unit test (#3713)

* Motivation for features / changes
  * Remove flakiness in `testRunInBackgroundRepeatedlyThreeTimes` for the method
    `debug_data_multiplexer.run_repeatedly_in_background()`
* Technical description of changes
  * The flakiness stems from the following fact: after the the `interrupt_event.set()` call
     the test checks the value of `state["counter"]` immediately. It doesn't wait for the
     background thread to stop (due to the deliberately-raised `StopIteration`)
column3:
hence the
     counter may not have had a chance to increment to 3 before the assertion happens. 
     Hence the failure (2 != 3)
  * This change lets `run_repeatedly_in_background()` return the background thread
column4:
so that the test can use its `join()` method to ensure that the assertion is made after
     the termination of the thread.
* Detailed steps to verify changes work correctly (as executed by you)
  * 500 runs with bazel all passed.
  * 2000 runs using internal test infra structure on equivalent change all passed."

"message": "Rollforward "Use tf-wbr-string in tf-node-info" (#3700)

This is a rollforward of 15f2f5588541526b6e268e4753c77d407f434f55 with fixes after a rollback in b5224c1a506bd518517beb158d9a09e00326af83.

Original commit description:

tf-node-info assigns some user-generated value to an element using innerHTML. It does this because it augments the user-generated value with some <wbr> tags. 

There is a nice tf-wbr-string component that can be used to insert <wbr> tags. Refactor to a common location and allow callers to specify a regex expression for delimiters for <wbr> insertion."

"message": "Support proxied URLs for TensorBoard running in IPython (#3674)

Users will frequently want to run TensorBoard in environments where they are not allowed to open up or expose additional ports. For those cases jupyter-server-proxy (and other proxy software) allows forwarding web traffic to other services running on the system without opening new ports. (The Google Colab integration also works around this same issue of not being able to directly expose the port that TensorBoard runs on.)

This PR allows users to optionally pass the TensorBoard traffic through a proxy by setting the TENSORBOARD_PROXY_URL environment variable. When this variable is not set TensorBoard will behave as normal.

This adds support for a new optional environment variable TENSORBOARD_PROXY_URL which if set will be used as the URL's path for the IFRAME displayed in the notebook when running %tensorboard."

wchargin-branch: program-include-dynamic-plugins"

"message": "Expand UploadLimits proto and use it in TensorBoardUploader (#3625)

Motivation for features / changes

There are a number of new parameters that impact the throughput of uploading data that we want the TensorBoard.dev frontend to return to the uploader in the handshake. Each of scalar
column4:
and blob now have a max_[scalars|tensor|blob]_request_size and min_[scalars|tensor|blob]_request_interval parameters.

Technical description of changes

Update the UploadLimits proto to include the new fields. Allow an instance of UploadLimits to be passed to TensorBoardUploader and use this throughout the code instead of the constants that have been used.

None of the clients for TensorBoardUploader are yet updated to pass UploadLimits (there is one in this git repo and there is one internal to Google) so temporarily have TensorBoardUploader construct its own UploadLimits if None is passed
column5: where values are all based on now-deprecated constants and arguments to the constructor. We hope to update clients in the next day or two so this is intended to be very temporary.\r\n\r\nTests have been updated to use UploadLimits as arguments exclusively."

"message": "vulc: fix pretty print messing up whitespace (#3604)

Our data location in the runs selector use tf-wbr-string which is
roughly written as `<template>[[prop]]<wbr></template>`. With the pretty
print
column3:
this was rewritten as
```
<template>
  [[prop]]
  <wbr>
</template>
```
which has whitespace and make the browser render the whitespace.

This change fixes the issue by turning off the pretty print."

"message": "ng: fix infinite loop when on plugin selector (#3563)

cause: mat-tab-group emits the changed event in the Angular's equivalent
to `componentDidUpdate`. The problem is that:

- it emits the change in a promise (next tick)
- it emits the change when the value is changed programmatically.

While lacking complete understanding of the flow
column4:
I found there
to be some kind of event dispatch queue and the emission to not invoke our
callback immediately.

fix: no longer use the mat-tab-group's change event and listen directly
at the click event.

Fixes b/155104143."

column2:
"message": "build: lock down visibility for targets with no rdeps (#3568)

Summary:
This patch removes `//visibility:public` specifications from all targets
that do not have any Google-internal dependents outside of TensorBoard.
This has two useful implications:

 1. It prevents backsliding of any future unwanted dependents.
 2. It clarifies which targets are actually depended on internally:
    `git grep '//visibility:public'` now suffices
column3:
so we can more easily
    audit these dependencies and start migrating dependencies where
    appropriate.

Generated by `xargs buildozer 'remove visibility //visibility:public'`
with a big list of targets generated via a Google-wide query that looked
roughly like:

```
let tb = //tensorboard/... in
let allrd = rdeps(//...
column6:
1) - //tensorboard/components/tf_imports:polymer_lib
```

where the `(//tensorboard|//tensorflow)[/:]` exclusion corresponds to
the internal equivalent of `//tensorboard:internal`’s scope
column7:
and we have
to exclude `tf_imports:polymer_lib` for… reasons.

Subsequent manual changes included reverting changes to proto library
rules due to some false positives from macro expansion. (I automatically
enumerated these by introspecting `generator_name`
column8:
but it’s too
complicated to automate the full pipeline.) Also made manual changes to
prevent Buildozer from removing comments on `expect_*_installed` rules.
There remain a few false positives due to abundance of caution with
protos (8 targets) and some differences between internal and external
web tests (5 targets).

Because all packages have a default visibility that is at least as
restrictive as `//tensorboard:internal`
column9:
these explicit public
visibility specs correspond to all targets with public visibility.
Because the query to find internal-only targets looks for dependents
outside the `//tensorboard:internal` package group
column10:
switching from
public visibility to package-default visibility should be safe unless
the package-default visibility is not `//tensorboard:internal`; this
applies to only a few targets
column11:
of which a quick audit checks out.

Test Plan:
Test sync <http://cl/309186477> indicates no new problems.

wchargin-branch: vis-no-rdeps-lockdown"

"message": "build: lock down default visibilities (#3566)

Summary:
This patch ensures that all packages have a `default_visibility` setting
of `//tensorboard:internal` or stricter
column3:
while preserving each target’s
visibility by adjusting explicitly as needed. This patch is not intended
to actually change the visibility of any target. The purpose of this
patch is to ensure that removing an explicit `visibility` spec on a
target always leaves that target with TensorBoard-internal visibility.

The `third_party/*.BUILD` (e.g.
column4:
`third_party/urllib3.BUILD`) shims are
excepted.

Test Plan:
Buildozer says that we got ’em all:

```
$ buildozer 'print default_visibility' //tensorboard/...:__pkg__ | sort -u
[:internal]
[//tensorboard:internal]
[//tensorboard/plugins/hparams:__subpackages__]
[//visibility:private]
```

wchargin-branch: vis-default-lockdown"

"message": "[DebuggerV2] Start DebugDataMultiplexer reading at plugin creation (#3530)

* Motivation for features / changes
  * Fix b/154132088: if a debugger run exists in the logdir
column3: `DebugDataMultiplexer` should start loading the data as soon as the DebuggerV2 plugin backend is created. This will shorten the time a user of the DebuggerV2 needs to wait until the data is fully loaded after opening the plugin in the frontend. The current behavior is that run and data loading starts only when the first request is make to the `/runs` route.\r\n  * This should not be a concern for the performance of other TensorBoard plugins
column4: because the tfdbg2 data (tfdbg_events.* files) are created *only* if the generating TensorFlow program calls the `tf.debugging.experimental.enable_dump_debug_info()` explicitly.\r\n* Technical description of changes\r\n  * `DebugDataMultiplexer` creates a `DebugDataReader` in its constructor
column5: instead of when handling the first `Runs()` call.\r\n  * After the `DebugDataReader` is created
column6:
start updating the reader in a periodic fashion in a background thread. The sleep interval between updates is 30 seconds.
  * The object used for `sleep()` between `_reader.update()` calls is an interruptable (wakeable) custom class called `Timer` in debug_data_multiplexer.py. The sleeps will be interrupted (waken) on when data-access methods of `DebugDataMultiplexer` is called.
* Detailed steps to verify changes work correctly (as executed by you)
  * New unit tests are added for the new behavior added in this PR.
  * Manual verification by running DebuggerV2 plugin in ng_tensorboard with real logdirs with tfdbg2 data."

"message": "[DebuggerV2] Use more efficient read in /execution/data and /graph_execution/data routes (#3526)

* Motivation for features / changes
  * Fix a performance issue in the HTTP route /graph_execution/data
  * The issue has to do with the fact that `DebugDataMultiplexer.GraphExecutionData()` uses the inefficient approach of reading all the `GraphExecutionTrace`s first and then slice the array. A much more efficient approach (analogous to the `DebugDataMultiplexer.ExecutionData()` for top-level executions) is to use the range reading support of `DebugDatataReader.graph_execution_traces()` that is now available.
  * Similarly
column3:
use the range reading support of `DebugDatataReader.execution()` in the `/execution/data` route.
* Technical description of changes
  * See the description above. Use range reading support of `DebugDatataReader.execution()` and `DebugDatataReader.graph_execution_trace()`.
  * Also
column4:
remove an extraneous element in the json response (`num_digests`). It is not in the design spec and was included due to oversight on my part.
* Detailed steps to verify changes work correctly (as executed by you)
  * No new unit tests are required to verify the correctness of the new implementation. The existing ones suffice. 
  * Manual testing in the web GUI to confirm much more efficient loading."

"message": "Remove functionality of legacy DB mode (#3539)

column3: but the `--db_import`\r\nand `--db` flags offered an experimental SQLite-backed read path. This\r\nDB mode has always been clearly marked as experimental
column4: and does not\r\nwork as advertised. For example
column5: runs were broken in all dashboards.\r\nA data set with *n* runs at top level would show as *n* runs in\r\nTensorBoard
column6: but all of them would have the name `.` and the same color
column7:

was also completely broken and did not show images. And lots of plugins
just didn’t support DB mode at all. Furthermore
column8: the existence of DB\r\nmode is an active impediment to maintenance
column9:

This patch removes support for DB mode from all plugins
column11:
and renders the `--db`
and `--db_import` flags functionally inoperative. The plumbing itself

the `TensorBoardInfo`  struct.

"message": "improve rerender of vz_line_chart (#3524)

We identified few several expensive operations going on underneath Plottable.
- When we modified dataset() attached to a plot
column3:
Plottable recalculated
  domain which in turn triggered redraw of the plot.
- Plot redraw is scheduled but repeated `clearTimeout` and `setTimeout`
  take considerable time which was the large part of the dataset update
- Changing a dataset caused us to updateSpecialDataset N times (N =
  number of runs)

We addressed the issue by:
- `commit` API after making all the changes
- remember which runs/dataset were changed
- update datasets only once per commit

We did not address:
- autoDomain recomputing the bounds on every data changes.
  - there is no programmatical way to disable auto domain unless we
    change the domain which causes
column6:
the render time:
- toggling run on the selector went down from 1740ms to 273ms
- triggering the log scale went down from 315ms to 264ms
  - from ~670ms to ~620ms when measured from mouse up

Do note that this change does not improve time for other charting
operation like zoom

"message": "text: batch HTML sanitization (#3529)

Summary:
By design
column3: we only expose an API for converting Markdown to *safe* HTML.\r\nBut clients who call this method many times end up performing HTML\r\nsanitization many times
column4:
which is expensive: about an order of magnitude
more expensive than Markdown conversion itself. This patch introduces a
new API that still only emits safe HTML but enables clients to combine
multiple input documents with only one round of sanitization.

Test Plan:
The `/data/plugin/text/text` route sees 40–60% speedup: on my machine
column5:
- from 0.38 ± 0.04 seconds to 0.211 ± 0.005 seconds on the “higher
    order tensors” text demo downsampled to 10 steps; and
  - from 5.3 ± 0.9 seconds to 2.1 ± 0.2 seconds on a Google-internal
    dataset with 32 Markdown cells per step downsampled to 100 steps.

wchargin-branch: text-batch-bleach"

column2:
"message": "util: add `timing.log_latency` (#3490)

Summary:
This patch adds a decorator and context manager for latency profiling.
Any file can just add `@timing.log_latency` to a function definition or
introduce a `with timing.log_latency("some_name_here"):` context
anywhere. The output structure reveals the nesting of the call graph.

The implementation is thread-safe
column3: and prints the current thread\u2019s name\r\nand ID so that the logs can easily be disentangled. (Basically
column4: just\r\nfind a line that you\u2019re interested in
column6:
and pass the
log through `grep THREAD_ID` to get a coherent picture.)

I’ve added this as a global build dep on `//tensorboard` so that it’s
easy to patch timing in for debugging without worrying about build deps.
Any `log_latency` uses that are actually committed should be accompanied
by a strict local dep.

This patch combines previous independent drafts by @nfelt and @wchargin.

Test Plan:
Simple API usage tests included. As a manual test
column7:
adding latency
decoration to a few places in the text plugin’s Markdown rendering
pipeline generates output like this:

```
I0417 13:31:01.586319 140068322420480 timing.py:118] Thread-2[7f64329a2700] ENTER markdown_to_safe_html
I0417 13:31:01.586349 140068322420480 timing.py:118] Thread-2[7f64329a2700]   ENTER Markdown.convert
I0417 13:31:01.586455 140068322420480 timing.py:118] Thread-2[7f64329a2700]   LEAVE Markdown.convert - 0.000105s elapsed
I0417 13:31:01.586492 140068322420480 timing.py:118] Thread-2[7f64329a2700]   ENTER bleach.clean
I0417 13:31:01.586783 140068322420480 timing.py:118] Thread-2[7f64329a2700]   LEAVE bleach.clean - 0.000288s elapsed
I0417 13:31:01.586838 140068322420480 timing.py:118] Thread-2[7f64329a2700] LEAVE markdown_to_safe_html - 0.000520s elapsed
```

This is only emitted when `--verbosity 0` is passed
column8:
not by default.

Co-authored-by: Nick Felt <nfelt@users.noreply.github.com>
wchargin-branch: timing-log-latency"

"message": "audio: deprecate labels and stop reading them (#3500)

Summary:
Most versions of the audio summary APIs only support writing audio data
column3:
but the TB 1.x `tensorboard.summary.audio` ops also support attaching a
“label” (Markdown text) to each audio clip. This feature is not present
in any version of the TensorFlow summary APIs
column5: \r\nand is not present in the TB 2.x `tensorboard.summary.audio` API. It\r\nhasn\u2019t been widely adopted
column6:
and doesn’t integrate nicely in its current
form with upcoming efforts like migrating the audio dashboard to use the
generic data APIs.

This commit causes labels to no longer be read by TensorBoard. Labels
are still written by the TB 1.x summary ops if specified
column7: but now print\r\na warning. Because we do not change the write paths
column9:
because
otherwise audio summaries will not be touched by `dataclass_compat`.
Tests for `dataclass_compat` cover this.

We don’t think that this feature has wide adoption. If this change gets
significant pushback
column10: we can look into restoring labels with a different\r\nimplementation
column11:
likely as a parallel tensor time series.

"message": "dataclass_compat: track initial tag metadata (#3512)

Summary:
The `dataclass_compat` transform dispatches on plugin name
column3: which is\r\nstored in the summary metadata. But the semantics of summary metadata is\r\nthat it need only be set in the first event of each time series. Thus
column5:
events past the first step of a time series have not been
modified by `dataclass_compat`. This has been fine because all
transformations have been either (a) only metadata transforms (which
don’t matter after the first step anyway) or (b) tensor transforms to
hparams data (which only ever has one step anyway). But an upcoming
change will need to transform every step of each audio time series
column6:
so
we need to identify which summaries have audio data even when they don’t
have plugin name set on the same event.

To do so
column7:
we let `dataclass_compat` update a stateful map from tag name
to the first `SummaryMetadata` seen for that time series (scoped to a
particular run).

Test Plan:
Some unit tests included now; the tests for migration of audio summaries
will be more complete because they have more interesting things to test.

wchargin-branch: dataclass-compat-initial-metadata"

"message": "Support comma-separated --plugins lists for "dev" subcommand (#3492)

Address feedback for the new --plugins flag to support comma-separated lists of plugins instead of space-separated lists.

User can still specify plugins like this:
tensorboard dev upload --logdir <your logdir> --plugins=scalars

User can no longer specify multiple plugins like this:
tensorboard dev upload --logdir <your logdir> --plugins scalars graphs histograms

User must now instead specify mutiple plugins like this:

"message": "ng: make sure we do not push 'null' onto hash (#3494)\n\nIn the Angular version of TensorBoard

column5: we use `null` to\r\ndenote the emptiness. However

column7:

understands to be the empty state."

"message": "ci: retry mirror URLs test (#3488)

Summary:
The `mirror_urls_test.sh` occasionally has flaky 404s. This happens
rarely for any given URL
column3: but the test currently checks 233 URLs
column4: so we\r\nsee false positives once in a while. This patch changes the test to\r\nretry up to 3 total attempts on each URL individually
column5:
not just on the
failure status of the whole test.

Test Plan:
Emulate flakiness by changing `check_cmd` to nondeterministically fail:

```diff
diff --git a/tensorboard/tools/mirror_urls_test.sh b/tensorboard/tools/mirror_urls_test.sh
index 8c50a742..a926b2f5 100755
--- a/tensorboard/tools/mirror_urls_test.sh
+++ b/tensorboard/tools/mirror_urls_test.sh
@@ -40 +40 @@ check_urls_resolve() {
-    check_cmd='curl -sfL "$1" >/dev/null || printf "%s\n" "$1"'
+    check_cmd='(( RANDOM % 16 )) && curl -sfL "$1" >/dev/null || printf "%s\n" "$1"'
```

Note that the modified test (usually) fails before this and (usually)
passes after this test. Note that if a URL is changed to genuinely not
resolve that the test consistently fails.

wchargin-branch: ci-retry-mirror-urls"

"message": "demos: use Windows-compatible path names (#3446)

Summary:
The audio and scalars demos wrote runs with embedded colons
column4:
sine_wave`. But Windows prohibits colons in file and directory
names. This patch changes the demos to emit paths that Windows likes.

Fixes #3445.

Test Plan:
Run the audio and scalars demos:

```
rm -rf /tmp/audio_demo /tmp/scalars_demo
bazel run //tensorboard/plugins/audio:audio_demo
bazel run //tensorboard/plugins/scalar:scalars_demo
```

Then
column5:
check the output to ensure that all filenames use only characters
that are valid on Windows:

```
find /tmp/audio_demo /tmp/scalars_demo -printf '%f\n' |
    grep '[<>:"/\\|?*]'
```

Running the same query over a logdir of all existing demo output shows
that audio and scalars were the only offenders.

wchargin-branch: demo-windows-paths"

"message": "ng: fix tiny charts (#3442)

There are many instances when vz_line_chart can be waiting to be
redrawn: it can wait for debouncing
column4:
and/or data.

One of the way Polymer based TensorBoard solved this asynchronousity is
by "visibility: hidden"ing the plugin container instead of "display:
none". This has an effect of giving the container non-zero width and
allows the vz_line_chart to properly render even in the background.

This change replicates
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blob/34530f4789647a81687cc2983866820096b831b1/tensorboard/components/tf_tensorboard/tf-tensorboard.html#L412-L418."

"message": "data: optimize `read_scalars` by skipping scans (#3433)

Summary:
Prior to this change
column3: `read_scalars` (resp. `read_tensors`) delegated to\r\n`list_scalars` (resp. `list_tensors`) to find the set of time series to\r\nread. This is slower than it might sound
column4: because `list_scalars` itself\r\nneeds to scan over all relevant `multiplexer.Tensors` to identify\r\n`max_step` and `max_wall_time`
column5: which are thrown away by `read_scalars`.\r\n(That `list_scalars` needs this full scan at all is its own issue;\r\nideally
column6: these would be memoized onto the event multiplexer.)\r\n\r\nWhen a `RunTagFilter` specifying a single run and tag is given
column7:
we
optimize further by requesting individual `SummaryMetadata` rather than
paring down `AllSummaryMetadata`.

Resolves a comment of @nfelt on #2980:
<https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/pull/2980#discussion_r353469128>

Test Plan:
When applied on top of #3419
column8:
`:list_session_groups_test` improves from
taking 11.1 seconds to taking 6.6 seconds on my machine. This doesn’t
seem to fully generalize; I see only ~13% speedups in a microbenchmark
that hammers `read_scalars` on a logdir with all the demo data
column9:
but the
improvement on that test is important.

wchargin-branch: data-read-without-list"

"message": "hparams: follow standard `is_active` pattern (#3416)

Summary:
Until now
column3: the hparams plugin has been active only when hparams data is\r\npresent *and* the scalars plugin is loaded and active. This cross-plugin\r\ndependency is unique and doesn\u2019t fit well into the data provider world
column4: \r\nso we remove it. The hparams plugin is now active iff hparams data is\r\navailable
column6: we loosen the error handling in parts of the plugin\r\nthat rely on the scalars plugin being active. As long as the scalars\r\nplugin is included in the TensorBoard instance
column7:
this should not be a
problem: TensorBoard core loads all plugins before accepting requests to
any of them. If the hparams plugin is used in an installation with no
scalars plugin
column8: the errors will now be 404s instead of 500s. This seems\r\nacceptable
column9:
as running without a scalars plugin is not a common pattern.

Test Plan:
The hparams plugin is still marked as active in logdirs that contain
hparams data and inactive in logdirs that don’t.

wchargin-branch: hparams-data-provider-is-active"

"message": "backend: always provide data provider on context (#3415)

Summary:
Until now
column3: `context.data_provider` was provided unless `generic_data`\r\nwas explicitly set to `false`. Now
column4: it\u2019s provided in all cases (except\r\nthe legacy DB modes). This was always expected to be safe
column5:
and has been
live by default since TensorBoard 1.15.0.

This is needed to write plugins that unconditionally assume that a data
provider is available.

A consequence of this is that `is_active`’s use of the experimental
`list_plugins` method is now always on as well. This has been on by
default for two months
column6: but was first released in TensorBoard 2.2.0\r\n(just released)
column8:
but also expected to be safe.

Test Plan:
Run TensorBoard with `--generic_data false`. If pointing at an empty
logdir
column9: no plugins are shown as active. If pointing at a full plugin
column10:
all appropriate plugins are shown as active. The debugger plugin is
still marked as active if `--debugger_port` is specified and as inactive
if no relevant flags are given
column11:
so the fallback `is_active` calls are
still working.

wchargin-branch: backend-always-data-provider"

"message": "Add --plugins option to uploader (#3402)

Motivation for features / changes
Allow uploader users to specify the plugins for which data should be uploaded. It has two-fold purpose:
(1) Allow users to specify "experimental" plugins that would otherwise not be uploaded.
(2) Allow users to list a subset of launched plugins
column3:
if they do not want to upload all launched plugin data.

Technical description of changes
Add "--plugins" command line option for upload subcommand. The information is sent in the ServerInfoRequest (aka the handshake) and may impact the list of plugins returned in ServerInfoResponse.plugin_control.allowed_plugins.

Sample usage:
tensorboard dev upload --logdir --plugins scalars graphs histograms

Outside of these specific changes:

It's expected that supported servers will evaluate the list of plugins and decide whether it is valid. If valid
column4: the server will respond with the entire list of plugins or perhaps a sublist. If the list is invalid then it will respond with a CompatibilityVerdict of VERDICT_ERROR and a useful detail message to print to console.\r\n\r\nIf --plugins is not specified then the server is expected to respond with a default list of plugins to upload."

"message": "favicon: check in source image and inline at build time (#3405)

Summary:
Our favicon has hitherto been defined only as four copies of the same
base64 data URI scattered about the repo. This commit creates an actual
file and inlines it into the various destinations at build time with a
very small shell script.

Test Plan:
Files are unchanged
column3:
modulo Prettier formatting:

```shell
prettify() { yarn -s prettier --stdin --stdin-filepath index.html; }
check() (
    set -eu
    bazel build "$1" >/dev/null 2>&1
    git show "HEAD~:$1" | prettify | shasum -a 256
    prettify <"bazel-bin/$1" | shasum -a 256
)
```

```
$ check tensorboard/components/tensorboard.html
e6139eb8dab40c5082b326dcaef810ccc9bd3f4ec5fe1903e18cc13e1eb80226  -
e6139eb8dab40c5082b326dcaef810ccc9bd3f4ec5fe1903e18cc13e1eb80226  -
$ check tensorboard/webapp/index.html
56088876962e466665d0c2a522b1bb323d771e7bd8890f5826627804957c0640  -
56088876962e466665d0c2a522b1bb323d771e7bd8890f5826627804957c0640  -
```

Also

"message": "plugin_util: cache Markdown converter for speed (#3348)

Summary:
Calling `markdown.markdown(s
column3:
...)` is shorthand for creating a Markdown
converter `md = markdown.Markdown(...)` and calling `md.convert(s)` on
the converter. But the initialization is expensive when extensions are
in play: it requires iterating over package entry points
column5: and mutating the newly initialized converter.\r\n\r\nOn my machine
column6: rendering an empty Markdown string takes 123 \u00b5s (\u00b1322 ns)\r\nwith a fresh converter
column7: or 96.7 ns (\u00b11.05 ns) with a cached converter.\r\nBy default
column8: the text plugin downsamples to 10 samples per time series
column9:
but each sample can have an arbitrary number of Markdown calls when the
summary data is rank-1 or rank-2. Most non-text plugins also call this
to render summary descriptions. Loading the scalars plugin with my
standard test logdir calls this method 369 times. Loading the text
plugin with the text demo data calls this method 962 times
column10:
burning
about 118 ms on absolutely nothing.

Test Plan:
Run TensorBoard with `--verbosity 9` and pipe through `grep markdown`
column11: \r\nthen load the scalars dashboard. Before this change
column12: you\u2019d see a bunch\r\nof \u201cimported extension module\u201d and \u201cloaded extension\u201d spam
column13: to the tune\r\nof hundreds of lines per page load. After this change
column14: you actually see\r\nnone (presumably because the logs happen at module import time
column15:
which is
before the `--verbosity` setting takes effect).

wchargin-branch: cache-markdown-converter"

"message": "Experimental plugins specified using ExperimentalPluginLoader (#3344)

Allow an administrator of a Tensorboard to mark certain plugins as "experimental" and hidden to users by default. Users would then need to add query parameter "experimentalPlugin=" to the URL to see the experimental plugin.

Introduce marker class ExperimentalPlugin which acts as an annotation on either TBPlugin or TBLoader that indicates a plugin is experimental. TensorBoardWSGIApp() uses isinstance() to determine if a plugin is experimental and passes the information as a list of names
column4:
in its call to TensorBoardWSGI()

TensorBoardWSGI._serve_plugins_listing() filters out plugins that are included in experimental_plugins but are not specified in an experimentalPlugin query parameter.

There is logic in createRouter() that forwards "experimentalPlugin" query parameter values from the original TensorBoard request to the call to the plugins_listing endpoint.

Usage examples:

class ExperimentalImagePlugin(
  images_plugin.ImagesPlugin

is part of Angular's DI system prebuilds injectable for the META_REDUCER

"message": "Use cPython 3.5–compatible function definitions (#3320)

Summary:
In Python as of PEP 3102
column3: function definitions may include keyword-only\r\narguments after a splat (`def foo(x
column5: y)`). But cPython 3.5 has a\r\nparser bug (<https://bugs.python.org/issue9232>) when trailing commas\r\nare used with this syntax
column9: )`. This is fixed in\r\nPython 3.6 and up
column11:
so for now we should make
sure to omit these trailing commas.

The change to `pyproject.toml` prevents Black from re-introducing these
trailing commas. We leave `py27` in the `pyproject.toml` to avoid a mass
reformat removing `u`-prefixes from Unicode string literals (which is
fine
column12: but should be a separate change for Bazel `srcs_version`).\r\n\r\nWe don\u2019t run our full test suite on Python 3.5 yet
column14: lack of `assert_not_called` and that `json.loads`\r\ndoes not accept `bytes`). For now
column15: it suffices to run `flake8` on both\r\nPython 3.5 and Python 3.7
column16:
because that at least parses all the code.

Test Plan:
That CI passes suffices.

wchargin-branch: py35-fundefs"

"message": "uploader: fix rate limiting for logdir polling (#3305)

Summary:
Recent refactorings to the RPC rate limiting had the unintended side
effect of removing rate limiting on logdir polling. This meant that
after all data had been read from the logdir
column3: the uploader would\r\ncontinue to poll it aggressively (thousands of times per second on my\r\nmachine)
column4:
which is bad for disks and expensive on network file systems.

This commit adds a separate rate limiter for the logdir polling. We
don’t reuse the RPC rate limiter because that would force us to tick
twice on the same timer every cycle.

Fixes #3301.

Test Plan:
Run `bazel run //tensorboard -- dev upload --logdir /nope --verbosity 0`
(with any logdir path
column5: but it\u2019s easier when it\u2019s empty)
column6:
and note that
the “Starting an upload cycle” logs now progress at 0.2 per second
rather than 6000 per second. Unit tests also included: if the `.tick()`
is removed

column5:
just once per
    time series.

    explicitly—

    ```

      allowed_plugins: "scalars"
    }
    ```

"message": "data: perform downsampling in multiplexer provider (#3272)

Summary:
The `MultiplexerDataProvider` now respects its `downsample` parameter
column3:

column4:
which is required.

    that they will behave correctly with other data providers.

Test Plan:

conflicts

to remove the static plugin at the exact same time that we release the
dynamic plugin.

and the redirect notice. In the virtualenv contents

```
find "$VIRTUAL_ENV"/lib/python?.?/site-packages/tensorboard_plugin_profile \
    -type f -execdir sed -i s/experiment_profile/profile/g {} +
```

Note that the dynamic profile plugin is now called just “profile”

"message": "data: rename `latest_max_index` to `max_length` (#3161)

Summary:
The metadata for a blob sequence has historically included the number of
blob values in the most recent blob sequence datum (`latest_max_index`).
The intent of this field was to enable the audio and image dashboards to
determine the total number of “samples” per summary. But the value that
is actually needed here is the _maximum_ length of any datum
column3:
not the
length of just the latest datum.

This commit renames `latest_max_index` to `max_length`
column4: keeping aliases\r\nfor both the initializer and the accessor property while we migrate\r\nclients. All clients in this repository are migrated in this commit
column5:
but
some Google-internal clients need to be handled separately.

Test Plan:
Unit tests show that both the old and new invocations still work. A test
sync shows that relevant Google-internal targets are still fine.

wchargin-branch: data-max-length"

column2:
"message": "ci: don’t store Pip HTTP cache (#3167)

Summary:
The Pip HTTP cache stores all downloaded wheels and is never evicted.
With new `tf-nightly` wheels every day
column3: this adds up quickly. We last\r\ncleared our Travis caches about a month ago
column4:
and they’re up to 14.3 GB.

"message": "data: add `list_plugins` for `is_active` support (#3124)

Summary:
The `is_active` method of TensorBoard plugins hasn’t worked well with
data providers so far
column4: and adding one would break backward compatibility. Instead
column5: we\r\ncan pull `is_active` handling into the core application logic
column6:
where
both the data provider and experiment ID are still available.

A new data provider method `list_plugins` takes an experiment ID and
returns names of plugins with relevant data. A new (experimental) plugin
API lets plugins specify whose data they want to read
column7:
defaulting to
just their own. The `/data/plugins_listing` logic now joins the list of
plugins with data (from the provider) with each plugin’s list of data
that it cares about to determine which plugins are active. As a fallback
for plugins whose data is not yet understood by the data provider
column8:
we
also check `is_active` for plugins that don’t pass the first test.

The new data provider method is optional (for now). If not implemented
column9:
this patch has no effect.

As a side benefit
column10: this can speed up the plugins listing route by a fair\r\namount: we only make one targeted query against the multiplexer rather\r\nthan querying all its `Tensors` once per plugin
column11:
and we don’t need to
invoke `is_active` at all for plugins that are known to be active by
this first check.

Test Plan:
Change the `is_active` methods for the scalars
column13: and histograms\r\nplugins to return `False` rather than `True` when a data provider is\r\nset. Then
column14: run TensorBoard in generic data mode pointing at (a) the\r\nscalars demo
column16: and (c) the images demo. Note\r\nthat in case (a) only the scalars and graphs dashboards are active
column17: in\r\ncase (b) only the histograms and distributions dashboards are active\r\n(this demo does not write graphs)
column18:
and in case (c) only the images and
graphs dashboards are active. Note that this behavior is the same across
generic and non-generic data modes. Note that the behavior prior to this
patch is restored if the implementation of `list_plugins` in the
multiplexer-backed data provider is removed
column19:
so this is a no-op until
data providers choose to implement this method.

wchargin-branch: data-list-active-plugins"

"message": "windows: explicitly register correct MIME types (#3128)

Summary:
The standard library’s `mimetypes.guess_type` can give incorrect results
on Windows
column3: because arbitrary programs can influence its behavior by\r\nwriting to the registry. This can be worked around by reinstating the\r\ncorrect MIME types with `mimetypes.add_type`
column4:
as in this patch. Fixes
#3120.

Test Plan:
To check that this patch works at all on Windows
column5:
edited the registry to
add a bad content type:

```
reg add HKCR\.js /v "Content Type" /d application/x-testing-123
```

…then verified that before this change
column6: `mimetypes.guess_type(\"foo.js\")`\r\ngives the wrong value and TensorBoard does not render properly (strict\r\nMIME type checking error in Chrome
column8:
whereas after this
change `mimetypes.guess_type("foo.js")` gives the correct value and
TensorBoard returns the correct content type in its JavaScript
responses. TensorBoard still does not render on Windows due to unrelated
errors in the debugger plugin.

To check that this set of patches is sufficient
column9: `git grep guess_type`\r\nshows call sites only in `core_plugin` and `projector_plugin`. The\r\nformer takes file names from `webfiles.zip`
column12:
and `woff2` files (plus a `LICENSE`). The latter has a fixed set
of inputs with extensions `html` and `js`.

wchargin-branch: windows-explicit-mime"

column2:
"message": "backend: fix locking for `_plugin_to_tag_to_content` (#3122)

Summary:
The `plugin_event_accumulator` tries to maintain fine-grained locks for
each plugin
column3: but didn\u2019t properly lock its table of locks
column4:
and didn’t
lock around accesses to the table of plugins. This commit replaces the
fine-grained locking with a simple coarse-grained lock.

Because all `dict`s involved are keyed only on Python strings
column8: this should be\r\na no-op in CPython implementations. But correct concurrency is\r\n[explicitly part of Google style][style]
column9: and without this patch some\r\nsubsequent changes would need to make this problem worse
column10:
so we might as
well just fix it Once and For All.

[style]: https://google.github.io/styleguide/pyguide.html#218-threading

Test Plan:
The primary safety concern due to this change is potential for liveness
failure
column11: but this change basically contracts a number of locks into one
column12:
so any lock waiting cycle that exists now would also have existed
previously.

wchargin-branch: mux-lock-locks"

"message": "ci: check lint with Black

Summary:
The Black binary only runs Python 3.6 and up
column3: so we only lint in the\nPython 3 CI build
column4:
but that’s perfectly fine. I’ve moved that build to
be first so that we can fail fast.

The preceding large sequence of change commits was generated with:

```
#!/bin/sh
set -eu
black .
docformatter -i -r .
black .  # should be a no-op
export GIT_AUTHOR_NAME="TensorBoard Gardener"
export GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL="tensorboard-gardener@google.com"
# Commit each directory in order of longest-named directory to
# shortest-named
column5: to force a topological ordering. Collapse some select\n# subtrees to reduce the number of commits.\ngit diff --numstat \\\n    | awk '{ print $3 }' \\\n    | rev \\\n    | cut -d / -f 2- \\\n    | rev \\\n    | sed -e 's#/\\(test\\|demo\\)$##' \\\n    | sed -e 's#^\\(tensorboard/compat\\)/.*#\\1#' \\\n    | sed -e 's#^\\(tensorboard/plugins/interactive_inference\\)/.*#\\1#' \\\n    | sed -e 's#^\\(tensorboard/summary\\)/.*#\\1#' \\\n    | sort -u \\\n    | awk '{ print length($0)
column6:
$0 }' \
    | sort -nrs \
    | awk '{ print $2 }' \
    | while read -r dir
do
    git add "${dir}"
    if git commit -m "black: reformat directory ${dir}" >/dev/null 2>&1; then
        printf 'reformat %s: ' "${dir}"
        git show --oneline --shortstat | tail -n 1
    else
        printf 'skip %s (covered by subtrees)\n' "${dir}"
    fi
done
```

as all files have been fixed
up. It takes about 0.3 seconds on my machine.

"message": "uploader: include metadata in `list` output (#2941)

Summary:
This commit teaches the uploader to display experiment metadata included
in `StreamExperiments` responses by supported servers. For servers
without this support
column3:
the change is a backward-compatible no-op.

The format is intentionally undocumented and not under any compatibility
guarantees
column4: but is designed to be easily parseable for ad hoc usage. For\r\ninstance
column5:
this simple one-liner finds experiments with lots of points so
that the user can delete them:

```
tensorboard dev list |
    awk '$1 == "Id" { id = $2 } $1 == "Scalars" && $2 > 1000 { print id }'
```

Test Plan:

column6: which does not yet support the new RPCs

"message": "build: tag all web tests with "webtest" (#2961)

Summary:
Web tests take a long time to Vulcanize and run
column3: and some have very\r\nwide-reaching dependencies. For example
column4: `core_test_chromium` depends on\r\nall of `//tensorboard`. They\u2019re also especially flaky when many of them\r\nare run concurrently
column5:
as they run out of resources even on capable
machines. All this makes `bazel test //tensorboard/...` prohibitively
expensive for quick incremental iteration. This commit adds build tags
such that one can write

    bazel test //tensorboard/... --test_tag_filters=-webtest --build_tests_only

to run all affected tests except web tests. (Using `--build_tests_only`
prevents Vulcanization of targets that match the `//tensorboard/...`
pattern but are only needed by tests tagged as `webtest`.)

Test Plan:

Summary:
Networking is hard. Everyone’s machine seems to do something different.
We have a lot of special cases in `program.py`
column3:
and we keep finding new
configurations. This commit adds a check to `diagnose_tensorboard.py`
that prints the available loopback and wildcard addresses on all address
families.

It could also be nice to check whether it is actually possible to
connect to sockets opened on the loopback address in various
configurations (e.g.
column4:
with a direct socket-to-socket connection and with
a Python-provided WSGI server and URL fetcher). We defer such a change.

On my machine

"message": "uploader: request `ServerInfo` from frontend (#2879)

Summary:
This commit integrates the new `ServerInfo` RPC with the uploader. It’s
not currently enabled by default: the current behavior is the same as
the existing behavior
column3:
except that experiment URLs now properly have a
trailing slash. We’ll soon remove the hard-coded API backend endpoint
behavior to enable this by default.

Test Plan:
Running a test frontend and a test backend
column4:
we observe the following
behavior with different arguments:

| `--origin` | `--api_endpoint` | → | URL origin | Backend |
|------------|------------------|---|------------|---------|
| empty      | empty            |   | prod       | prod    |
| empty      | prod             |   | prod       | prod    |
| empty      | test             |   | prod       | test    |
| test       | empty            |   | test       | test    |
| test       | test             |   | test       | test    |
| test       | prod             |   | test       | prod    |

Here
column6:
and “test” in the `--api_endpoint` column is like `localhost:10000`.
Note that the no-argument case is equivalent to the explicitly-empty
argument case because both arguments have empty default values.

Explicitly specifying `--origin https://tensorboard.dev`
column8:
fails with “Corrupt response from backend” because
server-side support has not yet been rolled out. This is expected.

Specifying `--origin http://localhost:0` or any other unreachable host
fails with `ECONNREFUSED` and a nice message.

My test frontend is configured to reject clients below version 2.0.0 and
warn on clients below version 2.0.1. Changing the local `version.py` to
`2.0.0a0` or `2.0.1a0` exercises these cases.

Finally
column9: double-checked that building the Pip package
column11:
and running `tensorboard dev list` properly uses the production backend
and prints URLs that resolve to the production frontend.

wchargin-branch: uploader-serverinfo-request"

column2: "message": "cleanup: migrate test over to karma based tooling (#2928)\n\nEspecially when we leverage Angular's module system
column3:
we need to use the
ng_module build rules to generate all necessary factory method. Although
it is yet unclear exactly why Angular's JIT compilation does not work
under node environment
column4:
the team decided to migrate all tests to the
karma based tooling.

This change addresses:
1. jasmine_node_test to karma_web_test (2 are remaining on tensor
widget)
2. fixed core effects that was using ts_library as oppposed to ng_module
(our app was broken because CoreEffectsModule did not get deps correctly
injected in)
3. migrated off of chai/sinon:
  This is tricky and requires some explanation. Normally
column5: when running test\r\n  with the karma executor
column6: one would use webpack or its equivalent to build the\r\n  binary. This should resolve all packages like React or chai correctly and\r\n  bundle in all necessary sources
column9: uses concatjs\r\n  as a bundler which uses requirejs by default. As such
column10: we need some of our\r\n  dependencies to be requirejs compatible some of which is not. For instance
column11: \r\n  import 'chai'; will fail and the test bundle will try to resolve 'chai' using\r\n  ES module
column12: which of course will fail. Because karma_web_test by default uses\r\n  jasmine framework
column13: we do not have to have think about whether chai is\r\n  requirejs compatible but adding other testing framework support quite tricky.\r\n  To relieve ourselves from the headache
column14: we have decided to move away from\r\n  chai/sinon in favor of jasmine."

"message": "Backport `mock` assertions for Python 2 tests (#2837)

Summary:
Some of the `//tensorboard/uploader/...` tests are currently disabled in
Python 2 because our backport of `mock` doesn’t support the required
assertions. We can’t easily upgrade the dependency (see #2132)
column3:
but we
can backport those assertions. The assertions backported are:

  - `assert_not_called`
  - `assert_called`
  - `assert_called_once`

This patch is the combination of (restrictions of) the following
upstream Git commits:

  - [`c7d6c7dcafd4482626194528b24f174dd15f5f5e`][1] (2014-04-17)
  - [`8882c2fccb9f7d3b8ba2b5534c0dd9d52343725f`][2] (2014-04-17)
  - [`7ca5d3afe293d5e4d769c1cb2dfccb0688ba1292`][3] (2016-03-11)
  - [`07532a75003ec8e871e494f9f1ab8f28fa246f08`][4] (2018-01-19)

I identified those commits by diffing our pinned version of `mock.py`
(the version at upstream commits `b14e284` through `dc1458a`) against
the version of `mock/mock.py` in the current repo
column4: tracing the blame on\r\nthe implementation of the relevant assertions
column5: then pruning commits that\r\nrelied on other changes not yet patched in (and were [only cosmetic
column8:
too. Changing
`uploader_test.py`’s `test_upload_swallows_rpc_failure` to comment out
the `_upload_once` call causes the subsequent `assert_called_once` to
fail with the correct error message
column9:
showing that the assertions are
wired up properly.

wchargin-branch: mock-backport"

"message": "data load: prevent JSE when canceling async (#2832)

Polymer.prototype.async without a wait time defaults to next microtask.
Polymer implemented custom microtask scheduling which is not impervious
to some edge case.

Polymer has some internal counter for the microtasks and the `async`
call returns (contrived for illustration) `currentMicroTaskCounter + i`.
When canelling the async
column3:
it checks whether the handle is in between
`currentMicroTaskCounter` and `currentMicroTaskCounter` + [numAsyncs]
and it expects callback to exist when it is in between. The problem
happened when a handle is cancelled twice (our `reset` method gets
called more than once in a microtask for hparams) as it cannot find a
callback for the handle.

reference: https://github.com/Polymer/polymer/blob/dc20feca22ed6915eb67a6df2a8475ceba295de7/lib/utils/async.js#L198-L204

simpler repro:

```ts
const handle = this.async(() => {});
this.cancelAsync(handle);
this.cancelAsync(handle); // throws the error.
```"

"message": "program: add subcommand CLI support (#2793)

Summary:
This commit adds a subcommand interface to support invocations in the
manner of `apt-get install` or `git commit`. All existing invocations
remain valid
column3: and are now also available under the `tensorboard serve`\r\nsubcommand. Other subcommands may be injected programmatically. For\r\ninstance
column4: we could migrate the existing `tensorboard --inspect` to\r\n`tensorboard inspect`
column5:
which makes more sense semantically (as it does
something quite different from starting a web server).

To support both `tensorboard --flags` and `tensorboard serve --flags`
column6: \r\nwe require some hacks first to get off the ground at all in Python 2
column7:
and then to have sane error messages without massive flag duplication in
all Python versions. Even recent Python versions don’t have a notion of
a _default_ subcommand
column8:
so we need to manually inspect `argv` to
determine what kind of argument parser to construct.

Test Plan:
Unit tests added
column9:
and the smoke test for the dynamic plugin (plus the
Pip package test script) serve as integration tests for existing
behavior. It’s important to test this in both Python 2 and Python 3. For
manual testing:

  - Check that the output of `tensorboard --help` still includes all the
    normal flags
column10: and now has a list of subcommands (one item long).\r\n  - Check that the output of `tensorboard serve --help` is just like the\r\n    output of `tensorboard --help`
column11: but without the list of subcommands.\r\n  - Patch a `demo` subcommand into `main.py`
column12:
and check that the output
    of `tensorboard demo --help` is just that subcommand’s help (without
    flags to `serve`) and that `tensorboard --help` shows the `demo`
    subcommand.

Finally
column13:
note that changing the implementation of the monkey patch to
just `yield; return` causes both `argparse_util_test` and `program_test`
to fail on Python 2 (but not Python 3).

wchargin-branch: subcommands"

"message": "sec: Enable CSP and disallow random script tags (#2726)\n\nFor our HTML-based resources
column3: we now apply the CSP so we do not load\r\nunknown image
column5:
and scripts.

**Design choice made**
the CSP is applied at the http_util with one API to configure the hash
part so no response can set the CSP to "unsafe" and make entire
application unsafe. e.g.
column6:
dynamic resource is served with "unsafe" and
the unsafe script tag gets loaded which now has access to the parent
frame and exfiltrate.

**Future work**
- Turn 'strict-dynamic' off
- Apply CSP to the projector_binary.html.
- CSP needs to work better with the dynamic plugin. One possibility is
  to modify our API so the plugins can define static resources which can
  be shasumed by TensorBoard.
- Above logic can introduce more complexity to the core_plugin. We
  should consider creating richer asset_provider API so it can mediate
  with serving."

"message": "backend: fix `--path_prefix` validation (#2737)

Summary:
Specifying a path prefix without leading slash has always been
disallowed by the docs
column3:
but in TensorBoard 2.0.0 this just hits an
inscrutable internal error when starting the server:

```
ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: '6006my_path_prefix'
```

As of #2733
column4: this is at least a correctly reported error
column5: but it still\r\nhas a stack trace. This commit makes it a normal
column6:
fast-failing usage
error.

The logic to strip trailing slashes was also duplicated
column7:
so `/foo` and
`/foo/` and `/foo//` were all the same but differed from `/foo///`. This
commit removes one copy of the logic and makes the remaining copy strip
all trailing slashes instead of just one.

Test Plan:
Run with `--path_prefix /foo`
column8: and note that TensorBoard exits with a\r\nsingle-line error. Run with `/foo`
column12:
and note that all four now have the same behavior.

wchargin-branch: path-prefix-validation"

as specifying experiment IDs. If these two path components are omitted

column5: so no existing logic needs to change.\r\nThe ID is added to the WSGI environment and may be extracted via a new\r\npublic function

Note that the `/data/plugins_listing` implementation does not need to
change: it correctly specifies experiment IDs in iframe loading
mechanisms because we already use the general-purpose `SCRIPT_NAME` key
specified by WSGI for this purpose.

    # at top of `_route_request`:

    eid = plugin_util.experiment_id(environ)
    logger.warn("%r [%r]" % (environ.get("PATH_INFO")

in the following configurations:

"message": "application: add redirect to ensure trailing slash (#2734)

Summary:
When using a `--path_prefix`
column3: TensorBoard has historically required a\r\ntrailing slash after that prefix: e.g.
column6: #1176.) Different\r\nversions of TensorBoard have different failure modes when the non-slash\r\npath is loaded; currently
column8:
but the frontend
computes relative URLs incorrectly. This commit adds a redirect from the
empty path to `/` to avoid the problem.

This logic could be inlined into the `PathPrefixMiddleware`
column9: but we\u2019ll\r\nsoon have other middlewares with similar needs
column10:
so providing this as its
own middleware avoids duplicating the functionality.

Test Plan:
Launch TensorBoard with `--path_prefix /foo` (or `--path_prefix /foo/`;
the two are equivalent) and navigate to `/foo/` and `/foo` in a browser.
Note that they now both work and resolve to `/foo/`
column11:
while prior to this
commit navigating to `/foo` yielded a broken TensorBoard.

wchargin-branch: empty-path-redirect"

column2:
"message": "vulc: combine script in compile=True and shasum (#2719)

Motivation: we would like to introduce CSP and not trust any script tags
that does not match our shasum.

Change 1: introduce a logic to combine all script tags (in the order
that it was laid out) into one so we can just shasum 1 script tag.

Change 2: Vulcanization outputs another file that includes sha256s of
all script elements's content or content of resource src points at. Note
that the .scripts_sha256 file includes newline delimited list of shas without
keys (script names are not named).

Change 3: webfiles.zip now have a _shasum directory that can be used by
Python server.

Future work: change our Python static file serving to include the shasum
in the CSP for HTML files. We special case the _shasum directory in the
zip files to not serve that."

"message": "application: extract path prefix logic to middleware (#2733)

Summary:
This way
column3:
we can reason about and test it in isolation as we add more
middleware to the application.

Note that when using `--path_prefix`
column4: loading the main TensorBoard page\r\nwithout a trailing slash on the URL has long been broken (#1117). This\r\ncommit does not fix that
column5: but changes the exact failure mode: rather\r\nthan 404ing
column6:
we now load a broken TensorBoard (relative URLs don’t
resolve). A follow-up commit will fix this properly.

Test Plan:
Verify that TensorBoard still works fully

column3: we apply the `_handle_errors` middleware as a decorator\r\ndirectly on `__call__`. We plan to add middleware that is parameterized\r\non instance variables

  - running with no `--host` flag:
      - can connect to loopback on IPv4 only
      - cannot connect over LAN
      - `strace` shows binding on `AF_INET`
      - a notice about `--bind_all` is printed to stderr
  - running with `--host=localhost`:
      - same behavior as with no `--host` flag
column7:
but no notice is printed
  - running with `--host='::1'`:
      - can connect to loopback on IPv6 only
      - cannot connect over LAN
      - `strace` shows binding on `AF_INET6`
  - running with `--host=0.0.0.0`:
      - can connect to loopback on IPv4 only
      - **can** connect over LAN
      - `strace` shows binding on `AF_INET`
  - running with `--host='::0'`:
      - can connect on both IPv4 and IPv6
      - **can** connect over LAN
      - `strace` shows binding on `AF_INET6`
  - running with `--bind_all`:
      - can connect on both IPv4 and IPv6
      - **can** connect over LAN
      - `strace` shows binding on `AF_INET6` with an additional syscall
        to `setsockopt(3
column12: which is not present in any other tested case\r\n\r\nIn all cases
column13: the printed serving URL (\u201cTensorBoard x.y.z running at\u2026\u201d)\r\nbears the exact `--host` flag
column14: or my full hostname if `--bind_all` was\r\ngiven
column15: or `localhost` if neither was given. In all cases
column16:
the URL is a
clickable link in my `gnome-terminal`.

Note that on my system dual binding to `::0` works without an explicit
syscall—i.e.
column17:
`IPV6_V6ONLY` defaults to `0`—but this is not portable.

Connection testing was performed via

```shell
for ipv in 4 6; do
    if curl -sfL -"${ipv}" localhost:6006/data/logdir >/dev/null; then
        printf 'v%d OK\n' "${ipv}"
    else
        printf 'v%d FAIL\n' "${ipv}"
    fi
done
```

in all cases.

wchargin-branch: localhost-only"

column2:
"message": "errors: add unified error types (#2631)

Summary:
We’d like to clarify the error semantics in the data provider APIs
column3:
but
there’s not currently a good way for errors at the data provider layer
to propagate through the stack: every plugin handler would need to
handle the various exception types appropriately
column4: which would be verbose\r\nand error-prone. To remedy this
column5: we add a family of unified error types\r\nthat may be raised from anywhere inside a TensorBoard HTTP handler
column6: and\r\nwhich will be caught and converted to HTTP responses by TensorBoard\r\nitself. For errors not in a whitelist
column7: we defer to the default \u201cInternal\r\nServer Error\u201d code path
column8:
to avoid accidentally leaking sensitive data.

The error types themselves are selected from Google’s standard errors;
we can add more as appropriate.

Test Plan:

```

Content-Length: 50
Expires: 0
Cache-Control: no-cache

Date: Tue

column2:
"message": "Properly handle bad requests to plugin data endpoints (#2611)

Summary:
Most\* plugin endpoints for serving actual data have historically tried
to access data from the multiplexer with no validation or error
handling
column3: and as a result would crash and burn (with 500s) given a run\r\nor tag that doesn\u2019t exist. This actually happens fairly commonly: if you\r\nstart TensorBoard and interact with the web UI
column4: kill the server while\r\nleaving the browser tab open
column5: and start a new TensorBoard on the same\r\nport but a different log directory
column6:
then the old TensorBoard’s refresh
loop will request data from the runs and tags that were previously
available.

These are now properly handled as 400s
column8: and they don\u2019t spam\r\nthe command line anymore
column9: either. We resolve some TODOs from 2015!\r\n\r\n\\* Weighted by frequency of use. :-) By raw counts
column10:
more plugins behaved
well than ill!

Test Plan:
Visit the following endpoints
column11: and verify that each one responds with a\r\n500 Internal Server Error before this patch
column12:
but a 400 Bad Request (with
human-readable message) after this patch:

  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/audio/audio>
  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/audio/individualAudio>
  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/example_basic/greetings?run=&tag=>
  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/images/images>
  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/images/individualImage>
  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/mesh/data?content_type=>
  - <http://localhost:6006/data/plugin/scalars/scalars>

wchargin-branch: keyerror-400"

"message": "ng: render plugins fetched from backend (#2587)

This change introduces ngrx effects that allows us to interact with the
TensorBoard backend.

This change is not what we ultimately want: it renders all plugins onto
the header instead of showing only active ones.

About testing
This change introduces karma testing instead of the node based testing which admittedly is less than ideal for its speed. It fails with less than ideal error like below.

```
  Message:                               
    TypeError: Cannot read property 'injector' of null
  Stack:                                     
        at <Jasmine>
        at TestBedViewEngine._createCompilerAndModule
...
```

Karma objectively is inferior than running the test in node because
1. source bundling takes time (even if it was simple concat)
2. browser bring-up/tear-down takes time
3. reporting is less than ideal (multi-browser reporter is not well implemented; it probably is configurable though).

If you are type of person who does TDD with ibazel
column3: the difference would be night and day -- node: <1s vs. karma: ~15s.\r\n\r\nAlthough not 100% clear yet
column4: it seems like you can use node test only if the component under test does not leverage any dependency injection (and require the angular JIT/AOT compilation)."

column2:
"message": "core: expose backend and storage as Polymer (#2590)

This change contains a hack that should improve developer experience
by allowing Angular app to wrap Polymer code.

In order for the Angular app to be useful
column3: we need to cross the\r\nJSCompiler and rollup boundary where symbols are separately mangled.\r\nBy exposing as property in the Polymer element
column4:
we can make the symbol
more stable.

Note that
column6:
the type information of the TypeScript
gets lost but here is the rationale:

1. in the future
column7: we expect to create a ts_library target both Polymer and Angular can depend on.\r\n  a. it is currently blocked due to the sync issue; we cannot have ts_library target\r\n  b. when both binaries have transitive dependency on the ts_library
column8: the code will be bundled twice in their closure.\r\n  c. note: hopefully
column10: we can abandon the namespace and just use module.\r\n2. foresee not too many shared modules between Polymer typescript and Angular typescript\r\n  a. the one that needs to be shared are the ones that are stateful like tf_backend. There are no other module that needs to share states."

"message": "data: add partial generic data provider base class (#2529)

Summary:
This commit begins an initiative to enable TensorBoard to consume data
from multiple sources using a single API. Like TensorBoard’s existing
experimental “DB mode”
column3: this opens the door to addressing fundamental\r\nperformance limitations. Unlike DB mode
column4:
this is not specific to any
particular database implementation.

In the short term
column5:

thin layer on top of the existing event multiplexer system. We will
migrate plugins to read data using the new APIs instead of from the
multiplexer directly. At that point
column6: we can begin looking into providing\r\nalternate
column8:
an SQLite-backed store
whose state persists across TensorBoard invocations.

For now
column9:
we include only the API calls for listing and reading scalar
data. We’ll expand the API surface as we proceed.

Test Plan:
Unit tests included (there’s not much to test).

column2: "message": "polymer2: fixed plugin dropdown UI issue (#2517)\n\nNow that we have real ShadowDom
column3: the input within the paper-input has to\r\nbe styled through mulitple layers of webcomponents
column5:
we would be using ShadyCSS (CSS mixin did not make it to the spec) and a
mixin API exposed by appropriate WebComponents to achieve that but it is
not viable in this case. Specifically
column6: paper-dropdown-menu allows\r\nstyling of paper-input using a mixin but in order to style input within\r\nthe paper-input
column7:
we need to use another mixin. ShadyCSS explicitly says
the nested mixin is not supported.

Instead of transforming with CSS
column8:
we decided to fix the issue by
pre-processing the tabName in JavaScript.

Also
column9:
we fixed the wrong CSS selector after paper-menu -> paper-listbox
change.

See:
https://github.com/webcomponents/polyfills/tree/master/packages/shadycss#known-issues"

column2:
"message": "Use `rel="noopener"` for `target="_blank"` links (#2516)

Summary:
Links with `target="_blank"` open in a new tab
column3:
but by default that new
tab can control the page that opened it via the `window.opener` object.
Using `rel="noopener"` closes this security hole.

Test Plan:
No automated test for now; we tend to catch these in code review
column4:
so
this is a backfill. Manual verification:

```
$ git grep -o noopener '*.html' | wc -l
20
$ git grep -o _blank '*.html' | wc -l
20
```

wchargin-branch: rel-noopener"

"message": "Allow plugins to declare wildcard routes. (#2476)\n\nCurrently
column3: plugins must explicitly enumerate the routes that they serve via get_plugin_apps(). This is inconvenient in the case of plugins that provide a set of related routes
column4: such as a directory full of static files
column5: whose names need not be known in advance. This is the case
column7: for dynamic plugins using Angular or React
column8: where the build process produces a set of assets (including HTML
column12: etc.).\r\n\r\nThis PR allows a plugin to declare a wildcard route ending in /*
column13: e.g. {'/foo/*': self._foo_wildcard_handler}. Any request beginning with the specified path prefix will be passed to the given handler.\r\n\r\nNote the handler may do whatever it likes with these requests; they do not necessarily correspond to filesystem paths (as in the static assets use case). Thus this change also allows for RESTful apis
column14: where object IDs and such are encoded as path elements. Any security concerns (e.g.
column16: are the responsibility of the handler."

"message": "ci: check lint with Prettier

Summary:
The `--ignore-engines` appears to be needed on Travis (but not locally);
without it
column3:
Angular cannot be installed:

```
error @angular-devkit/architect@0.800.6: The engine "node" is incompatible with this module. Expected version ">= 10.9.0".
error Found incompatible module
```

The preceding large sequence of change commits was generated with:

```
#!/bin/sh
set -eu
yarn fix-lint
export GIT_AUTHOR_NAME="TensorBoard Gardener"
export GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL="tensorboard-gardener@google.com"
# Commit each directory in order of longest-named directory to
# shortest-named
column4: to force a topological ordering. Collapse test and\n# demo directories
column5: and group by parent directory to reduce from ~110\n# commits to about ~20.\ngit diff --numstat \\\n    | awk '{ print $3 }' \\\n    | rev \\\n    | cut -d / -f 2- \\\n    | rev \\\n    | sed -e 's#/\\(test\\|demo\\)$##' \\\n    | xargs -n 1 dirname \\\n    | sort -u \\\n    | awk '{ print length($0)
column6:
$0 }' \
    | sort -nrs \
    | awk '{ print $2 }' \
    | while read -r dir
do
    git add "${dir}"
    if git commit -m "prettier: reformat directory ${dir}" >/dev/null 2>&1; then
        printf 'reformat %s: ' "${dir}"
        git show --oneline --shortstat | tail -n 1
    else
        printf 'skip %s (covered by subtrees)\n' "${dir}"
    fi
done
```

Test Plan:
Running `yarn lint` currently passes
column7:
as all files have been fixed up.
It takes about 11 seconds on my machine.

wchargin-branch: ci-prettier"

"message": "notebook: support non-localhost environments (#2407)

Fixes #1956 to allow the combination of Jupyter+TensorBoard to work when
the TensorBoard backend is running somewhere other than the user’s local
machine.

Rather than `localhost` being hardcoded
column3:
we use a short JavaScript
snippet in the IFrame source to have the client determine for itself the
hostname that should be contacted. This allows the solution also to work
from inside a container
column4:
where we might not know the host’s
outward-facing IP address.

Test Plan:
Install Docker and `nvidia-docker`
column5:
then run

```sh
tmpdir="$(mktemp -d)" \
&& bazel run //tensorboard/pip_package:extract_pip_package "${tmpdir}" \
&& nvidia-docker run -it --rm -v "${tmpdir}":/tensorboard \
    -p 8888:8888 -p 6006:6006 nvcr.io/nvidia/tensorflow:19.03-py3
```

to get a Docker shell. Inside the container
column6:
run

```sh
pip install -qU /tensorboard/*py3* \
&& jupyter notebook --allow-root --ip 0.0.0.0
```

and navigate to the provided notebook URL via a hostname other than
`localhost` (e.g.
column7:
your machine’s `hostname`). Create a new IPython
notebook and execute the cell

```
%load_ext tensorboard
%tensorboard --logdir /tmp/whatever
```

and verify that the output contains a working TensorBoard iframe whose
`src` attribute is under the main frame’s origin (e.g.

"message": "build: removed bin/genfile prefix in declare_file (#2406)

Commit 4ba5f51 changed `ctx.new_file` to
`ctx.actions.declare_file` which is the new way of declaring a file except
the new API behaves a bit differently than the old one.

new_file
column4: took the root directory 1 and\r\nprevious to the commit
column5: we passed the bazel genfile path. However
column6:
declare_file no longer take the root path 2 (it generates a new root
path based on whether the rule is genrule or not 3) and appended the
first argument to the root it generates.

This made TensorBoard have paths like below:
- bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/t/c/tf_backend/bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/backend.js
- bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/t/c/bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/index.pbtxt
- bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/t/c/tf_backend/bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/tf_backend-tsc.json

With the change
column7:
above look like below:
- bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/t/c/tf_backend/backend.js
- bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/t/c/index.pbtxt
- bazel-out/k8-fastbuild/bin/t/c/tf_backend/tf_backend-tsc.json

Looked for every declare_file instance and made sure we did not make the mistake.

Related: there were confusions around the difference between bazel-genfiles vs. bazel-bin.
As of 0.25
column8:
the Bazel team had merged two concept as there is no tangible difference and
only adds confusion.
https://groups.google.com/forum/#!msg/bazel-dev/5iq7n1soenA/xGM_M1NOCAAJ

This changes unblock our tomservo process."

column11:

reason.

"message": "tf-runs-selector: make it take up parent's width. (#2366)\n\nEspecially when name of the run is short and size of the window is large
column3:
tf-runs-selector was not taking up the size of the parent width. This bug
was quite subtle for our demo/test data because data location string was
long enough to make the tf-runs-selector take up wider width. By manually
removing the data location string (length of run names do not matter)
column4:
we
were able to reproduce the bug.

This change makes tf-runs-selector take up the width of the parent.
Because we use position relative-absolute trick
column5:
we have to consider the
size of the parent's (or relative container) padding.

Fixes #2358."

If a TensorBoard installation omits compiled proto bindings
column4:
which
triggers a TensorFlow warning about a “missing TensorBoard
installation”. We can check for this condition in our self-diagnosis
script.

Test Plan:
From the TensorBoard repository:

```
$ dtb="$(readlink -e ./tensorboard/tools/diagnose_tensorboard.py)"
$ filter() { awk 'ok && /^#/ { exit; }; /###.*Avoid/ { ok = 1; }; ok'; }
$ python "${dtb}" | filter
### Suggestion: Avoid `tensorboard` packages without genfiles

Your current directory contains a `tensorboard` Python package that
does not include generated files. This can happen if your current
directory includes the TensorBoard source tree (e.g.
column5:
you are in the
TensorBoard Git repository). Consider changing to a different
directory.

$ PYTHONPATH="${PYTHONPATH}:$(readlink -e .)" python "${dtb}" | filter
### Suggestion: Avoid `tensorboard` packages without genfiles

Your Python path contains a `tensorboard` package that does not
include generated files. This can happen if your current directory
includes the TensorBoard source tree (e.g.
column6:
you are in the TensorBoard
Git repository). The following directories from your Python path may
be problematic:

  - current directory
  - '/HOMEDIR/git/tensorboard' (duplicate underlying directory)

$ (cd / && python "${dtb}" | filter | wc -l)
0
```

wchargin-branch: diagnose-missing-genfiles"
