"message": "Fixed incorrect runs-selector rendering (#2333)

Nature of the bug:
Sidebar tf-runs-selector is a bit trickier in term of layout: its height
depends both on number/size of the content (# of runs) and size of the
viewport (show scrollbar if it does not fit in the sidebar).

To confine the size of the tf-runs-selector w.r.t the height of its
container (whose height is not defined by content but its sibling sizes
which are computed by respective descendents)
column3: we need to make each flex\r\ncontainer `overflow: hidden`. `overflow: hidden` makes child and\r\nchild-flex-container compute height w.r.t
column4:
the flex-container with
`overflow: hidden`.

When run numbers are low
column5:
we make tf-runs-selector's height computed
w.r.t. descendent heights by not putting `height: 100%`.

Confirmed the change both on Chrome 75 and Firefox 66."

"message": "infra: upgrade three.js to r104 from r77 (#2326)

Notable changes:
- Vertex shader require related glsl code block
- other API changes in between
- WebGLRenderer.render no longer takes 4 inputs. Instead
column3:
you must set
  renderTarget manually.
- BufferAttribute.prototype.count is important and attribute.array is
  discourage in favor of setArray

Notable no changes:
- Types are not updated.
  - DefinitelyType no longer provide the latest
    typing of three in favor TypeScript in three.js repo. For the time
    being
column4:
we have decided not to pursue this as downloading the archive
    would fetch unnecessarily large file (examples dir is 300+MB).
  - TypeScript complains about mixing UMD and module when using
    newer types from three.js"

"message": "Set base URI for plugin iframe (#2329)

Plugins are developed with a relative to its package in mind. Without
setting the baseURI
column3: the iframe has base path of\r\nhttp[s]://[TBPATH]/[pathPrefix] which forces all relative paths the\r\nplugin uses require 'data/plugin/[name]/' prefix
column4:
which is unnatural.

This change sets the base URI of the plugin iframe to
http[s]://[TBPATH]/[pathPrefix]/data/plugin/[name]/."

"message": "core: stabilize and use `plugin_metadata` (#2304)

Summary:
This patch switches first-party plugins from calling `registerDashboard`
on the frontend to implementing `plugin_metadata` on the backend.

This requires reworking the “dashboard containers stamped” logic
column3: whose\r\npurpose is to introduce a Polymer data dependency from the `dom-repeat`\r\nstamping state to the dashboard rendering. Previously
column5:
but this may no longer be the case; we must
instead track exactly which containers have been stamped.

Plugin ordering was also previously defined implicitly on the frontend;
we shift that ordering to the backend.

Test Plan:

intended and in the correct order). Click through every dashboard to
verify that the proper web component is rendered. Verify that navigating
to `/#wat` displays a “no such dashboard” message

`/#scalars` shows no such message even before the plugins listing loads.
Verify that TensorBoard works properly when pointed at an empty logdir.

column7: check that all plugins were migrated (except for the core plugin
column8:

$ git grep -l registerDashboard
tensorboard/components/tf_tensorboard/registry.ts
$ comm -3 \
> <(git grep -l 'class .*TBPlugin' ':!*test.py' | sort) \
> <(git grep -l 'def frontend_metadata' ':!*test.py' | sort) \
> ;

```

column2: "message": "build: use `mirror.tensorflow.org`
column3:
now populated (#2245)

Summary:
It’s easier for TensorBoard team members to upload files to the
TensorFlow.org mirror than the Bazel mirror. Many of our files were not
mirrored
column4: and fetches from GitHub can be noticeably slow. (For instance
column5: \r\nthe Bazel 0.22.0 binary is 1.8\u20132.0 seconds from the TF mirror and 8.5\u201312\r\nseconds from GitHub.) As of this commit
column7:
and all such URLs
contain valid content.

Along the way
column8:
I swapped out the defunct numericjs source to a host that
actually still resolves.

On Travis
column9:
getting Bazel and running `bazel fetch //tensorboard/...`
typically takes about 44 seconds. Let’s see if this speeds that up.

Test Plan:
Check that Bazel URLs resolve:

```
$ git grep -Pho '(?<=")https?://mirror\.tensorflow\.org/[^"]*' |
> grep -vF '${BAZEL}' | sort | uniq |
> xargs -n 1 -P 32 -- \
> sh -c 'curl -sfL "$1" >/dev/null && echo OK || echo FAIL' unused |
> sort | uniq -c
    231 OK
```

Check that the Travis URL resolves:

```
$ BAZEL=0.22.0
$ curl -sfL "http://mirror.tensorflow.org/github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/releases/download/${BAZEL}/bazel-${BAZEL}-linux-x86_64" |
> shasum -a 256
8474ed28ed4998e2f5671ddf3a9a80ae9e484a5de3b8b70c8b654c017c65d363
```

Check that we caught ’em all:

```
$ git grep mirror.bazel | wc -l
0
```

wchargin-branch: mirror-tensorflow-org"

"message": "tools: create `diagnose_tensorboard` (#2237)

Summary:
Users often report problems that depend on environment-specific
configuration. Rather than asking them to find all this information and
enter it into an issue template manually
column3: we can ask them to run a\r\nscript and paste its output verbatim into the issue. Furthermore
column4: we can\r\ndetect and suggest fixes to common problems
column5:
such as #1907 and #2010.
The script can grow as we see fit to add new diagnoses and suggestions.

Test Plan:
The script is designed to be robust to errors in each individual
diagnosis: in the worst case
column6:
it prints a stack trace and continues to
the next one. I’ve manually tested that the main framework works in
Python 2 and 3 on Linux and in Python 3 on Windows.

Automated testing of this script is possible
column7: but would take a fair\r\nnumber of CPU cycles to run tests (setting up virtualenvs and Conda
column8:
installing and importing TensorFlow many times). Given that this script
is never a production dependency and is explicitly designed to be run in
a discussion context
column9: light testing seems reasonable.\r\n\r\nTo simulate a bad hostname
column10:
add

```python
socket.getfqdn = lambda: b"\xc9".decode("utf-8")
```

to the top of the script.

To simulate a bad `.tensorboard-info` directory and test the quoting
behavior
column11:
run

```shell
export TMPDIR="$(mktemp -d)/uh oh/" &&
mkdir -p "${TMPDIR}/.tensorboard-info" &&
chmod 000 "${TMPDIR}/.tensorboard-info" &&
python ./tensorboard/tools/diagnose_tensorboard.py
```

To cross-check the autoidentification logic:

```
$ python tensorboard/tools/diagnose_tensorboard.py |
> awk '/version / { print $NF }'
e093841ffaea564cb2410e0b430bd0c552ada208
$ git hash-object tensorboard/tools/diagnose_tensorboard.py
e093841ffaea564cb2410e0b430bd0c552ada208
$ git rev-parse HEAD:tensorboard/tools/diagnose_tensorboard.py
e093841ffaea564cb2410e0b430bd0c552ada208
$ git cat-file blob e093841ffaea564cb2410e0b430bd0c552ada208 |
> diff -u tensorboard/tools/diagnose_tensorboard.py - | wc -l
0
```

wchargin-branch: diagnose-me"

column2:
"message": "test: skip V1-only tests under TF2 behavior (#2217)

Summary:
When the `TF2_BEHAVIOR` environment variable is set
column3: TensorFlow behaves\r\nas if `tf.compat.v1.enable_v2_behavior()` were invoked. In such a case
column4:
we should not run V1-only tests.

We elect to test this by importing a private TensorFlow module rather
than reading the environment variable directly. Both are undocumented
column5: \r\nbut the module import will give us a hard failure if it is changed
column6:
while the environment variable will silently change behavior.

This fixes some Google-internal issues (see <http://cl/247294725>). It
should be a no-op externally; we do not set this environment variable.

Resolves #1996.

Test Plan:
Count the number of skipped tests before and after this change:

```
tests="$(bazel query "
    tests(rdeps(
        //tensorboard/...
column7:
set($(git grep -l run_v._only)) - //tensorboard/util:test_util.py
    ))
")" &&
bazel test ${tests} --test_output=all 2>&1 |
    sed -n -e 's/.*(skipped=\([0-9]\+\)).*/\1/p' |
    awk '{ c += $1 } END { print c }'
```

On TF 2.0
column8: it prints `166` both before and after this change; on TF 1.x
column9:
it prints `21` both before and after this change.

wchargin-branch: respect-tf2-behavior"

"message": "Refactor graph-loader to factor out graph loading\n\ntf-graph-control
column4: changed recently to work\nbetter with other graph components like tf-graph-controls. More\nspecifically
column5:
the problem happen because the tf-graph-loader was
refactored to take `selection` as the primary input to the loader and
it used run & type of graph selected by user to fetch appropriate data.
This contrasts with previous input `datasets` which took a `path` as an
input which loader used to fetch the data from. tf-graph-app and
tf-debugger-dashboard plugin were using the datasets prop to pass in
the special endpoint where the data lives.

Before describing refactor
column6:
we should define what the tf-graph-loader
should be. The loader is a UI-less functional component (renders no DOM;
uses lifecycle method and props to provide some functionality) that is
capable of fetching various informations like graph
column8:
and profile info (RunMetadata). We have recently introduce more
complexity to it.

Interestingly
column9:
all tf-graph variants (internal to Google too) does not
make use of any other data type other than the graph and there is almost
no reason to use the tf-graph-loader. The graph utilities provide an
ability to fetch and parse GraphDef
column11:
and create a
hierarchy with ease. The core values the tf-graph-loader provides are
1. error handling and 2. progress tracker (uses Polymer API). By
reusing the component
column12: one can provide some consistency there.\n\nHere
column14: we decided to put as much load+parsing into utility\nmethod and have loader specific to the dashboard while having another\nloader that is API compatible with old tf-graph-loader."

RequestManager is a thin wrapper around XMLHttpRequest and fetch.
Unfortunately
column3: for some convenience of plugin authors
column4: XMLHttpRequest\r\nversion hide away certain control over the request or response. For\r\nfetch API

we would like to keep it as true as possible to the real browser
API while giving it feature of automatic retries and request queuing.

"message": "hparams: add Python layer for hparams and metrics (#2126)

Summary:
This change introduces `HParam`
column5: \r\nwhich represent their proto counterparts in a more Python-friendly way.\r\nIt similarly includes a `Domain` class hierarchy
column6: which does not\r\ncorrespond to a specific proto message
column7:
but rather unifies the domain
variants defined on the `HParamInfo` proto.

The design is roughly as in the original sketch of #1998.

The primary benefit of this change is that having first-class domains
enables clients to reuse the domain information for both the experiment
summary and the underlying tuning algorithm. We don’t provide a method
to do this out of the box
column8: because we don\u2019t actually provide any tuners\r\nat this time
column9: but it\u2019s easy to write (e.g.) a `sample_uniform` function\r\nlike the one included in this commit. Then
column10:
sampling is as easy as

```python
    hparams = {h: sample_uniform(h.domain
column11:
rng) for h in HPARAMS}
```

It is also now more convenient to reference hparam values such that
static analysis can detect potential typos
column12: because the `HParam` objects\r\nthemselves can be declared as constants and used as keys in a dict.\r\nWriting `hparams[\"dropuot\"]` fails at runtime
column13:
but `hparams[HP_DROPUOT]`
fails at lint time.

As a pleasant bonus
column14: hparam definitions are now more compact
column15:
fitting
on one line instead of several. The demo code has net fewer lines.

Manual summary writer management is still required. A future change will
introduce a Keras callback to reduce this overhead.

Test Plan:
Some unit tests included
column16: and the demo still works.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: hparams-structured-api"

"message": "build: register `mock` dependency with Bazel (#2132)

Summary:
We’ve heretofore used the `mock` library without telling Bazel about it.
This isn’t generally a problem when `tensorflow` is installed in the
same virtualenv
column3: because `tensorflow` pulls in `mock`. But tests that\r\ndon\u2019t depend on TensorFlow have no build edge to `mock` when imported\r\ninto google3\u2019s build system
column4:
causing build failures after syncing. This
commit makes the `mock` dependency explict.

We use `mock==1.0.0` rather than the current version (2.0.0) because the
current version depends on `pbr` at runtime in a way that does not play
well with Bazel: <https://github.com/testing-cabal/mock/issues/383>
(It appears to be trying to find some globally registered `setup.cfg`
file from which to read a version identifier.) Rather than vendoring and
patching `mock`
column7: we simply depend on a\r\nsaner version of the library
column8:
which is also the version used in google3.

Existing `mock` users have been detected and fixed up:

```
$ bazel query "
>     kind(
>         py_.*rule
column11:
1)
>     )
> " \
> | awk '{ print "add deps @org_pythonhosted_mock|" $0 }' \
> | buildozer -f - \
> ;
```

Test Plan:
All notf tests now pass in a virtualenv that does not include `mock`:

```
$ virtualenv -q -p python2 ./ve
$ . ./ve/bin/activate
(ve) $ pip install 'absl-py>=0.7.0' 'numpy<2.0
column12:
>=1.14.5' boto3==1.9.86 flake8==3.5.0 futures==3.1.1 grpcio==1.6.3 yamllint==1.5.0 >/dev/null 2>&1
(ve) $ python -c 'import mock'
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<string>"
column20:
level)
ImportError: No module named mock
(ve) $ cd ~/git/tensorboard
(ve) $ bazel test //tensorboard/... --test_tag_filters=support_notf
...
INFO: Build completed successfully

"message": "program: initialize server objects exactly once (#1987)

Summary:
This resolves a piece of technical debt that was convenient but not
robust to implementation changes in Werkzeug and the Python standard
library. When searching for ports
column3: instead of calling superclass\r\ninitializers multiple times until they succeed
column4:
we create new server
objects (each with a single port) multiple times until one is
successfully initialized. Each object’s initializer chain is invoked
only once.

The mechanism provides a `with_port_scanning` factory that is agnostic
to the actual server implementation.

This commit is easier to review when ignoring whitespace changes.

Test Plan:
Spawn 11 TensorBoard processes without specifying a port; e.g.:

```
$ bazel build //tensorboard
$ for in in {1..11}; do
> ./bazel-bin/tensorboard/tensorboard --logdir /tmp/whatever &
> done; sleep 2
```

Observe that the first ten bind to successive ports
column5:
and that the last
one gives “TensorBoard could not bind to any port around 6006 (tried 10
times)”).

Then
column6:
run

```
./bazel-bin/tensorboard/tensorboard --logdir /tmp/whatever --port 6006
```

to see that you still get the “could not bind to port 6006
column8: you can use `jobs -p | xargs kill` to kill all extant jobs.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: program-single-init"

"message": "Add UMAP to embedding projector (#1901)

* Motivation for features / changes

Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection ([UMAP]) is a dimension
reduction technique that can be used for visualisation similarly to
t-SNE. I've ported the python implementation to JavaScript to add an
additional projection method to the embedding projector.

The UMAP projection technique pretty much follows the approach for the
tSNE projection. The UMAP code is grouped in its own directory for ease
of maintenance. There are two things to note about this current
implementation of UMAP in the embedding projector:

1) UMAP's SGD optimization doesn't really animate as nicely as t-SNE.
I've addresses this by choosing not to animate the steps and just track
progress through a dialog.

2) I'm currently reusing the GPU computed k-nearest neighbors - there
didn't seem to be too big of a difference between using the UMAP CPU knn
approach vs the existing GPU approach in the projector. To note
column3: the GPU\r\nknn approach uses cosine distance
column4: while the rest of UMAP's\r\nimplementation uses euclidean distance. Again
column5:
the subjective results
seem fine with this choice.

[UMAP]: https://github.com/lmcinnes/umap

* Screenshots of UI changes

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7818584/52659999-88c2c400-2eb3-11e9-9b68-eab380cbf11d.png)

* Detailed steps to verify changes work correctly (as executed by you)

Run the [tf-dev-summit-tensorboard-tutorial] demo to generate test data
with embeddings
column6:
then point TensorBoard at that log directory and
exercise the new UI functionality in the UMAP section of the projector
dashboard.

[tf-dev-summit-tensorboard-tutorial]: https://github.com/martinwicke/tf-dev-summit-tensorboard-tutorial"

"message": "scalars: document why SVGs are base64-encoded (#1971)

Summary:
This commit amends the comment added in #1601 per my subsequent
investigations. The generated SVG includes hash characters in the
`clip-path` attribute; Firefox interprets these as fragment specifiers
column3: \r\ntruncating the SVG. The prior version of the comment speculated that the\r\nissue was related to the length of the SVG
column4:
but there’s no evidence that
this is the case.

With this understanding
column5: it\u2019s easy to construct a [simple repro][1] to\r\nconfirm this behavior. In Firefox 61
column6: a data-URI describing an SVG image\r\nwith a hash character is invalid in both an `img src` and an `a href`;\r\nin Chrome pre-72
column8:
while Chrome 72 behaves the same as
Firefox. Firefox and Chrome also differ in their handling of newlines in
the non-encoded data-URI; Chrome includes the newlines (except for the
last one)
column9:
while Firefox strips them.

[1]: https://gist.github.com/wchargin/f644d584ddafb19d003d46084c0f80e5

Test Plan:
No functional change. Inspect the above-linked gist to confirm behavior.

wchargin-branch: svg-url-truncation-comment"

"message": "profile: fix loading progress behavior (#1945)

Summary:
The profile dashboard had an existing bug that was revealed by #1914:
the loading progress bar never actually finishes. Prior to #1914
column3:
you
could actually see the loading bar if you made your window narrow
enough:
![Screenshot of a zombie progress bar](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/53674700-95317580-3c44-11e9-924f-82f6dc8d5f18.png)

This was because the prior version of the dashboard rendered the main
tool irrespective of whether the data had actually finished loading. As
of #1914
column4: the \u201cloading\u201d and \u201cactive\u201d states are mutually exclusive
column5:
so
instead of just having a zombie progress bar we actually block the view.

The cause of the bug is a promise that never resolves. (The executor
provided to the `Promise` constructor’s return value is ignored; only
the `resolve` and `reject` callbacks can fulfill a promise.)

This was not caught while testing #1914 because it cannot be reproduced
with the demo data present at that commit; with that more complete set
of data
column6: there are other code paths that clobber the progress value to\r\n100% (which is really a separate issue
column8:
such as `_maybeUpdateData`.

Test Plan:
Regenerate profile plugin demo data if you haven’t done so since #1942
column9:
then launch TensorBoard:

```
$ rm -rf /tmp/profile_demo/
$ bazel run //tensorboard/plugins/profile:profile_demo
$ bazel run //tensorboard -- --logdir /tmp/profile_demo
```

The trace viewer should be displayed (prior to this commit

"message": "profile: disable dashboard inside Colab (#1914)

Summary:
The profile dashboard now shows a “disabled” message on the frontend
when we detect that we’re running in a Colab notebook. See #1913.

This commit does _not_ cause the profile dashboard to be marked inactive
by the main TensorBoard UI. We might want to do that
column4: the backend is responsible for telling the\r\nfrontend which plugins are active
column5: and the backend can\u2019t know whether\r\nwe\u2019re running in Colab. As a quick hack
column6: we could add special-case logic\r\nin `tf-tensorboard.html` to check for the profile plugin specifically.\r\nAs a longer-term solution
column7: we could let the `tf_tensorboard.Dashboard`\r\ninterface specify an `isActive` callback
column8:
defaulting to `() => true`.

![Screenshot of the “Profiling isn’t yet supported in Colab” message][s]

[s]: https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/53541886-b83b1880-3ad0-11e9-9501-299f5e671d7a.png

The implementation includes a small refactor to the profile dashboard to
make it easier to introduce a new state.

Test Plan:
Evaluate `!!(window.TENSORBOARD_ENV || {}).IN_COLAB` in both standalone
TensorBoard and Colab `%tensorboard`
column9:
and note that each evaluates to
the appropriate boolean.

Run TensorBoard locally with the profile plugin’s demo data
column10: and note\r\nthat its behavior is unchanged. To trigger the loading state
column13: \r\nthen change the selected tool. To trigger the \u201cno data\u201d state
column14:
relaunch
TensorBoard pointing at a different log directory.

Then
column15: test the Colab behavior by either pointing TensorBoard at a log\r\ndirectory that does not contain profile data
column16:
then executing

```js
window.TENSORBOARD_ENV = window.TENSORBOARD_ENV || {};
window.TENSORBOARD_ENV["IN_COLAB"] = true;
```

in the main TensorBoard pane before switching to the inactive profile
dashboard. Note that this is the same setup JavaScript as is injected
into the Colab output frame by `notebook.py`.

wchargin-branch: profile-disable-colab"

"message": "build: upgrade to Bazel 0.22
column3:
rules_closure HEAD (#1904)

Summary:
Fixes #1903. Googlers are now locked to Bazel 0.23
column4: which breaks\r\n`rules_closure` unless we pull in HEAD (they\u2019ve not yet had a release).\r\nConversely
column6: so our CI\r\nneeds to be upgraded to match; Bazel 0.22 is the minimum working\r\nversion. Also
column7: `rules_closure` had a breaking change in a package\r\ncalled `private` whose default visibility is `public`
column8:
so our
`clutz.bzl` needs to be updated to work around that.

Test Plan:
Running `bazel build //tensorboard/... && bazel test //tensorboard/...`
passes on Bazel versions 0.22.0 and 0.23.0
column9:
failing on version 0.21.0.

Verified that the shasum matches the properly signed Bazel 0.22 binary:

```
$ gpg --verify ./bazel-0.22.0-linux-x86_64{.sig
column10:
}
gpg: Signature made Mon 28 Jan 2019 05:30:32 AM PST
gpg:                using RSA key 71A1D0EFCFEB6281FD0437C93D5919B448457EE0
gpg: Good signature from "Bazel Developer (Bazel APT repository key) <bazel-dev@googlegroups.com>" [full]
$ shasum -a 256 --check ./bazel-0.22.0-linux-x86_64.sha256
bazel-0.22.0-linux-x86_64: OK
$ shasum -a 256 ./bazel-0.22.0-linux-x86_64
8474ed28ed4998e2f5671ddf3a9a80ae9e484a5de3b8b70c8b654c017c65d363  ./bazel-0.22.0-linux-x86_64
```

wchargin-branch: bazel-0.23"

column2: "message": "server: when no port is specified
column3:

Summary:
This patch teaches TensorBoard about `--port=default` (which is the new
default value for `--port`). If `--port=default` is specified
column4: \r\nTensorBoard will attempt to bind to port 6006
column5: just as prior to this\r\npatch. If this fails
column6: TensorBoard will try to bind incrementally to\r\nports 6007
column9: giving up after 10 attempts.\r\n\r\nIf an explicit port is specified
column10:
TensorBoard will not try to search for
other ports; it will fail (as before) if it cannot bind. This is the
only way in which `--port=default` and `--port=6006` differ.

This patch also changes the behavior of one edge case
column11: at least on\r\nLinux. Prior to this patch
column12: explicit port numbers were interpreted\r\nmodulo 65536 (TCP ports are u16s)
column13:
so `--port=71542` and `--port=6006`
had the same behavior. It is now an error on all platforms to specify a
port that does not fit in a u16.

Resolves #1848.

column2: "message": "main: handle SIGTERM
column4: TensorBoard does not change the default signal dispositions\r\nfor any signal handlers
column5: so if killed by SIGTERM or SIGQUIT it will exit\r\nwithout running its `atexit` handlers
column6: such as the one registered by the\r\nDB import mode. As of this commit
column7: we handle SIGTERM by exiting\r\ngracefully. We leave SIGQUIT at the default disposition (temporary files\r\nwill not be cleaned up)
column8:
in accordance with the GNU libc guidelines:
<https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Termination-Signals.html#index-SIGQUIT>

The implementation is not perfect. Ideally
column9: we would perform our\r\ngraceful cleanup and then kill ourselves with the same signal to\r\nproperly inform our parent of the source of the exit: for details
column10:
see
<https://www.cons.org/cracauer/sigint.html>. But `atexit` doesn’t
provide a function like “please run all registered handlers now but
don’t actually quit”; we might be able to implement this in Python 2.7
using `sys.exitfunc`
column11: but that\u2019s deprecated in Python 2.7 and removed in\r\nPython 3. If we want to do this right
column12: we could implement our own\r\nversion of `atexit` (which would not be hard: the module is tiny). For\r\nnow
column13:
I’m comfortable with submitting this mostly-correct patch.

Supersedes part of #1795.

Test Plan:
Run `bazel build //tensorboard` and add the built binary to your PATH.
Then
column15: wait for it to\r\nprint the \u201cserving\u201d message
column16: and send SIGTERM via `kill(1)`. Note that\r\nTensorBoard prints a message and exits cleanly
column17:
and that “`after`”
is printed to the console.

Patch `program.py` to add a pre-existing signal handler and `atexit`
cleanup from the top of `main`:

```diff
diff --git a/tensorboard/program.py b/tensorboard/program.py
index da59b4d1..c07cb855 100644
--- a/tensorboard/program.py
+++ b/tensorboard/program.py
@@ -201
column20: frame):\r\n+      print(\"Handling some signals...\")\r\n+    assert signal.signal(signal.SIGTERM
column21:
fake_handler) == signal.SIG_DFL
+    def fake_cleanup():
+      print("Cleaning everything up...")
+    import atexit
+    atexit.register(fake_cleanup)
+
     self._install_signal_handler(signal.SIGTERM
column22: \"SIGTERM\")\r\n     if self.flags.inspect:\r\n       logger.info('Not bringing up TensorBoard
column25:
and note that the signal handler and
`atexit` handler are both executed prior to cleanup:

```
$ tensorboard --logdir whatever && echo after
TensorBoard 1.13.0a0 at <hostname> (Press CTRL+C to quit)
TensorBoard caught SIGTERM; exiting...
Handling some signals...
Cleaning everything up...
after
```

Ideally
column26:
`after` should _not_ be printed; that it is is a consequence of
the fact that we don’t properly propagate the WIFSIGNALED flag as
described above.

wchargin-branch: handle-signals"

column2: "message": "build: temporarily pin working tf-nightly version
column3:
and fix the build (#1758)

Summary:
This commit\* solves three problems.

First
column4: the current-latest `tf-nightly` package is buggy (it does not\r\nprovide a `tf.compat.v1` module)
column5:
so we pin an old version until a new
version with <https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/24867> is
released. That’s easy.

Second
column6: the Travis build was hitting a numpy error that looks like\r\n<https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/12736>. We started hitting this\r\nnow because numpy 1.16.0 was released
column7:
and something in the Travis
environment was causing a failure. The fix for this (included in this
commit) is to explicitly uninstall Travis’s preinstalled `numpy`.

Third
column8: the Travis build was hitting a GCC error
column9: wherein Bazel was\r\ninvoking `gcc` with the `-fcolor-diagnostics` argument
column10: which Trusty GCC\r\ndoes not support. This one is puzzling
column11: as the functionality that Bazel\r\nuses to test whether this argument is supported has not changed in a\r\nwhile. It\u2019s possible to reproduce the failure
column12:
but the circumstances
under which I could reproduce it are bizarre. Here is a full repro
script to be run on a fresh Ubuntu Trusty VM:

https://gist.github.com/wchargin/15ce5e31ab0976edca33eb4c0e6c36dc

Clearing Travis caches for `master` and this pull request through the
Travis UI does not fix the problem
column13: but running `bazel clean --expunge`\r\ndoes. I added that into the `.travis.yml` file
column14: which caused builds to\r\nsucceed even after I removed the `--expunge` line (i.e.
column15:
the cache only
needed to be expunged once). Suffice it to say that we have no idea
what’s happening here and are simply hoping that we’ve lucked out into
not having to deal with it again.

Test Plan:
Running bazel run `//tensorboard/pip_package:build_pip_package` includes
a smoke test that fails before this change and passes after it. This
addresses the first problem listed above. The other two problems can
only be tested by running on Travis.

wchargin-branch: pin-tf-nightly"

workspace to accommodate.

column5:
please use the latter (https://docs.bazel.build/versions/master/skylark/lib/native.html#repository_name). You can temporarily allow the old name by using --incompatible_package_name_is_a_function=false

column6:

"message": "build: fix Bazel 0.20.0 compatibility issues (#1661)

Summary:
Bazel 0.20.0 introduced some incompatible changes that broke both our
code and our dependencies. Our dependencies also introduced some
incompatible changes of their own. This commit upgrades our dependencies
and fixes up our code to accommodate them.

An upgrade to transitive dependency `rules_go` introduces a dependency
on the `@bazel_tools//tools/build_defs/cc:action_names.bzl` builtin
target. This target was only introduced in Bazel 0.16.0
column3: so as a\r\nconsequence our workspace is no longer compatible with earlier versions\r\nof Bazel. In practice
column4:
we must use at least version 0.16.1 to fix a
regression in 0.16.0: <https://github.com/bazelbuild/bazel/issues/5726>.

Unfortunately
column5: Bazel 0.16.0 also introduced a regression that prevents\r\nus from using the `--distinct_host_configuration=false` option; this has\r\nnot been fixed as of Bazel 0.20.0. As a result
column6:
parts of our build will
now be twice as slow.

The new `urllib3` dependency is due to a transitive Selenium upgrade.

This commit shifts our Bazel version window from [0.13.0
column8:
0.20.0].

Test Plan:
Running `bazel test //tensorboard/...` passes in Python 2 and 3 in Bazel
versions 0.16.1 and 0.20.0 (latest at time of writing)
column9:
with
the `.bazelrc` file set up as on Travis:

```sh
>~/.bazelrc
echo "startup --output_base=${HOME}/.bazel-output-base" >>~/.bazelrc
echo "startup --host_jvm_args=-Xms500m" >>~/.bazelrc
echo "startup --host_jvm_args=-Xmx500m" >>~/.bazelrc
echo "startup --host_jvm_args=-XX:-UseParallelGC" >>~/.bazelrc
echo "build --local_resources=400

column2: "message": "tf_web_library: serve webfiles on IPv4
column3:
not IPv6 (#1619)

Summary:
Our Travis environment does not support IPv6. If we try to spin up a
webfiles server on Travis with the current config
column4:
we see an error:

    java.net.SocketException: Protocol family unavailable
            at java.net.PlainSocketImpl.socketBind(Native Method)
            at java.net.AbstractPlainSocketImpl.bind(AbstractPlainSocketImpl.java:387)
            at java.net.ServerSocket.bind(ServerSocket.java:375)
            at java.net.ServerSocket.<init>(ServerSocket.java:237)
            at javax.net.DefaultServerSocketFactory.createServerSocket(ServerSocketFactory.java:231)
            at io.bazel.rules.closure.webfiles.server.NetworkUtils.createServerSocket(NetworkUtils.java:51)
            at io.bazel.rules.closure.webfiles.server.WebfilesServer.runForever(WebfilesServer.java:136)
            at io.bazel.rules.closure.webfiles.server.WebfilesServer.run(WebfilesServer.java:124)
            at io.bazel.rules.closure.webfiles.server.WebfilesServer.main(WebfilesServer.java:75)

We want to be able to run webfiles servers from Travis for testing
purposes
column5:
so this commit changes the `tf_web_library` configuration to
bind to IPv4-compatible `localhost` instead of IPv6 `[::]`.

This does not affect the main TensorBoard target
column6:
which is a `py_binary`
and has a completely separate pipeline.

Test Plan:
To verify that this has the desired effect
column7:
run

    $ bazel run //tensorboard/components/vz_sorting/test

before and after this change
column8: and look for the \u201cListening on:\u201d line.\r\nBefore this change
column10:
it says `http://localhost:6006/`. Either URL actually
works both before and after this change.

To verify that this fixes Travis
column12: which works only with this change.\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: tf_web_library-ipv4"

"message": "Fix the issue where minimap content gets clipped (#1600)

Bug: #1574

Cause: the graph in the bug contains no main graph node and all nodes
are auxiliary nodes. As a result
column3:
the drawn nodes are shifted right by
predefined amount for visuals.

When measuring the bounding box of the scene to draw the minimap
column4: \r\nwe were using SVGGraphicsElement.getBBox which returned a tight BBox\r\nwithout concerning any whitespace. As a result
column5: although we wanted the\r\nwidth from the origin to right edge of the right most node
column6: we were omitting\r\nthe origin to left most edge
column7: resulting in clipped content in the minimap.\r\n\r\nFix: measure the scene width from origin to the right edge of the content."

"message": "Export current line chart as SVG (#1446)

Motivation: TB should give ability to save line chart as high quality
SVG.
Right solution: Modify Plottable to draw in one SVG with grouping
instead of multiple SVG fragments.
Problem: SVG creation is scattered and it may require a lot more effort
to understand design choice around these fragments (may require dynamic
creation of clipPath for masking a part of a figure)
Current solution: Parse the Plottable drawn DOM and generate one SVG out
of the DOM snapshot
Shortcomings:
- X-axis label may take up larger than required space
- There are no labels to each line (should give an option when
  exporting)"

column2: "message": "Turn off dependency pruning (#1478)\n\nES6 modules are incorrectly considered moochers right now. Once this is fixed in the compiler the vz-example-viewer file will be moved after its use. Nothing imports it directly
column3: so the compiler thinks its can move it later (it will put moochers before explicit entry points).\r\n\r\nA moocher is something that is not importable
column4: e.g. has no `goog.provide` or `goog.module` statements and is not an ES6 module and thus can never be `goog.require`d or `import`d. Moochers with `setMoocherDropping(false)` are considered entry points (why else would they be input?)."

simply hides the slot.
https://github.com/Polymer/polymer/blob/1.x/src/lib/template/dom-if.html#L127

"message": "REFACTOR: mv tooltip container out of scroll area (#1406)

Chart tooltip (or all popovers) should render at the body level in order
to prevent clipping from a scrollable area. To be more specific
column3: even\r\nposition:fixed can get contained inside a region if it is within a\r\nscrollable region. As a remedy
column4:

body.

To achieve this in a component structure
column5: there are two competing goals:\r\n1. intuitive component structure (tooltip is a subcomponent chart)\r\n2. DOM-wise
column6:
tooltip should not be nested in chart but should be at body
   level.
Libraries like React allows such pattern via "tunneling". By manually creating
an element in the body
column7: we emulated the behavior.\r\n\r\nIn this commit
column8:

column2: "message": "Disable Pylint (#1207)\n\nPylint is a nice tool
column3:
but hasn't been that helpful for TensorBoard.

- See https://travis-ci.org/tensorflow/tensorboard/jobs/376968526 where it
  takes more than two minutes to run
column4:
representing >35% of Travis CI latency.

- We typically have to wait until the very end of a Travis run before we get
  Pylint results
column5: because we run it in a really hackish way. This is also\r\n  likely the cause of its poor performance and has resulted in surprising\r\n  breakages
column6:
such as the one we encountered in #1206.

- Pylint has a very different point of view on style / best practices compared
  with Google and IntelliJ.

- TensorBoard doesn't work with the latest version of Pylint.

IntelliJ is good enough
column7: in my personal opinion. I'd be open to keeping Pylint\r\nif it gave quick feedback as part of the normal Bazel build process. I looked\r\ninto the difficulty of doing that and it was discouraging."

"message": "Make pr_curves_demo manually implement clip (#1132)\n\nTensorFlow commits https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/083cf6b91a380641933457a4301f9b1efa13af92 and https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/commit/daf0b206b5afde875a19270136ad22d9d2bb138c have made their way into `tf-nightly` build 254. The commits modified the behavior of the `tf.clip_by_value` op in an attempt to resolve https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/7225 in a way that minimizes memory usage by taking different pathways of logic based on characteristics of the system running TensorFlow. Unfortunately
column3: our python 2 and python 3 setups on travis differ along those characteristics
column4: causing the `tf-nightly` build to break `:pr_curves_test` (which relies on the demo to generate test data) for python 2 only.\r\n\r\nThis PR fixes the test by removing usages of `tf.clip_by_value` from the demo and instead uses `tf.maximum(minValue
column6: value))`. The most fulfilling solution for this bug would be to resolve the mismatch in behavior of `tf.clip_by_value` on the TensorFlow side. However
column7: this PR unblocks development of TensorBoard immediately."

column2: "message": "Reload runs with multiple (1 by default - per status quo) threads (#1104)\n\nPreviously
column3: runs would reload one after another in TensorBoard. This sometimes resulted in confusing behavior. A user must wait for one run to complete before subsequent ones do. If one run takes a particularly long time to reload
column4: the user could be prevented from seeing desired runs. Or just be confused about how the run never loads.\r\n\r\nFor instance
column5: when loading the logs directory outputted by mnist_with_summaries.py on my\r\nlaptop
column6: the `eval` run takes much less time than the `train` run to reload (4s vs 25s). However
column7:
I
must wait the full 25s for any eval data to show up because TensorBoard loads the `train` run
first.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4221553/38326883-c6119da4-37fb-11e8-84c5-fc8c6a556625.png)

By reloading accumulators with 2 threads
column9:
so I can see data for
the quickly reloaded `eval` run in about 3 seconds.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4221553/38326955-e91e362c-37fb-11e8-9928-7fd1234cfadf.png)

This change solves that problem by making TensorBoard reload runs using a couple of threads (customizable by the user). We default to 1 to avoid surprising perhaps some users whose 
performance might suffer when running with multiple threads.

Ultimately
column10: migrating to a SQL-backed system does away with reading data sequentially from events files entirely
column11: which would resolve the much more substantial problem of how we can avoid loading\r\ndata in a sequence over time."

column2: "message": "Generalize logic for computing series nodes (#1020)\n\nPreviously
column3: graph explorer logic made series nodes based on the last few digits of node names. This change generalizes that behavior to make series nodes based on any consecutive indices found within the names of nodes. This change enables an internal team seeking to generalize the graph explorer to move forward. Thank you to Chen Li for the generalization method.\r\n\r\nThe new logic for series collapsing may entail changes to existing behavior as well as performance. Therefore
column4: we guard this behavior with a boolean hierarchy param called `useGeneralizedSeriesPatterns`. The graph loader component is now able to specify that boolean within its `overridingHierarchyParams` property."

"message": "Always reload multiplexer on thread. (#1105)\n\nPreviously
column3: when the reload_interval flag was set to 0
column4: TensorBoard\r\nwould reload the multiplexer once at the beginning of TensorBoard\r\nstartup on the main thread. Now
column5: TensorBoard performs that reload on a\r\nseparate daemon thread. As comments note
column6:
this behavior prevents joining
threads that start while TensorBoard is reloading from blocking
TensorBoard from quitting after the user hits Ctrl + C.

This PR introduces a change in behavior. When the user starts a
TensorBoard with reload_interval set to 0 (no continuous reloading)
column7: \r\nTensorBoard server starts up before all data is read from disk.\r\nPreviously
column8:
TensorBoard would read all events files (reload
multiplexers) before starting its server. A few tests were modified
accordingly.

Test Plan:

Start TensorBoard pointed at logs from mnist_with_summaries.py with the
reload interval set to 0. Verify that TensorBoard starts up successfully
and that the multiplexer only reloads once in the beginning.

Start TensorBoard with the reload interval set to 5 seconds. Verify that
TensorBoard starts up successfully and that the multiplexer continuously
reloads with a 5-second interval in between reloads.

Start TensorBoard with the reload interval set to -1. Verify that
TensorBoard never performs a reload."

column2: "message": "Ignore .DS_Store files (#1112)"
"message": "Find runs by glob-ing levels of subdirectories (#1087)\n\nPreviously
column3:
TensorBoard found runs within the log directory by
performing a `tf.gfile.Walk` across directories. That turned out to be
very slow for users with expansive log directories (with many
subdirectories and files) because `tf.gfile.Walk` makes many calls at
the python level to C++ logic for reading data from disk (as opposed to
performing much of that logic directly at the C++ level). Disk reads can
be very costly for certain (such as remote and distributed) file systems.

We find runs (subdirectories) much more quickly by iteratively glob-ing
deeper and deeper directory levels. For a certain internal user
column4:
this
reduced the time it took to find all runs from 20 minutes to 20 seconds.

We already have tests that check whether the multiplexer correctly finds
subdirectories that are runs
column5: so this pull request adds no further\r\ntests. We preserve that correctness and just speed up that logic. This\r\nchange may result in us finding runs in different orders
column6:
but that is
fine - TensorBoard documents no guarantees in terms of the order in
which runs are discovered.

Thank you to @nfelt for this idea and the fruitful brainstorming
session."

"message": "Store colormaps in python (#1085)\n\nPreviously
column3:
the beholder plugin read a colormaps.npy file from disk to
obtain matplotlib color mappings used for visualization. This introduced
complexity. Reading the file involved different APIs for internal and
external users. Furthermore
column4:
the colormaps.npy file was being read
during module import time. Both of these issues prevented TensorBoard
from starting up internally.

@nfelt proposed this solution that does away with that complexity. We
store the color maps in python. The color maps are stored as immutable
numpy arrays.

All color maps seem to work after this change."

column2:
"message": "Count regular edges while picking metaedge. (#1082)

The logic for patching inputs to function nodes performs a scan across
metaedges (edges that encapsulate potentially numerous base edges) in
order to determine the correct metaedge to patch. Previously
column3:
this logic
had not taken into consideration how a metaedge could represent several
regular edges. This was problematic since the index pertained to the
collective number of regular edges (not metaedges).

This had caused an internal user's graph to fail to render. The graph
contained an edge into a series node within a function. The series node
caused several regular edges to be collapsed into one metaedge.

This change has been tested with that graph as well as other graphs that
make use of TensorFlow functions. The graph WAI."

"message": " Make Beholder fail gracefully on non-writable config file (#1070)\n\nThis change makes Beholder fail gracefully if it can't write a config file.  Previously the plugin attempted to write a default config file to the log directory as early as `__init__()`
column3: so any error on writing the file (e.g. a permissions error on a read-only directory) would kill TensorBoard.\r\n\r\nWith this change
column4: Beholder only attempts to write a config file if it's already determined that it should be active (i.e. if the `Beholder` class in the model code is writing data).  This ensures that users who aren't intending to use Beholder won't have their log directories written to at all
column5: which avoids leaving \"junk\" in those directories and ensures that they won't be impacted by missing write permissions.\r\n\r\nAs a further convenience
column6: we also rewire the Beholder frontend controls to accept a disabled parameter and make the backend indicate that the controls should be disabled when it's unable to write out the config file
column7: which should help reduce user confusion as to why the controls wouldn't be working in a case like this."

column2: "message": "Reimplement video writing support in Beholder (#1046)\n\nThis change reimplements video writing in Beholder.  The new API consists of a VideoWriter class that takes a list of VideoOutput types.  When sending a frame to VideoWriter
column3: it handles cascading through the list of outputs until it finds one that works
column4: as well as re-initializing an output if the frame size changes
column5: which lets us simplify logic in Beholder itself.\r\n\r\nRight now there are only two VideoOutputs implemented.  The primary one is FFmpegVideoOutput which uses a subprocess call to FFmpeg and currently is hardcoded to generate lossless-VP9-encoded video wrapped in a .webm container at 15 FPS.  As a fallback that should work in just about any scenario
column6: PNGVideoOutput writes individual frames as PNG files to disk using TensorFlow's own `encode_png()` op."

"message": "Fix and enhance tooltip logic in vz-bar-chart.ts (#1040)

This fixes the build breakage due to a few TypeScript compilation errors in the newly introduced vz-bar-chart.ts from PR #1037.  One was a typo and the other was a typing issue with the createTooltipHeaders() function not having type information its tooltipColumns parameter necessary to know it has a .title property.

There were a few other fixes necessary to get the tooltips fully working:
- moved it inside BarChart (where it probably belongs more anyway) so the selection can use `this.tooltip` since it wasn't finding `#tooltip-table-header-row` from the old location
- added the insertion of an initial empty header (for the column that contains the swatches of color to identify different data series).
- as a bonus
column3: I added in the \"closest\" highlighting behavior from the scalars tooltip chart so that the white border on the colored swatch is only added for the currently hovered bar\r\n\r\nJust as an aside
column4: IMO we might want to make the tooltip not be positioned dynamically based on the hovered bar's position
column5: since that means unlike with the scalars tooltip chart
column6: when you move the cursor across the chart the tooltip jumps around
column7: so it's harder to scan for changes in the numeric values.  That would make it more of a \"chart tooltip\" and less of a \"bar tooltip\".\r\n\r\nFinally
column8: I renamed \"points\" to \"bars\" everywhere in the drawTooltips() logic since they really are Bar objects and this was confusing - see the comment I reworded to explain that we are really passing in a `{key: String
column9: value: Bar}` key-value pair into TooltipColumn.evaluate() and just telling TypeScript that it's a Point because that's what the signature requires."

"message": "Change histogram SQL query to use linspaced sampling (#1022)\n\nThis replaces the randomized downsampling used in the histograms plugin SQL query with a systematic linear sampling strategy
column3: based on dividing the range into k - 1 equal-sized intervals and then returning the lowest steps at or above the k interval boundaries.  This produces cleaner and more readily understandable/predictable charts
column4: where we now get the nice property that (at least when steps are contiguous) any two adjacent histogram curves will be separated by the same step delta +/- 1 so the actual rate of change is easier to discern.  As a bonus
column5: the new results also always include the lowest and highest steps in the series."

"message": "Fix attempt in _serve_runs() to .sort a py3 dict_keys (#1004)

Fixes #1003.  Also simplifies the code a bit overall; there's no need to pre-cache the first event times in a dict because the key function passed to sort will only be called once per element anyway (i.e. it will cache it internally).  At that point I think it's cleaner to just inline the key function to where it's used.

I also extended the testing of the run ordering to cover the no-started-timestamp cases."

"message": "Disable event file loading when --db is passed (#1001)\n\nThis disables event file loading when --db is passed.  It does this by making a negative value for --reload_interval have the effect of disabling all the Multiplexer run-adding and reloading logic (even the initial load that you get by passing 0)
column3: and then conditionally setting reload_interval to -1 if we got a DB.\r\n\r\nCurrently
column4: even when you pass --db and do not pass --logdir
column5: we still try to load event files
column6: which could lead to inconsistent state across the DB-enabled and not-yet-DB-enabled plugins.  It's especially bad if you don't pass --logdir at all
column7: since that gets interpreted as the empty directory i.e. the current directory
column8: and so we can easily waste a lot of cycles on the Reloader thread searching through the entire current directory tree looking for tfevents files."

column2: "message": "Fix DB-based is_active() methods to not always return True (#1000)\n\nApplying `bool()` to a `sqlite3.Cursor` always returns `True` - while the Cursor can be used like an iterable
column3: it doesn't define `__len__()` (since the result set size isn't necessarily known until you start iterating over it) or `__nonzero__()` and hence is Truthy always
column4: even when the result set is empty.\r\n\r\nThe fix for this is just to convert it to a list first."

"message": "Add /data/environment route (#961)

This new `/data/environment` route (of the core plugin) responds with
base properties relevant to the frontend upon startup of TensorBoard.

These properties include:
* the window title
* the location of data - either a path to a log directory or a database
URI. This new route will enable the frontend to display the data
location on the bottom left when TensorBoard runs in database mode
(once the frontend makes use of this backend change in a different PR):

"message": "Let user know which tags are missing per run (#967)

Some early users of margin plots noticed a bug. If data associated with
a tag for any run was missing
column3: an error message appeared noting that\r\ndata was missing for that tag. The error message gave no indication of\r\nwhich runs were missing information. Sometimes
column5:
some run might not log a certain scalar value.

This change now offers users a more nuanced message when margin plot
logic is missing information for certain tags within a run. The message
notes specific runs and then lists the specific tags without data for
those runs. The message is placed under a collapsible so that the user
can chose to not see the message if the behavior is intended. Messages
are only shown if a run is missing data for some but not all tags."

column2: "message": "Add 1.6.0 relnotes to RELEASE.md (#964)"
"message": "Bump VERSION at HEAD to 1.7.0a0 (#960)\n\nI propose that going forward we should maintain our version at HEAD as +1 minor release ahead of our most recent release
column3: i.e. as soon as we release the first release or release candidate for 1.N then we should move head up to 1.(N+1).0a0.  Or concretely
column4: in this case since we've release 1.6.0-rc0 we should be at 1.7.0a0 at HEAD.\r\n\r\nThis is because logically
column5: at HEAD we may already have new features that aren't going to be in 1.6.x and will be instead only incorporated into 1.7.0.  So HEAD is really an \"alpha prerelease\" for 1.7.0
column6: not for 1.6.0.\r\n\r\nOnce we've bumped the version and have at least one 1.(N+1).0a<date> nightly release on PyPI
column7: but no earlier than the TensorFlow release 1.N.0-rc0 release
column8: we would send a PR to TensorFlow updating their tb-nightly dep to >= 1.(N+1).0a0 < 1.(N+2).0a0.  This would ensure that as soon as tf-nightly will start to diverge past the TF 1.N branch
column9: tb-nightly is appropriately pinned to 1.(N+1).\r\n\r\n(Note that at that point it would be decoupled from the PRs we send to their release branches to update the regular tensorboard dep.)"

For instance

"message": "Include iron-flex styles within dashboard styles (#904)

The classes/iron-flex-layout.html file is deprecated.
Previously
column3:
this caused line charts within TensorBoard run in Google to
stack atop each other - the file contained CSS necessary for flex
postioning.

We now instead include the recommended file
iron-flex-layout/iron-flex-layout-classes.html in order to import those
necessary flex styles. This causes the line charts to lie next to each
other (flex-positioned) as expected.

We still can't drop classes/iron-flex-layout.html from BUILD
dependencies
column5: because TensorBoard's version of the paper-styles\r\ncomponent still imports that file. We may want to consider upgrading the\r\nversion of paper-styles."

column2: "message": "Make smoothing not affect margin charts (#903)\n\nPreviously
column3: smoothing would affect the main line within margin charts
column4:
but not the lower and upper bounds. That confused the user.

Hence
column5:
we avoid making smoothing affect margin charts. The alternative
of smoothing the bounds in addition to the main line raises statistical
concerns about how valid the smoothing is when applied to bounds. The
first team that might find this feature valuable also noted that just
making margin charts unsmoothed would likely work nicely."

"message": "[Debugger Plugin]: Continue to condition & misc. improvements (#897)

* [Debugger Plugin]: Continue to condition & misc. improvements

Main new feature:
* Ability to continue to a given condition for any of the watched
  tensors. This is presented as a new section in the pop-up dialog
  of the "Continue..." button
column3:
while the existing continue n times
  of Session.run is put into the first section of the dialog.
* The new continue-to momde supports the following modes:
  * Contains inf or nan
  * Contains inf
  * Contains nan
  * Max > or < ref value
  * Min > or < ref value
  * Range (Max - Min) > or < ref value
  * Mean > or < ref value
  * Stddev > or < ref value
* The pop-up dialog for Continue... is refactored into its own
  Polymer component: tf-debugger-continue-to-dialog.html

Misc. improvements:
* Fix a bug wherein continue across multiple Session.run keys does
  not render graph for new run key.
* Move the toast from the bottom left to the bottom center. This
  prevents the toast from obscuring the Step and Continue... buttons."

column5:
the graph
would not render within the minimap.

Surprisingly
column7:
in this case
`tf-debugger-initial-dialog`. That dialog is only rendered by the
debugger plugin - the debugger dashboard is not even constructed when

I perused the vulcanized HTML and JS

and no issues seem to stand out
there.

making the selector more specific and apply only to the component. I
will later investigate what is causing a CSS specification within the

minimap."

"message": "[Debugger Plugin]: Add Source Code View (#848)

Main feature:
* Viewing the Python source code files involved in the creation of nodes
  of the graph. (Only files outside the TensorFlow library are
  included.)
* Lines of the code files are annotated with collapsible views of the
  nodes whose creation stacks involve the lines.
* Clicking the node names in the Source Code View will focus on the
  corresponding node in the Node List
column3:
the Graph View and the Tensor
  Value Overview.
* Clicking the "forward" icon button next to the node name in the
  Source Code View will cause the debugger to continue to the node and
  display any tensor values in the Tensor Value Overview.
* Clicking the "stack" icon button right next to the node name will
  open a sticky dialog that shows the full stack trace of the node's
  creation. The stack trace contains clickable links that enables
  the user to navigate to various frames of the stack
column4:
potentially
  located in different source files.

Front end tested manually. Backend PyUnit tests added."

"message": "Projector: Semi-supervised t-SNE (#811)

Add supervise metadata column selection and unlabeled class input in
data-panel
column3:
and supervise factor in t-SNE projections-panel. Use
available labels to modify t-SNE input similarities so that same-label
samples have amplified attraction and different-label samples have
attenuated attraction to a degree specified by the supervise factor (0
no supervision
column4: 100 full supervision). Metadata edits immediately\r\nupdate the labels used by t-SNE
column5: which effectively provides interactive\r\nsupervision by being able to label a continuous semi-supervised t-SNE\r\nembedding process."

"message": "Let custom scalars dashboard plot margin charts (#818)

We let the user plot both margin charts as well as (the pre-existing)
multi-line charts within the custom scalars dashboard. Margin charts are
configured with a list of series. Each series takes 3 tag strings
(value
column4:
and upper) that correspond to scalar summaries (logged as
usual via `tf.summary.scalar` or via TensorBoard's summary module).

Those 3 tag strings are used to populate the value
column6:
and
upper bounds of margins. See changes to the Layout proto for details.

We display error messages if tags cannot be found."

column2: "message": "Correct logic for finding if a node is in bounds (#837)\n\nPreviously
column3:
logic for determining whether a node was out of bounds in
the graph did not take into account how the top-left of the graph might
not match the top-left of the viewport.

Now
column4: we correct that and furthermore pan to a node if it is even\r\npartially out of view."

column3: the debugger dashboard would not pan to a node if it had\r\nalready been selected. Now

column2: "message": "Include entire :lib target in pip package (#827)\n\nThis fixes our pip package's bundled library (what you get from `import tensorboard`) so that it actually includes the full `:lib` target rather than just `:summary`.  Right now
column4: except that `:lib` also includes the lazy-loading functionality that makes `import tensorboard as tb` work as intended.  This is also more future-proof since at some point we may want our consumer python API to include more easily accessible functionality than just `tb.summary`.\r\n\r\nI added some clarifying comments and a test in `pip_smoke_test.sh` to avoid regressions."

column2:
"message": "[Debugger Plugin]: Add continue-to-node action from context menu & buttons (#826)

* Add "Continue to" command to the context menu.
  Now we have two modes of "continue":
  * the existing continue over a given number of Session.runs
  * continue until a given node is reached
* Add continue-to paper-icon-buttons to value cards
* Add continue-to paper-icon-buttons to Tensor Value Overview
  When clicked
column3: these continue-to paper-icon-buttons let the TF runtime\r\n  continue executing until hitting the tensor again. If the graph\r\n  visualizer is open
column4: it will focus on the corresponding node. It will\r\n  also focus on the corresponding node in the Node List.\r\n* Use red as the highlight color throughout
column5: to be consistent with the\r\n  graph visualizer"

column2: "message": "Fix issues related to panning to a node (#824)\n\nWhen a user selects a node that is out of view
column3: the graph explorer pans\r\nto it and centers it. Unfortunately
column4:
this feature had some issues.

0. Panning happened before graph expansion completed. This led to pan
target calculations that relied on incorrect
column5:
outdated measurements. We
fix by waiting 250ms (the default duration for animations in the graph
explorer) before panning in order to give enough time for node expansion
to complete.

1. The graph explorer did not take into account the position of the
graph's root SVG element with respect to the viewport. This led to
panning calculations that were slightly off. We fix by taking that into
account.

2. Nodes could sometimes be occluded by the minimap - those nodes are
strictly speaking still in the view of the graph explorer
column6: so we\r\npreviously did not pan to nodes occluded by the minimap. Now
column7:
we do.

There are still issues related to panning that are not fixed. For
instance
column8:
we do not pan to extracted nodes. Panning sometimes yields a
console error:

```js
Error: <text> attribute x: Expected length
column10: this PR does fix several big issues."

"message": "Make pip_smoke_test.sh more robust against false positives (#801)

This makes `pip_smoke_test.sh` robust against two types of false positives that I realized it might produce:

1.  Testing for the post-pip-package-installation presence of a tensorboard binary with `which tensorboard` could falsely return true if tensorboard was anywhere on the path (e.g. installed to the system outside the virtualenv)
column3: meaning it didn't actually guarantee that the tensorboard command used later in the script would be the one from the pip package.\r\n\r\n2. Testing for whether URLs are accessible at `localhost:6006` (by default) could falsely succeed if there was another pre-existing tensorboard instance running locally on port 6006 (which is common for a developer machine since that's the default tensorboard port)
column4: since the accesses don't really have a way to check that they're talking to the freshly launched tensorboard.  Note that the newly launched tensorboard actually dies on startup in this case (since it can't bind to the requested port) but it's hidden since it's been backgrounded.\r\n\r\nThis fixes the first one by checking directly for a `tensorboard` binary inside the virtualenv's `bin` directory
column5: and fixes the second one by ensuring that we wait for the `tensorboard` binary to start up successfully and print its serving URL before proceeding with the test.  That also means we can extract the serving URL automatically
column6: which makes it possible to set the default port to 0 (aka requesting an unused local port from the kernel) which should eliminate the risk of interference in the default case."

"message": "Make build_pip_package.sh use only one python binary (#797)

This change ensures that `build_pip_package.sh` uses just one python binary - whatever is available as `python` - rather than building the py2 wheel file with `python` and the py3 one with `python3`.  Building a wheel file for pyX doesn't actually require running `setup.py` with the matching pythonX binary; you can just specify the version the wheel file should be built for explicitly.

It's better to use just `python` because that means that within a virtualenv that only provides `bin/python` (e.g. a python2 virtualenv)
column3: you still pick up the hermetization of the virtualenv.  Otherwise
column5: the invocation of `python3` will break out of the virtualenv to the system's python3 and whatever old crufty package versions it shipped with
column6: instead of using the virtualenv's python and its freshly updated packages.\r\n\r\nAnd in particular
column7: for my machine with these old crufty packages
column8: this fixes `pip_smoke_test.sh` - which otherwise fails with an error in the `python3 setup.py bdist_wheel >/dev/null` line of `build_pip_package.sh` saying that the `install_requires` spec is invalid
column9: when this is actually caused by my machine's python3 not having a sufficiently up-to-date version of setuptools that recognizes an `install_requires` that uses environment markers like `python_version >= \"3\"`."

"message": "Preload and precompress static assets in CorePlugin (#708)\n\nThis changes CorePlugin to load its static assets into memory at startup and precompress them with gzip. The two static assets in this case are \"index.html\" (the main vulcanized TensorBoard HTML blob) and \"trace_viewer_index.html\". Since \"index.html\" at a minimum is always served when using TensorBoard
column3: this spends roughly 1 MB of extra RAM to move the cost of preparing it to startup-time so that it can be served directly from memory.\r\n\r\nPrior to this change
column4: a typical request for those assets would involve 1) a disk read to open the assets_zip_provider webfiles.zip file
column6: 3) extracting the index.html file from the zip archive
column7: and 4) recompressing the file using gzip (about 40ms to compress 2.6MB down to 0.7ish) to send it back to the client.\r\n\r\nNow it's just served as precompressed gzip data directly from memory. From some basic testing on my workstation with a local TensorBoard
column8: this changes the TTFB (Time To First Byte [1]) for index.html from about 100ms average to less than 5ms
column9: and the average delay to DOMContentLoaded firing correspondingly drops from about 1000ms to 900ms.\r\n\r\nModern browsers pretty much all send Accept-Encoding: gzip but in case the user doesn't send that header
column10: this change also adds support for decompressing precompressed data before responding. In theory we could avoid the decompression delay as well by also storing uncompressed assets in memory
column11: but I opted not to because it complicates the Respond() API and the argument in favor is much weaker since decompression is typically faster than compression (in testing it took about 20ms for index.html) and we expect gzip supporting requests to be the vast majority
column12: so it'd be spending more memory to save less time less often.\r\n\r\n[1] https://developers.google.com/web/tools/chrome-devtools/network-performance/reference#timing-explanation"

column2:
"message": "Make TensorBoard work in raw sources mode (#747)

With this change we withdraw our support for the ECMA `import` keyword hitherto
mandated by certain tools. In doing so
column4:
rather
than taking a minute.

The ES6 `import` standard only defines / and ./ prefixed paths. All other paths
that exist are undefined. Since most tooling and early-adopter codebases rely
on the undefined behavior
column5: the standard itself is mostly syntactic sugar (that\r\nisn't even sweet.) The true problem is having a world where Closure
column7:
and
web server namespaces coexist.

The ES6 `import` keyword makes JavaScript incompatible with web browsers. The
support added in Chrome 61 is not sufficient
column8: as it only allows the `export`\r\nkeyword on functions and not variables. This is a point of view much different\r\nfrom early-adopters
column9:
which raises concerns that the standard is unlikely to
gain a meaningful consensus.

The ES6 `import` keyword makes TypeScript incompatible with web browsers. This
keyword is not supported by the TypeScript compiler. All it can do is punt the
problem to rollup. However we can't use rollup since it doesn't support Closure
namespaces.

The only tool that supports all three of Web
column11: and Closure namespaces is\r\nthe Closure Compiler. Without it
column12:
ES6 TypeScript or JavaScript can't run in any
web browser.

But since the Closure Compiler was designed to create production builds for
google.com
column13:
it isn't very fast. Therefore it's unreasonable that developers on
a small project like TensorBoard should be expected to wait on this tool
whenever making one line changes in a development iteration cycle.

Since the Closure Tools were originally designed to be compatible with web
browsers in the absense of tooling
column14: this change seeks to bring TensorBoard back\r\ninto accordance with those principles."

"message": "Convert the simplest cases of <content> to <slot> (#701)\n\nThe <content> element is deprecated
column3:
part of the Shadow DOM v0 API which has
been supplanted by Shadow DOM v1's <slot> element. For very simple uses – like
those in this CL – this change should be safe and will not require changes to
the usage sites of your element. Therefor
column4:
these changes are
backwards-compatible with Polymer 1.0 applications.

Polymer 1.0 supports both <content> and
<slot> by converting <slot> back into <content> at runtime. Polymer 2.0 only
supports <slot>. There will likely never be cross-browser native support for
<content>

"message": "Fix TextPlugin scalar string decoding errors in py3 (#685)\n\nThis fixes tensorflow/tensorboard#647 in which TextPlugin incorrectly decodes scalar string values as their raw numpy byte representation before passing them to `markdown_to_safe_html()`.  When running python 2 this happens to work because numpy and Python use the same raw byte representation for string data

"message": "Change TextPlugin to compute index_impl() asynchronously (#663)\n\nAddresses tensorflow/tensorboard#625 by changing TextPlugin to avoid blocking its `is_active()` method on reading from the filesystem.  Note that \"reading from the filesystem\" is not only reading once
column3: but reading in all plugin assets from all runs
column4: which could be dozens of reads per run
column5: potentially over the network if using a remote filesystem.  In my testing this could easily cause `is_active()` to take 30+ seconds that kind of scenario
column6: which in turn blocks the `/plugins_listing` response for the whole of TensorBoard.\r\n\r\nSince the TextPlugin's `is_active()` is based on its `index_impl()` (which backs its `/tags` route) and the expensive filesystem-checking logic is shared
column7: this change puts the entirety of `index_impl()` on a background thread.  This way the `/tags` route can also benefit from not blocking.\r\n\r\nThe semantics are now that `is_active()` will return False and `index_impl()` will return a placeholder empty response when first invoked
column8: but they'll kick off at most one background thread at a time to do the computation and store the resulting index response.  Once the plugin is detected to be active
column9: `is_active()` will no longer kick off new background threads when invoked
column10: but `index_impl()` will still kick off a new background thread when called (if one is not running already) so that refreshes will pick up new data as it gets written to the logdir."

column2:
"message": "Fix pageview hit counting to avoid dupes (#674)

This fixes some duplication issues in pageview counting for Google Analytics. Note that currently analytics is only enabled for internal Google users.

Specifically
column3: sending pageview hits from _updateSelectedDashboard() was not really correct because that Polymer observer is invoked on any change to either observed property - the selected dashboard or the list of active dashboards. That means that as the active dashboards are loaded
column4: every change to _activeDashboards will result in a duplicate page hit being logged for the currently selected dashboard.\r\n\r\nAs a special case of this
column5: observers are also invoked a single time once their default values are all initialized to handle the default values (as a new change from \"undefined\"). So this also meant that on every page load we would send a pageview hit right away for the \"/\" page corresponding to the \"null\" default value of _selectedDashboard
column6: even if loading e.g. http://tb/#scalars directly.\r\n\r\nThis fixes the first issue by changing _updateSelectedDashboard() to exclusively focus on setting the selected dashboard to the first active dashboard (if appropriate)
column7: and moving the pageview and hash updating into a separate observer _selectedDashboardChanged() that only observes _selectedDashboard. It fixes the second issue by making _selectedDashboard default to the value from the hash
column8: so that loading http://tb/#scalars generates only a single pageview hit for \"/scalars\" rather than \"/\" followed by \"/scalars\".\r\n\r\nNote that the way I have it now
column9: loading http://tb/ will still always generate that first hit for \"/\" even if the active dashboards result in immediately \"redirecting\" to e.g. http://tb/#scalars which then gets recorded as a second hit. I think this is reasonable since the user did still type in \"/\" and that way we can distinguish visitors to the TensorBoard \"home\" page who get redirected to the first active dashboard from visitors who go immediately to a preselected dashboard.\r\n\r\nLastly
column10: this removes the extra pageview hit for \"/v/graph\" sent by tf-graph-dashboard; it was introduced before the automatic hash-based plugin pageview hits were added to tf-tensorboard
column11: and it's pretty much just redundant with the hit for \"/graphs\" that the latter would generate."

"message": "Log time taken by is_active() calls for plugin listing (#662)\n\nThis is a preliminary step in addressing tensorflow/tensorboard#625 that just adds logging (at INFO) for the amount of time taken by the is_active() call for each plugin loaded by TensorBoard when the plugins listing endpoint is invoked. This way as we make fixes we can monitor for regressions

"message": "Lower _MINIMUM_COUNT to 1e-7 (#644)

PR curve summaries had used 1.0 as the minimum division value while computing precision and recall.

That actually does not work because certain weights can cause TP
column5: and FN values to be below 1.0.\r\n\r\nThis change sets that minimum to 1e-7 and adds a test."

column3: unfriendly bin edges. The number of bins is 1 less than the number of thresholds. Hence
column4: it usually makes more sense for the number of thresholds to be odd.\r\n\r\nThis is a request from Waymo folks."

column2: "message": "Try just removing prefix if no match (#623)\n\nPreviously
column3: the graph explorer attempted to extract a label from a\r\nstring to use as the display name for a node representing a function.\r\nApparently
column4:
that regex does not always match a function. Certain graphs
found within Google directly use the entire string as the name of the
function. That caused the graph explorer to be blank due to an error.

Now
column5:
the graph attempts to strip the prefix from the string and just
use the second half as the display name if parsing the display name

"message": "Tidy up the tensorboard.main API (#620)

This change will make it easier to write plugins with custom builds of
TensorBoard. The plugin author will no longer be required to explicitly list
all the first-party plugins
column3:
as they can now be inherited via the
`tensorboard.default` module.

The `tensorboard.program` module has also been introduced. This module gives a
permanent home to all the APIs that crept into `tensorboard.main` over the
years. After this change
column4:
the `tensorboard.main` module is nothing more than
glue between the `program` and `default` modules.

The special-case code in main.py that the debugger plugin was using
column5:
has now
been relocated into the debugger plugin's directory.

This change is backwards-compatible. Delegates have been added for relocated
functions that will log a deprecation warning if used."

column5: and also serves to document the API."

This change makes the `is_active` method of the scalars plugin

demo data. The scalars plugin is inactive.

Use `time.time()` to log the time it takes for some internal events file
(with over 30K tags in one specific run) with and without this change.

`is_active` takes too long to respond.

Granted
column7: one might reason that a user should not have 30K tags ... but\r\neven so

Added a new property to `tf-graph` and `tf-graph-board` called

"message": "Add property edgeWidthFunction to tf-graph (#599)

This change adds a `edgeWidthFunction` property to tf-graph and
tf-graph-board. This is a method that a user can specify to compute the

instead of tensor size."

"message": "Make EPIPE tracebacks go away (#595)

These errors aren't very helpful and they tend to fill up logs. They could be
caused by something as innocent as `curl -N http://localhost:6006/ | head`. It
could also be caused by firewalls
column3: or perhaps the browser abruptly navigating\r\nsomewhere else. So we wouldn't want users to mistake these as meaningful when\r\ntroubleshooting."

column2: "message": "Ensure that the list of function usages updates (#578)\n\nPreviously
column3: when a user selected a node that represents a function
column4: the list of function usages in the info card might not update. In response
column5:
this change

1. makes the info card asynchronously update that iron-list when the list of function usages changes. The logic for asynchronously updating node list items is now moved into a helper method also used by the logic for rendering lists of inputs and outputs.
2. makes `_functionUsages` depend on `_node` instead of `nodeName` like the other lists of nodes do. This prevents duplicating a little code and also ensure that `_resetState` is called when `_functionUsages` updates.
3. Renamed the 3 methods that obtain lists of nodes (`_getSuccessors`
column7:
and `_getFunctionUsages`) to be consistent. Moved them closer together so that future developers will hopefully see a pattern between them and not forget to asynchronously update the UI.

Test plan:
Start TensorBoard with the attached events file. In the graph dashboard
column8: select an op node such as `y_`. Then select a function call node such as `MnistLoss` in the core graph. Notice that usages of the function are listed in the info card. Notice that the info card still lists inputs and successors for various ops throughout the graph as expected."
