"message": "Add the `tensorboard.summary` public entry point (#562)

Summary:
Resolves #561.

Test Plan:
Ran the `build_pip_package.sh` script to build the Python 2 package
column3:
then created a new Python 2 virtualenv in which I installed only the
latest nightly TensorFlow release (2017-09-22) and the generated wheel.
Then wrote
```py
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorboard import summary
result = tf.Session().run(summary.scalar('shelby'
column4:
tf.constant(3)))
s = tf.Summary()
s.ParseFromString(result)
print(s)
```
and verified that the result was a proper scalar summary.

I then repeated the process using `pip install tensorflow==1.3.0`
instead of the nightly version to ensure that the module works for
normal TensorFlow users. (Note: the audio summary will not work because
TensorFlow 1.3 lacks 22730fd4c633a74e59c03ff76dc92e6ae2d5d020. This is
fine; users can continue to use the old API for that one.)

wchargin-branch: summary-module"

column2:
"message": "Fix non-existent localStorage lookup behavior (#534)

Summary:
When we use the `tf-storage` module’s APIs to look up a key that does
not exist
column3: it is supposed to return `undefined`. However
column4:
calling
`getNumber("nonexistent")` before this patch would return `0` instead.
This is because `localStorage.getItem("nonexistent")` evaluates to
`null`
column5: and `undefined !== null`. Using weak equality fixes the issue.\r\n\r\n(Despite the timing
column6:
this error was not introduced by the recent
refactor to `tf-storage`; it was present previously.)

Test Plan:
Add `console.log(getNumber("nonexistent")
column7: /*useLocalStorage=*/true)` in\r\nsome module. Note that it prints `0` before this patch

"message": "Load new projector config when dataset changes (#519)\n\nPreviously
column4:
a new projector config might not load because the name of the new run (string) could stay the same - indeed the name of the run is always 'proto'.

This change makes it so that we load a new projector config and correspondingly update the UI when the data provider changes (even if the run name changes).

Fixes #478. This commit is coauthored by @svsgoogle and @chihuahua."

column2: "message": "Stylize the newly selected node after expansion (#516)\n\nPreviously
column3: when the user performs some functionality to expand the\r\ngraph and then select a node (such as navigating to a node after\r\nobserving TPU compatibility or clicking an op in the debugger plugin)
column4:
the graph would select a node before expanding its parent nodes.

This can cause an error because the selected node is not yet present in
the graph hierarchy:

```
(index):7546 Uncaught (in promise) TypeError: Cannot read property
'node' of undefined
   at HTMLElement._updateNodeState ((index):7546)
         at HTMLElement._selectedNodeChanged ((index):7547)
	 ```

This change makes the scene only stylize the selected node
after expansion of necessary nodes finishes. I don't think I can repro
the issue after this change."

column2:
"message": "Fix the PR curve plugin backend JSON serialization (#538)

Summary:
The PR curve data route was returning numpy arrays
column3: which are not\r\nJSON-serializable. This caused `/data/plugin/pr_curves/pr_curves`\r\nrequests to fail with status 500
column4:
which in turn caused the PR curve
dashboard to not display any data.

Test Plan:
Load the PR curve dashboard with some demo data. Before this patch
column6: plus some console failures\r\nindicating the status-500 request. After this patch
column7:
the PR curves will
load and there won’t be any console failures.

wchargin-branch: fix-pr-curve-serialization"

column2:
"message": "Fix dimensions of card heading’s colored run label (#537)

Summary:
In the case where a run label appears on the same line as the tag name
(i.e.
column3: is not wrapped to the next line)
column4: the label is too tall. This is\r\nbecause the label was a direct flex item and so was being blockified.\r\nIt should have been a `<span>`
column5:
and it also needs to be wrapped in a
second `<span>` to avoid blockification.

Before:

"message": "Add base_url support and base_url tests (#436)

This change adds base_url support for tensorboard such that a user can specify the base path as follows:

```
tensorboard --logdir=/path/to/log_files --base_url=/path/to/tensorboard
```

Tensorboard will then be able to be accessed at (assuming default port of 6006):
```
localhost:6006/path/to/tensorboard/
```

Changes mostly in applications.py by adding the base_url as a prefix to each self.data_applications[path]

Additionally
column3: test for base_url support was added to applications_test.py\r\n\r\nFixes #30."

"message": "Redesign the `tf-storage` module (#509)

Summary:
This commit improves the API of the `tf-storage` module
column3:
and also
simplifies its internal implementation (hence the negative delta).
There are two API changes:

  - It is now possible to have a `polymerProperty` different from the
    `key` used in the storage layer.

  - Arguments other than the `key` are now accepted in an `options`
    object
column4: so that they are effectively named arguments instead of\r\n    positional arguments. This is especially useful for the boolean\r\n    observer and initializer functions
column5: which used to take two\r\n    consecutive boolean parameters: one was the default value
column6:
and one
    indicated whether to use local storage. (Which was which?)

Internally
column7: each object type\u2019s bindings are now generated and exported\r\nfrom a single function call. This removes a bunch of boilerplate code\r\n(120 lines of it
column8:
to be precise).

Test Plan:
  - Verified that each result of `get.*\(Observer\|Initializer\)` has
    been upgraded to the new API.
  - Verified that values are persisted both to the fragment and to local
    storage.
  - Verified that `window.localStorage` has the correct value.
  - Verified that changes to the hash cause Polymer properties to
    update.
  - Applied the patch listed below to verify that two-way binding still
    works when the `polymerProperty` differs from the `key`.

```diff
diff --git a/tensorboard/plugins/scalar/tf_scalar_dashboard/tf-scalar-dashboard.html b/tensorboard/plugins/scalar/tf_scalar_dashboard/tf-scalar-dashboard.html

column2: "message": "Create `addParams`
column3:
replacing `queryEncoder` (#492)

Summary:
The existing `queryEncoder` function had a significant flaw: it always
returned a string starting with `"?"`
column4: but the initial delimiter should\r\nbe `\"&\"` if the URL already contains a query component. This could\r\nhappen unexpectedly if
column6: an application embeds TensorBoard and\r\nmonkey-patches the router to include some parameters in every URL
column7:
so
that a call like `pluginRoute` has query parameters where the original
author of the plugin expects none.

A simple solution is to replace this with a function `addParams` that
constructs the query string and attaches it to the URL in one go
column8:
adding
to an existing string if one exists. This new function also now supports
repeated parameters for convenience.

Test Plan:
I tested that all existing plugins work as intended. I didn’t test the
JS test because we have no way to run them.

wchargin-branch: add-params"

"message": "Remove max op from numerator of precision (#465)

When the threshold is high enough so that the predictor makes no
positive predictions
column3: precision is undefined because its denominator is\r\nfp + tp. Hence
column4: we remove the max operation from the numerator of the\r\nprecision calculation
column5:
so that precision is 0 (and not 1) when the thresold is
1.

A subsequent effort will make the frontend just not show data points for
which fp + tp = 0. For now
column6: we get rid of that max op so that the user\r\ndoes not see precision as equal to 1e-07
column7:
which can be confusing.

Also computed recall simply as

```python
recall = tp / tf.maximum(_MINIMUM_COUNT
column8:
tp + fn)
```

We already compute false positive counts via fn = tp[0] - tp. That seems
more straightforward."

column2:
"message": "Pass skipLibCheck to tsc in ts_web_library (#407)

skipLibCheck means that the TypeScript compiler will not check `.d.ts` files for
internal correctness. It will only check their use in `.ts` files.

This works around two issues:
- With certain inputs
column3: Clutz will produce inconsistent `.d.ts` files. The\r\n  problems are cosmetic insofar as using the APIs generated works and checks\r\n  correctly
column4: just the `.d.ts` doesn't check out internally. As no user wrote\r\n  that code
column5: it doesn't make sense to check it.\r\n- TypeScript initially reads large declaration files such as `lib.d.ts`. That\r\n  takes a lot of time
column6: so this change will speed up compilation.\r\n\r\nThis change unblocks an upgrade of Clutz in google3."

column2: "message": "Add a \"Functions\" scene group (#394)\n\nThis change adds a \"Functions\" scene group if the graph being visualized has a function library
column3: which contains definitions for functions (templates for subgraphs) used in the TensorFlow graph.\r\n\r\nAs part of that effort
column4:
this change also strips the arbitrary hexadecimal suffix from names of functions in the graph. That suffix is not user-generated - it merely serves to distinguish between functions with the same name but different signatures.

This refactors the implementation to prefix metanodes representing functions with FUNCTION_LIBRARY_NODE_PREFIX instead of lumping them under a metanode named FUNCTION_LIBRARY_NODE. We now also remove the function metanodes from the core graph later when building the sub-hierarchy instead of excluding them in the first place from the __root__ metagraph. That lets us use existing paths to render the metanodes for functions in the scene group.

The metanodes in the scene group (which represent function definitions) are not yet linked to individual calls throughout the graph - that will happen in a later change.

This change is complex and will be tested via internal Selenium-based integration tests."

for tensor and graph data from debugger-enabled (tfdbg-enabeld)

following information in the Graph Dashboard:

"message": "Add a demo script for creating PR curve summaries (#289)

This demo script generates random colors associated with true labels RGB
based on a 3D normal distribution situated at each corner of the RGB
color triangle. It then uses 3 different distributions (one for each of
the 3 classes RGB) to assign probabilities to each color for whether it
falls under a certain class.

Also added a test for computing PR curve summary data that involves
multiple classes and weighing predictions for one class more than the
other. Made the tests for the pr_curves plugin depend on data 
generated by the demo."

"message": "Switch to a more accessible color scale (#288)

Summary:

Existing colorblind-accessible color schemes
column5:
but unfortunately do not
employ TensorBoard’s signature orange color. This commit switches
TensorBoard to use a custom color scheme designed by Paul Tol around the
TensorBoard orange.

[alt]: https://personal.sron.nl/~pault/#qualitativescheme

Screenshots:
![Scalar dashboard with the new color scheme](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/29087264-32f0d914-7c2a-11e7-9ce3-d4d5e3b49195.png)
![Histogram dashboard with the new color scheme](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/29087267-342989f2-7c2a-11e7-944c-359c347a4995.png)
![Distribution dashboard with the new color scheme](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/29087269-35daa10a-7c2a-11e7-87d6-51dd6b1485fc.png)

See #288 for discussion and previous iterations.

the actual value of the argument cannot be tab-completed
column4: etc. We should only encourage the superior form.\r\n\r\nI found this occurrences with `git grep -- '--.*='`

column2: "message": "Make metanodes out of functions in the graph explorer (#341)\n\nPreviously
column3: the graph explorer had visualized nodes that represented function calls as op nodes
column4: which was not helpful because that showed none of the logic within the function.\r\n\r\nThis change makes it so that the graph explorer parses the library of GraphDefs and visualizes each function call as a metanode. Functions can recursively call functions
column5: so we introduce a means for the graph hierarchy to dynamically change. This is done via first creating a metanode for each function and then making a copy of a function's metanode and injecting that copy into a meta graph when necessary (ie
column6: when the user expands a node with a function).\r\n\r\nThere is still much work to be done. We need to make it clear that the metanodes represent functions. We need to enumerate the places in which each function is called. We should also visually indicate that 2 metanodes represent the same function if they do (perhaps via filling the nodes with the same color). However
column7: this change lays down the code organization that at least allows functions to be visualized."

"message": "Force reinstallation of TensorFlow deps on Travis (#338)

Summary:
We were recently encountering the following error on Travis on any
attempt to import `tensorflow` in the Python 3 environment:
```
RuntimeError: module compiled against API version 0xb but this version of numpy is 0xa
```
This exception ultimately manifests with the following message:
```
SystemError: initialization of _pywrap_tensorflow_internal raised unreported exception
```
The Travis logs include the following line during the TensorFlow
installation:
```
Requirement already satisfied: numpy>=1.11.0 in /home/travis/virtualenv/python3.4.6/lib/python3.4/site-packages (from tensorflow==1.head)
```
This indicates that the Travis system already has a conflicting numpy
version installed. Because we’re not using a virtualenv
column3:
this conflict
prevents TensorFlow from being imported.

You can reproduce this in a virtualenv as follows:
```
$ virtualenv test -p python3
$ source test/bin/activate
$ pip install numpy==1.11.0  # critical line
$ pip install "${NIGHTLY_URL}"  # Python 3 nightly wheel (in .travis.yml)
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
```
The presence of the critical line causes the import to fail.

By passing the `-I` flag to `pip install`
column4: we ask `pip` to ignore\r\nexisting versions of dependencies
column5:
instead reinstalling the latest
versions.

We might want to switch to a virtualenv
column6:
anyway.

Test Plan:
Deploy to Travis. We expect tests to still fail
column7: but they should be\r\nactual failures due to recent changes in TensorFlow nightly. (We have a\r\nPR out to fix them
column8: but it needs this PR to run the Python 3 tests.)\r\n\r\nwchargin-branch: force-travis-deps-reinstallation"

"message": "Make is_active for projector return quickly (#326)\n\nThis change makes the projector plugin start a separate thread to compute whether it is active. This allows the `is_active` method to return immediately. Otherwise
column3: it may take a long time to return
column4: which could cause issues - see https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/301\r\n\r\nWe can actually compute the _is_active property in less time by halting the other thread when we know we have 1 entry in the config object (instead of computing all the values of the object)
column5: but computing the config object should usually not take severely long anyway so the added complexity and duplicated logic does not seem worth it.\r\n\r\nFixes #301."

column3: which assists with reading them in order."

column2:
"message": "Implement DB transaction logic (#324)

These helpers allow us to do optimistic write-deferred transactions retried
with exponential back-off. This is necessary because we're planning to compute
primary keys randomly
column3: in order to get good sharding behavior
column4: and collisions\r\nmight occur. Writes are deferred to minimize the amount of time that SQLite\r\nneeds a RESERVED lock
column5: which blocks both transactional reads and writes."

column2:
"message": "Remove histogram compression from TensorBoard core (#291)

Summary:
This commit moves histogram compression from the event accumulator to
the distributions plugin. That is
column3: instead of compressing histograms at\r\nevent processing time
column4: we compress them at serving time (when the\r\n`/distributions` route is requested). This should have no performance\r\nimpact
column5: as the number of buckets in the histograms being compressed is\r\nat most 30 (unless the user overrides the default)
column6:
and the compression
algorithm is already very efficient.

Here is one subtle effect of this change: because the histograms and
compressed histograms had different reservoir sizes
column7:
naively applying
the change as described above would result in the time granularity of
the rendered distributions becoming significantly more coarse. (See
screenshots below.) To resolve this effect
column8: we raise the histogram\r\ndownsampling threshold to that of the distributions
column9: but perform\r\nadditional downsampling in the histograms plugin (and not the\r\ndistributions plugin). As a result
column10: the amount of data sent over the\r\nnetwork in any given request is unchanged. It's true that more\r\nhistograms than before are stored in TensorBoard's memory
column11: but the\r\nincrease should not be too great. Indeed
column12: instead of thinking of the\r\nchange as increasing the amount of histograms stored
column13:
think of the
change as "uncompressing" all the already-compressed histograms and then
deleting all the original histograms. Because the uncompression factor
is not too large (in turn because we're always compressing from 30 bins
to 9 basis points)
column14:
there shouldn't be any performance problems.

Here are three screenshots. The first is the original dashboard. The
second is the dashboard with this commit but without the dynamic
downsampling logic; this exhibits the coarse granularity issue described
above. The third is the dashboard after this commit
column15: whose data is only\r\nimperceptibly different from the original data.\r\n![The distributions dashboard on master
column16:
before this commit](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/28701498-730a2898-730b-11e7-9c16-201ba02cebd0.png)
![The distributions dashboard with a version of this commit that did not include dynamic downsampling](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/28701494-7088b544-730b-11e7-9ac4-72bef442b8c9.png)
![The distributions dashboard after this commit](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/28702387-7855821a-7311-11e7-8443-6c458f034c39.png)

Note that the distributions dashboard now supports new-style histograms.
In fact
column18:
because the distributions dashboard now
wraps the histogram dashboard plugin and post-processes its results!
This implementation change reflects the implicit dependency that the
distributions plugin has always had on the histograms plugin
column19:
making it
an explicit dependency in the code.

Full disclosure: the test data in `compressor_test.py` didn't make any
sense. The histogram protos had `min` and `max` values that were
disjoint with the data
column21: etc.\r\nI simply created reasonable test data and copied the results from\r\n\"actual\" to \"expected
column22:
" so these tests trivially pass currently and from
now on can serve as regression tests. My test that the behavior is
actually reasonable is to compare the first and third screenshots above
and note that everything appears well-behaved: I cannot perceive a
single difference in the output. (Also
column23:
the only changes that I made to
the algorithm were to redirect the appropriate inputs for the new
format.)

Test Plan:
As described above
column24: view the dashboard before and after this change
column25: and\r\nnote that the distributions qualitatively appear very similar (though\r\nthe underlying data will of course not be exactly the same)
column26: while the\r\nhistograms dashboard is unchanged. Also

column2: "message": "Define SQL schema for tensor storage (#293)\n\nThis code only supports SQLite
column3: but the schema itself takes Spanner
column6:
which we intend to support soon.

The following tables are defined:

- Experiments: Has one-to-many relationship with Runs.
- Runs: Has one-to-many relationshi with Tags
column7: with experiment locality.\r\n- Tags: Has one-to-many relationship with Tensors
column8:
with experiment locality.
- Tensors: Gzipped tf.Tensor protos stored in-page with tag locality.
- BigTensors: A one-to-one Tensor storage with no particular locality.
- EventLogs: Used to track loader progress for Runs.

While serving anything related to a given experiment
column10: Tags rows associated with that experiment at once
column11:
and cache
them for a short period of time.

When TensorBoard serves charts
column12: it will fetch all Tensors associated with a Tag\r\nat once
column13: to render for example a plot of scalars. If we are fetching big\r\ntensors
column15:
TensorBase will farm out futures to fetch
BigTensors in parallel as it iterates over Tensors.

Physical locality is controlled by making the assumption that the natural
ordering of the primary key can control where row data is sharded in the cloud
and stored in b-trees.

This design is scalable
column16:
but it's not entirely web scale. It can store 21
million charts before the write abort rate reaches 1%. It supports step counts
up to four billion. One can reasonably expect to store a hundred thousand
Experiments. In the future
column17: we will special case the primary key behavior on\r\nSpanner."

"message": "Introduce `data_compat`
column3:
legacy summary converter (#290)

Summary:
As we move from using old-style summaries to using only tensor
summaries
column4: we need to continue supporting the old formats. The only\r\nplugin that has been converted so far is the histogram plugin
column5:
and that
plugin manages the compatibility itself. But it would be nicer to have a
unified Event Translation Layer where we convert all the old-style
events to new-style events. Once we do this
column6:
plugin code will only have
to deal with new-style events---which is especially attractive because
it makes the plugins more copy-pastable.

This commit introduces `data_compat`
column7:
a module that will perform such
conversions. This module will intercept events before the event
accumulator processes them. This is forward-compatible with SQL mode:
we can simply call out to this module from the SQL loader instead of the
event accumulator. For now
column8:
`data_compat` converts histogram values and
leaves everything else alone.

I haven't connected this layer to the event accumulator because it has
breaking behavior for the distributions plugin
column9:
which depends on
special-casing behavior in the accumulator. The plan to deal with that
is to move the histogram compression logic out of the event accumulator
and into the distributions plugin itself (so that compression is
performed on the fly instead of being precomputed).

Run the included unit tests

column2: "message": "Fix :summary_test by avoiding scatter_add (#303)\n\nPer issue tensorflow/tensorflow#11856
column3:
a variable cannot be read from
directly after it is merely initialized in a TensorFlow graph. We must
instead use read_value to retrieve its value. This means that using
tf.scatter_add is problematic because it only accepts a single mutable
tensor (tf.Variable) that is both written to and read from.

Hence
column4: we avoid using tf.scatter_add and re-implement its logic using\r\ntf.gather and tf.scatter_update. We also use read_value() to retrieve\r\nthe values of variables throughout the summary logic."

column2: "message": "Fix issue where scalar charts can become tiny. (#204)\n\nThere is a general issue across TensorBoard: with the tf-paginated-view
column4: it's likely that some charts will be rendered when they\r\nare `display: none`. Data visualizations often depend on measurement code to\r\nlayout properly
column5: and the measurements break when the item is not being\r\ndisplayed. As a consequence
column6:
the chart renders wih strange and broken
proportions.

When @wchargin and I were pair-programming this
column7: we initially tried to work\r\naround the measurement issue so that the chart would layout properly even if it\r\nwere `display:none`
column8: but that proved infeasible. So instead we decided to write\r\ncode to detect when the chart gets in a bad state
column9:
and fix it.

This code marks scalar charts as being in a bad state if their data finishes
loading when the chart is no longer in an active pane. When the chart's pane
becomes active
column10: an observer redraws the chart. Rather than redrawing\r\nsynchronously
column11: we've set up an asynchronous redraw cascade with a 32ms timeout;\r\nthis way
column12:
we don't block the UI or unduly slow down the ripple on the
"next page" button.

Note
column13: the bug actually exists on other dashboards (distributions and histograms\r\nboth repro it)
column14:
and this fix only works on the scalar dashboard. We may fix it
on other dashboards in the future.

Fixes #190"

column2:
"message": "Introduce RecordReader and BufferedRecordReader (#188)

Introduce RecordReader and BufferedRecordReader

These classes are similar to EventFileLoader but have functionality for
tracking the current offset and size of a record file. This will allow the
loader to display a really cool looking progress bar.

RecordReader provides a higher level and more Pythonic alternative to
PyRecordReader when it comes to reading TensorFlow record files.

BufferedRecordReader layers a thread on top of RecordReader and implements the
same interface. This will become the default because it doesn't have any impact
on local throughput
column3: but is guaranteed to go fast for remote file systems.\r\n\r\nIn the future
column4: we may decouple these classes from PyRecordReader.\r\n\r\nSee #92"

"message": "Add open source logging infrastructure (#187)

Open source logs now:

- Use the same format as Google logs
- Use ANSI color for non-INFO records
- Get emitted *above* the line with the TensorBoard URL

The functionality that makes the TensorBoard URL stick to the last line in the
terminal is ironically called "ephemeral logging" because it was designed to
meet the requirements of FileLoader's progress bar.

Please note that ephemeral logging and ANSI colors do not happen on Windows or
anything that isn't a TTY. For example
column3:
piping stderr to a file will cause
everything to look normal.

In the future
column4: flags will be added so open source users can configure the\r\nverbosity of the logger."

column6:

![New view of the histogram dashboard.](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/4317806/27709831-71f3a24e-5cd2-11e7-8d66-410f6e6bfefa.png)

By introducing a search bar in the main content pane
column7:
we get the
following features for free.

First
column9:
we have search itself. This is superior to tag groups
because updating the search query does not lose the state of all
categories (both the category panes' "am I expanded?" state and the
individual visualization's properties
column10:
like the current plot window).
This also means that you can see your search results update as you type.

Second
column11:
we set the default search query to `.*`. This has the effect
that the initial screen of a dashboard provides useful data instead of
just collapsed categories loading a dashboard shows you some useful data
instead of nothing. It also suggests to the user that the search field
supports regular expressions
column12:
which is a nice bonus.

column2:
"message": "Improve the scalar chart user experience (#189)

Summary:
This fixes a number of issues with the scalar charts
column4:
and all of which are existing issues made more visible
by the presence of a search pane.

In particular:

 1. If a chart's `run` and `tag` properties are changed simultaneously
column6: and the first update will see the\r\n    data in an inconsistent state (e.g.
column7: Tag B but still Run A). We fix\r\n    the resulting issues by making observer updates asynchronous
column8:
so
    that they only actually take effect once all changes have flushed.
    (This fixes #169.)

 2. To reduce latency due to the above solution
column9:
we further debounce
    these update handlers.

 3. Because the handlers are asynchronous and debounced
column10: we need to\r\n    maintain stronger invariants on the caching keys. (In particular
column11: if\r\n    a chart changes from Tag A to Tag B and then to Tag C
column12:
we don't want
    the network requests for Tag B to fill the runs-loaded cache and
    then have Tag C forgo its fetches.)

 4. Furthermore
column13: when the tag of a chart is changed
column14: we display a\r\n    loading indicator. This is to prevent problems in the scenario where\r\n    many charts change from one tag to another: in this case
column15: all the\r\n    charts' titles will update immediately (they're just bound to text\r\n    nodes in the DOM)
column16: but charts' data will take a while to update; the\r\n    result is that there are many charts with titles that simply do not\r\n    match their data
column17:
which is at best very confusing. The loading
    indicator makes it clear that the data is stale.

 5. When a chart's tag is changed
column18:
we now reset the domain of the chart
    once all the data has loaded. (This fixes #164.)

 6. Finally
column19: we offer a button to manually reset the domain of the\r\n    chart. (This is often useful when changing the set of selected\r\n    runs: after adding a new run
column20: you may need to expand the domain
column21:
but
    we don't do this automatically because you may often want to keep
    your old domain.)

Issues (1)
column23: and (5) arise frequently when changing a search query
column24:
as this causes many charts to change their tag and runs.

Issues (1)
column26: and (4) apply to other dashboards as well
column27: but have not\r\nbeen fixed. (Issue (3) would apply to other dashboards that display one\r\nvisualization per tag instead of per run-tag combination
column28:
but there are
no such dashboards.)

Test Plan:
Cherry-pick #173 before proceeding. (Without a search feature
column29:
the
effects of this change are minimal---but I want to merge this change
before I merge the search feature!)

Launch TensorBoard with a few dozen scalar tags. Suppose without loss of
generality that the name of the fifth tag displayed in the search
results pane (on query `.*`) is `foo`. Set the search query to
`(?!foo)`; this should still match all tags. Now
column30:
add a caret at the
beginning to search for `^(?!foo)`. Charts past the fifth one should
reload. Check that the reloading behavior is pleasant.

Then
column32: manipulating their windows. Click the\r\n\"reload\" button
column34: and ensure that the window is\r\npreserved. Change the search query
column36:
and the windows should be
reset to show all the data.

wchargin-branch: improve-scalars-ux"

"message": "Fix 18 Closure Compiler warnings (#149)

Summary:
This eliminates all warnings except for the following:
  - warnings from library code
column3: like `paper-input-container`\r\n    (10 occurrences);\r\n  - warnings of the form \"Bad type annotation. Unknown type $foo\"
column4:

    $foo is a qualified type expression like `tf.scene.Minimap` or

The former we should not fix

Most fixes in this patch simply required specifying nullability
constraints on Polymer properties and functions from TypeScript code.
(Ideally
column6: the existence of a default value for a TypeScript parameter\r\nwould inform the Closure Compiler
column7: but this is not the case.) Others\r\ninvolved specifying default values of arguments (e.g.
column8:
explicitly
setting `false` instead of leaving a boolean argument absent).

Test Plan:

"message": "Fix logging and error handling (#148)

Summary:
We attempt to quiet the Werkzeug logger
column3:
because it's quite verbose. But
our patch to do so wasn't robust: Werkzeug only initializes its log
handlers if we don't touch the logger at all [1]. The result of this was
that any calls to Werkzeug's log function would yield an error
column4:
'no
handlers could be found for logger "werkzeug"'. This is particularly
problematic because the Werkzeug log function is used whenever there's
an internal server error
column5: so the effective result was that any 500s\r\nwouldn't print tracebacks
column6:
but instead just yield the above message.

[1]: https://github.com/pallets/werkzeug/blob/423a356d4a49a50179a2be7ba131570dbc607a34/werkzeug/_internal.py#L80-L86

This patch fixes that by emulating [1] and reinstating the default
logging handler.

"message": "Redesign the audio dashboard (#134)

Summary:
The audio dashboard used to be laid out in a grid
column3: with tags by row and\r\nruns by column. This made it inconsistent with all other dashboards
column4: and\r\nalso gave it some bizarre behaviors (e.g.
column5: if you have ten runs without\r\nany audio summaries and then five runs with the summaries
column6:
you'd have
to scroll horizontally past all ten runs without summaries before
getting to anything interesting). The implementation also had some
needlessly complicated behavior
column7:
like generating `<source>` elements and
manually listening for onload events instead of letting the browser do
what it does best.

This commit replaces it with a clone of the image dashboard adapted to
serve audio instead. The implementation is just like the image
dashboard
column8: but considerably simpler because the audio dashboard needs\r\nfewer features: cards needn't expand
column9: nor can audio clips show an\r\n\"actual size\"; we don't need a loading spinner
column10:
because the browser
already has a loading state for audio elements that will be familiar and
consistent across applications; etc.

I think it looks rather nice!

in `/tmp/audio_demo` if you don't have any audio summaries handy. Then

including toggling runs and making sure that the clips update
their sources correctly.

"message": "Centralize a global color scale

We have a `ColorScale` object with some nice logic and some nice
associated palettes
column3:
which we'd like to keep. But we also have a Polymer
component `tf-color-scale` whose role is to upward-bind a `ColorScale`.
Because the domain of all these color scales should be the same---the
set of available runs---exposing a single global color scale provides a
simpler API. Just look at the delta on this diff! :-)

This change introduces a `runsColorScale: ColorScale` that listens to
the `RunsStore` and updates itself when the runs change. Existing
dashboards and components have been retrofitted to use this instead of
the now-removed `tf-color-scale` component.

Note that this change does not prohibit clients from using custom
`ColorScale`s should they so desire: the pure-JS (well
column4:
TS) `ColorScale`
object is still available.

Tested all dashboards and found no functional changes.

"message": "Create a standalone tf-runs-selector

This change creates a `tf-runs-selector` component for selecting multiple
runs
column3: and implements it on the scalars dashboard as proof of concept. It\nfulfills the same functionality as the existing `tf-run-selector` (note\nthe singular)
column4:
but with a different and simpler API: it takes no input
and produces as output a list of selected runs. It uses a centralized
runs store as its source of truth; this will facilitate synchronizing
all run selectors to the same set of runs.

It currently behaves the same way as `tf-run-selector` with the
exception of the order of runs: this new component sorts the runs
column5:
while
the old component did not (so it was getting them in arbitrary order
from the `/runs` endpoint). It seems like sorting them is a good
idea---prefer determinism unless there's a good reason---but this will
result in a bit of drift among plugins with the old and new selectors in
this transition period. To combat that
column6: I've made the color scale sort\nits domain
column7: so that at least the colors are consistent. (I don't see a\nreason not to keep this in the final version

sorted by their
`first_event_timestamp` so that the order is append-only with respect to
newly discovered runs.

Dependency-injecting the router everywhere is not _too_ bad when there's
only one backend that's passed everywhere
column3: but we're trying to extract\nthe plugin-specific data from the backend. As a result
column4: each plugin will\nhave its own little \"micro-backend
column5:
" and forcing these to depend on a
router results in some very inconvenient Polymer code. Making the router
functions static simplifies this greatly.

column2:
"message": "Fix hash URLs

URLs like localhost:6006/#graphs weren't working. This was because the
`USE_HASH` property of `TF.Globals` was being read as false by the
router
column3:
even though `tf-tensorboard` was trying to set it to `true`. The
problem was that `tf-tensorboard` was only setting to true the _copy_ of
`USE_HASH` that it created at import time. The solution adopted here is
to let `globals.ts` close over a private `use_hash`
column4:
and expose a getter
and setter. An alternate solution is to expose a constant object
`{use_hash: false}`; importing modules would copy the _reference_ to
this object
column5:
so their mutations would pass through. This alternate
solution would perhaps be more elegant if we had more properties.

Test Plan:
  - Load http://localhost:6006/.
  - Change the URL to http://localhost:6006/#graphs.
  - Note that the view updates.

  - The data is of a realistic form.
  - The data is sufficient to exercise all capabilities of the plugin.
  - The data is not completely boring.

Such data then serves many purposes: it is documentation for this
particular plugin; it is documentation for TensorFlow and TensorBoard in
general; it can be used for manual testing of TensorBoard; and it can be
used in the plugin's unit tests. Ideally
column3: we'll also be able to create a\nscript to aggregate the test data from all first-party plugins
column4:
providing a single data set that can be used to comprehensively test
TensorBoard.

To start us off
column5: this change adds such data for the scalars plugin. It's\nrealistic in that it has a few thousand steps and a few dozen runs. It\nenables testing smoothing (due to the added noise)
column6: tag groups (due to\nthe various summary names)
column7: and run filters (due to the combinatorial\nrun parameters). And it's implementing a tiny physics simulation

column2: "message": "Validate plugin names and routes\n\nA plugin name shouldn't contain slashes or be empty
column3: as these would lead\nto confusing routes: a plugin with name \"eggs/ham\" and route \"/data\"\nwould handle the route \"/data/plugin/eggs/ham/data\"
column4: but this route\ncould also be handled by the plugin \"eggs\" along route \"/ham/data\".\nFurthermore
column5: it could also be handled by the plugin with name \"\" along\nroute \"eggs/ham/data\"
column6: or the plugin with name \"eggs/h\" along route\n\"am/data\". None of these is desirable
column7: so I'm forbidding\n  - plugins with characters not in [A-Za-z0-9_.-]
column8:
and
  - routes without a leading slash.

"message": "Tweaks for selecting y axes for plots
column3:
especially ones with small ranges.

The previous range selection heuristic tended to be too aggressive in expanding
the range of the y-axis when dealing with values close to 0. For example
column4: if\nall of the values ranged between 0.65 and 0.7 then it would set the y-range to\nsomewhere near [-0.1
column6: making it impossible to see changes over time. If\nall the values [0
column7: 1e-4] then it would select a range close to [-0.1
column8:
1e-4].

This change adds logic to avoid expanding the range of the y-axis too much. It
also modifies the 'ignore outliers' logic to select a range that includes 90%
of the data
column9: as opposed to the checked-in version that uses 80%.\nChange: 151071239"

"message": "Improve TensorBoard scalar dashboard domain calculation.\n\n- Add an \"ignore y-outliers\" option (default true). When true
column3: the domain is calculated based on the middle 8 deciles of the y range
column4: i.e. the lowest 10% of data and highest 10% of data is ignored for domain calculation purposes. Also
column5: this is done with the smoothed data rather than the raw data. This means that brief spikes or an initially high loss value will not distort the chart. This can be disabled to view the full data domain.\n- If the y values are all in the range [0
column7: then the domain is automatically set to be approximately [0
column8: 1]. That makes it easy to compare proportional values.\n- Added bold gridlines at the origin (0
column9: 0) to make the charts easier to understand at a glance.\nChange: 150362432"

"message": "Refactor TensorBoard into WSGI application.  Adds werkzeug pip dependency to
tensorflow.

This change is motivated by the need to use middleware to provide authentication internally. It also makes the TensorBoard backend more embeddable/re-usable.

* Adds a dependency on werkzeug for convenience in setting up WSGI apps.
* Replaces "TensorBoardHandler" with "TensorBoardWSGIApp". Now each route is a WSGI application. Generally uses convenient werkzeug decorators for making these applications.
* Removes handler.py
column3:
server.py; these are merged into application.py
* The Respond method in http.py now returns a Werkzeug Response object.
* Modify projector plugin to also be a WSGI application.
* Add a few error messages for helpfulness.
* Remove some dead code along the way. It has to do with sampling
column4: but we never incorporated it anywhere.\nChange: 145183192"

"message": "Changed the method for extracting high in and out degree nodes to be more nuanced than just extracting any node with in or out degree greater than 4.\n\nSpecifically
column4:
allow Variable nodes to be extracted.
If the graph has fewer than 15 nodes:
  Do not extract any nodes.
Else:
  Extract any nodes with
    in-degree > max(5
column6:
Q3 + 4 * (Q3 - Q1))

Here Q1 and Q3 refer to one of either the in or out degree set of data.

The threshold for out-degree is higher because
column8:
certain graphs such as  "cifar-10 train" regress (convolution nodes are unfortunately extracted) with a lower out-degree threshold.

Barebone/backbone implementation of the curses-based command-line UI for tfdbg.

The fibonacci_network demo constucts a simple TF graph that computes the fibonacci sequence
column11:
wraps a tf.Session object with a CLI debugger wrapper session and calls its run() method. which leads to launching of the curses CLI.

The CLI debugger wrapper implements the BaseDebugWrapperSession.

The UI currently has only minimalist command set including
  ni: inspect node info
  lt: list all dumped tensors
  li: list node inputs
  lo: list node output recipients
  pt: print tensor.

Currently supported UI features:
  * command history navigation using Up/Down keys: with or without prefix
  * scroll large output with PgUp/PgDown/Home/End keys
  * terminal resize response

See CLI help output for more information.

* tfdbg: Debug session wrapper framework

The design is done with supporting the following use cases in mind:
  1) A CLI debugging a locally running
column17:
in-process session.
  2) A CLI debugging a remotely running session.
  3) TensorBoard visual debugger debugging a remotely running session.

The wrapper provides the abilities to
  1) Intercept a run() call to a wrapped session and insert debug tensor watches according to debug URLs.
  2) Release control to an external object before and after the run() call
column18: so that the external object can perform actions such as launching a UI to allow users to inspect the intermediate tensors and partition graphs from the run() call.\r\n  3) (To be implemented in a future CL) Intercept a run() call and give control to DebugStepper to perform stepping / continuing-to actions on the graph.\r\n  4) (To be implemented in a future CL) Enter an instruction loop to let an external object (e.g.
column19:
remote client) launch run() and cont() calls remotely.

"message": "Integrate the embedding projector backend into TensorBoard.

* Introduce a simple plugin architecture for plugins to add their HTTP handlers and data to TensorBoard. Each plugin implements a simple interface defined in base_plugin.py. Each plugin P exports its own API methods to tf.tensorboard.plugins.P

* The goal of this plugin system is minimal coupling between tensorboard and plugins so we can remove tensorboard/plugins/... later and replace it with the new plugin architecture - only 10 lines of code added to tensorboard/backend/handler.py will need to be removed.

* Add and register the embedding projector under the name `projector`. Also export tf.contrib.tensorboard.plugins.projector.visualize_embeddings(summary_writer
column3:
config) to the tensorflow API.

* The embedding projector writes its own data in a separate file but in the same logdir as the summary writer.

"message": "Fix a bug in TensorBoard where ctrl+c does not shut it down after it serves its first HTTP request.

The problem was that socketserver.ThreadingMixIn was improperly configured to run its threads as daemons (so that it did not do so).

See https://docs.python.org/2/library/socketserver.html for more details.

- passed opensource_build
- passed unit tests

"message": "Change TensorBoard categorization logic to use "directory name" instead of "root name" for constructing categories.

E.g the tags:
"foo/bar/zod/1"
"foo/bar/zod/2"
"foo/bar/zoink/1"
"foo/bar/zoink/2"
"foo/bar/zzz"

Will now create categories "foo/bar/zod" and "foo/bar/zoink" and "foo/bar/zzz" rather than a single category called "foo".

This will make the new image dashboard (which uses categorizer logic) much better organized.

"message": "Use HTTP/1.1 for TensorBoard

This change causes less network and GIL thrash.

Previously
column3: a separate TCP connection and non-pooled thread had to be\ncreated for each and every request. By using HTTP/1.1
column4:
each connection
and thread can serve >1 requests.

This change might not necessarily cause elements on the page to render
more quickly due to the way browsers limit simultaneous connections per
hostname.

The following is Chrome network inspector for TensorBoard on localhost:

Before: http://i.imgur.com/tjLJWGv.png (refresh of images page)
        http://i.imgur.com/ushQpCg.png (each fetch from localhost)
After:  http://i.imgur.com/B1nZXX2.png (refresh of images page)
        http://i.imgur.com/6ile1Ge.png (each fetch from localhost)
Change: 130325620"

"message": "Expose the timestamp of the first event in any given run.

This can be used to provide an ordering on runs that remains the same even as
new runs are added (unlike sorting the run names alphabetically).

We always load the first event whenever we add a run to a multiplexer because
FirstEventTimestamp() and Reload() both grab the same mutex. Since the first
event is just a version specifier

"message": "For the tensorboard graph visualizer
column3:
fade out and cross-hatch nodes and edges that don't have stats when viewing stats for a run.

Other minor tweaks:
- Adds a rect color legend in the graph controls
- Fades out nodes in the node info panel

Note: we use !important for a lot of these overridden CSS values so we don't have to make the javascript more complex. We simple toggle the .faded or .faded-type class on parents
column8: etc on children. As much as I hate !important
column9:
this was much simpler than scattering rendering logic for faded nodes all over the place. This also gives us the flexibility to not re-render the entire graph for stats changing if we decide to do that.

This change also modifies the graph loader _readAndParseMetadata observer such that
this method is only called when the selected metadata tag changes
column11: or the metadata tag changed we were notified
column12: and in no deterministic order. This means the parse metadata method is only called when the dropdown for session runs is interacted with.\nChange: 122840662"

column3: trim lines as we parse them. When copying files on\nwindows machines

column2: "message": "Fix a flakey TensorBoard test
column3: by not depending on precise async behavior from Polymer.\nChange: 122471926"

column2: "message": "Have TensorBoard clearly display NaN data points.\n\nBefore this change
column3: TensorBoard doesn't guarantee any display for NaNs
column4:
and the presence of NaNs
could cause other pieces (like the final bullet-point display) to break.

After this change
column5: TensorBoard draws a small triangle where there are NaNs. The triangle has a horizontal position that corresponds to the NaN's x position
column6: and the y position in general is the same as the y position for the last valid data point in that series (or the first valid data point if the series started with NaNs
column7: or 0 if there were no valid data points).\nI chose this approach rather than e.g. putting the triangles all on the bottom in the hopes that if multiple series are NaN
column8: they would not all overlap and be invisible.\n\nThere is room for improvement
column9: e.g. changing the symbol from a triangle to something that more clearly conveys the idea that there was a NaN.\nWe can draw any svg path we want there...\nChange: 122468486"

"message": "Filter graph on server-side before serving it to the client.

Updated the HTTP endpoint (and the doc) so the user can control filtering using the query parameters `limit_attr_size` and `large_attrs_key`.

For now
column3: the filtering includes removal of values of large attributes (size > 1KB). This significantly reduces the size of graphs that have embedded tensor values in them. For instance
column4:
a graph shared by our users with embedded values is reduced from 94MB to 290 KB.
The values for the filtered-out attributes show up in the info card in the graph view as "Too large to show...".

The filtering doesn't add significant computation cost. On a graph of 30K nodes (very large by standards)
column5:
the filtering added 0.4 seconds.

Added also test when the server serves the graph.
Change: 116168623"

"message": "Swap TensorBoard local build from \"tsd\" to \"typings\".\nReason: tsd is deprecated (https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/tsd/issues/269) and typings is the new standard. Also
column3: tsd was behaving badly - running `tsd install` on a clean client was causing it to incorrectly depend on typing files from node_modules
column4: which resulted in a broken build. This issue does not exist with typings.\n\nFor convenience
column5: and since typings is really fast when all deps are up-to-date
column6: I made it a part of the standard gulp task. `npm install` so you have all the deps
column7: and running `gulp` will keep the typing files synchronized - there no longer is a separate step for downloading them.\n\nThe logical next step is to do the same for bower. I did wire that up
column8: but I will not connect it to the gulp task until after the big bower dependency upgrade CL is through. If I add it right now
column9: it will fail on unresolved dependency conflicts and make everyone sad.\nChange: 115370585"

"message": "Add tensorboard/lib/nanite
column3: a simple system for storing data and creating Polymer data bindings in a typesafe fashion.\n\nNanite exposes a single class
column5: which you can think of as a reified Polymer data binding. The store can bind out to a Polymer object (equivalent to [[downwardBinding]]) or bind up from a Polymer object (like {{oneWayAutomaticBinding}}). Unlike Polymer data bindings
column6: there is a typesafe way to call these methods. Also
column7:
having the state accessibly stored in these objects will make it easier to serialize and deserialize the application state.

Nanite also exposes some methods for transforming stores into other stores in a functional fashion.

You can think of this as a very small system for FRP that is compatible with Typescript and Polymer.

Nanite is thoroughly tested.

N.B. I already have a version of the event dashboard that was refactored to use Nanite
column8: so this definitely can work for our needs without too much effort :)\nChange: 114149110"

"message": "Refactor how TensorBoard url overwriting works.

Currently TensorBoard urls are changed by modifying a global variable (TF.Urls).
This creates racyness where we need to ensure that that global variable changes before the TensorBoard instantiates.

It also makes it impossible e.g. to have multiple TensorBoards on the same page using different url schemes.

This CL changes TensorBoard so it takes in a "router" object which specifies what the routes are.

It also adds a tf-tensorboard-demo component which is just like a TensorBoard
column3: except it has a \"dataDir\" property that determines where to look for demo data.\nChange: 111558450"

column2:
"message": "TensorFlow: upstream changes to git

Change 109195845
	Fix TensorFlow for build against Bazel 0.1.2rc2

	Two things are currently broken with TensorFlow and Bazel 0.1.2:
	  - Bazel now use sandboxing by default on Linux and have fixed it for cc_* rules.
	    Undeclared headers are not mounted in the sandbox which make several cc_* rules
	    fails.
	  - Bazel now enforce strict header checking and some target were missing
	    headers even though the headers were mounted in the sandbox. This change
	    adds a "strict_headers" target that globs every headers of the core
	    library and add it to the `tf_cc_tests` targets.

	the input to the output.

Change:
	Speed up for models that use the same variable multiple times in the case
	where variables must be copied across devices:
	- Have Variables wrap the Variable op in an Identity op when converted to Tensor.
	  This avoids multiple copies across devices if a variable is used multiple time
	  in a computation.
	- Add Variable.mutable() to return the non-wrapped Variable op for used when
	  assigning new values.
	- Add an as_ref parameter to convert_to_tensor() to allow code to specify
	  if they plan to assign a new value to the result of the conversion.  Make Variable
	  return the result of Variable.mutable() when as_ref is True.
	- Make all ops that assign values to variables pass as_ref=True when converting
	  their arguments.
